<FIRST>u a AM-LiverTransplant 3rdLd-Writethru a0413 11-28 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liver Transplant, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0413,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Surgeons Complete Nation's First Living-Donor Liver Transplant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to restore dropped words; picks up 4th graf
pvs: `Broelsch said ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1, LaserColor CX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors implanted part of a woman's liver in her
21-month-old daughter Monday and predicted the nation's first
living-donor liver transplant would be a success.
   ``We're quite confident that this organ will work,'' said Dr.
Christoph Broelsch, who led the surgical team in the 14-hour
operation at University of Chicago Medical Center.
   Teresa Smith and her daughter, Alyssa, were in critical
condition in intensive care and doing well, officials said. Alyssa
came out of surgery about 9:10 p.m., about five hours after her
mother's operation ended.
   Broelsch said doctors would get some indication over the next 24
hours on how the liver is functioning.
   In three to five days they will know if the surgical wounds are
healing properly, and in a week they should get an indication of
whether the liver segment is being rejected by the body.
   The liver was already starting to work, producing bile, as
doctors were finishing the operation, Broelsch said.
   ``She's in as good a shape as any child we see'' at this stage
after a transplant, he said.
   The surgery is the first liver transplant from a living donor in
this country, doctors at the hospital said.
   Broelsch said the most difficult moment came when Mrs. Smith's
spleen was damaged during her surgery and doctors had to remove it.
   ``We didn't expect that at all, but we had it under control in
two or three minutes,'' Broelsch said. ``In no way at any point was
the mother's life in danger.''
   The surgery was the first liver transplant from a living donor
in this country, according to doctors at the university hospital.
   Alyssa went through a critical period of about a half-hour
without a liver very well before the segment was sutured into place
shortly before 6 p.m., Ernst said.
   Doctors then had to flush preserving fluid out of the organ
segment. They planned to make sure it was beginning to work
properly before reconnecting blood vessels and bile ducts, Ernst
said.
   Mrs. Smith was out of surgery at 4 p.m., more than seven hours
after entering surgery. She was listed in critical condition in an
intensive care unit, but is expected to be fine, the spokesman said.
   ``She's fine, a little hurting, she has some pain,'' said her
husband, John L. Smith, who visited her after the surgery.
   People can live without their spleens, although it may make them
more susceptible to infection, Ernst said.
   If successful, the operation could provide a solution to a
severe shortage of organs for children who need transplants, said
doctors at the hospital.
   More than 700 babies a year in the United States need liver
transplants, and as many as half die for lack of a donor.
   Alyssa suffers from an often-fatal liver disorder called biliary
atresia, the leading cause for liver transplants involving children.
   She had been waiting more than a year for a cadaver liver
transplant when the Smiths heard about the hospital's plans for an
experimental living-donor program in August. Liver transplants from
living donors have been performed only three times _ in Brazil,
Australia and Japan. One child has died.
   Mrs. Smith went into surgery at 7:35 a.m. to begin the operation
in which the left lobe of her liver _ about one-third of the organ
_ would be transplanted in her daughter.
   ``She was as eager to get started as she was a month ago when we
first proposed this to her,'' said hospital spokeswoman Mary
Fetsch. ``She has not displayed any signs of doubt or hesitation.''
   Broelsch led the surgical team in the two-phase operation. About
3{ hours into the mother's operation, doctors prepared Alyssa for
the transplant.
   Monday's surgery was complicated by the need to keep the removed
portion of the liver intact, he said. But he noted the hospital's
doctors had been transplanting portions of cadaver livers into
children since 1984, ``with better than 80 percent success.''
   A medical ethicist said using a parent as donor raises some
serious questions.
   Given the ``extraordinary pressure that any parent would feel
... to do anything possible to help the life of their child, would
the emotional attachment ... interfere with being able ... to fully
understand the benefits and risks of the operation?'' researcher
Reinhard Priester said Monday from the University of Minnesota's
Center for Biomedical Ethics.
   Mrs. Smith had no doubts.
   ``Once you've given someone a big piece of your heart, it's easy
to throw in a little bit of liver,'' said the 29-year-old
schoolteacher from Schertz, Texas, before Monday's surgery.
   A medical ethics team worked closely with doctors in preparing
the family for the operation, Ernst said.
   ``In a way I kind of fear for her, but I'm confident everything
will turn out OK,'' said John Smith, an assistant shipping
supervisor who was at the hospital with the couple's 3-year-old
son, Richard.
   The Chicago hospital has spent more than a year planning the
program, and last August authorized 20 such operations to determine
whether the procedure is viable.
   Until now, the only regularly performed living-donor transplants
have involved kidneys and some pancreas segments.
</TEXT>
