<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites SUB a0420 11-28 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites, SUB, a0420,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf of 2nd item to CORRECT spelling of Nancy Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editors of a Nevada cookbook claim it's
down-home, but some of the recipes came from the White House _
although the Bushes' Mexican Mound isn't exactly the haute cuisine
one expects at state dinners.
   The Country Cookbook by the Nevada Farm Bureau Women's Committee
consists mainly of Nevadans' recipes dating from the 1880s, and
includes instructions from an Indian chief on how to roast a
groundhog.
   But editor Chris Shuey solicited President Bush, former
President Reagan and their wives for some of their favorites to
give the publication national flavor.
   Mrs. Shuey, who lives on an alfalfa farm in central Nevada, said
she hadn't tried the recipes the First Families sent.
   ``We didn't have a test kitchen,'' she explained. ``I hope
they're good, but I probably shouldn't say that.''
   The Bushes also submitted recipes for American clam chowder,
vegetable salad and apple crisp in orange juice.
   Their Mexican Mound dish has corn chips, ground meat, taco
seasoning, cheese, onions, olives, tomato, sour cream, lettuce and
avocado dip piled high on plates and served buffet style, first
lady Barbara Bush said.
   Nancy Reagan's recipes included chocolate brownies, piccata of
veal and cool cucumber soup. Reagan sent a recipe for a cold
Spanish soup.
   Chief Frank Temoke Sr., of Elko County, submitted the method for
roasting squirrel and groundhog. It calls for dressing the animal
and pinning it together to avoid getting ashes in the opening.
   ``Make a hot fire and singe all the hair off so that it's
smooth,'' the chief explained. ``Dig a hole in the coals with a
shovel and put the squirrels in; leave this way for about two
hours. To eat, peel off the skin.''
</TEXT>
