<FIRST>r w PM-ChicagoControllers     11-28 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Controllers,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Lawmakers Hit Justice Department Over Controller Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers who say they uncovered fraud during
an investigation of the firings of Chicago air traffic controllers
are criticizing the Justice Department for shifting the case to
another agency.
   ``It is your department's responsibility to investigate and
prosecute perjury or obstruction of justice violations _ not the
responsibility of the inspector general,'' Rep. Glenn M. Anderson,
D-Calif., said in a letter to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh.
   Anderson, chairman of the House Public Works and Transportation
Committee, questioned the decision to ``buck the matter'' to the
Transportation Department's inspector general.
   In September, the committee's investigations panel released a
report that said aviation officials lied and created evidence to
support the firings of hundreds of Chicago controllers during the
1981 strike.
   A government appeals board, citing attendance records, upheld
the firings in 1985.
   However, the investigations subcommittee said FAA officials had
set up a ``war room'' at the Chicago Air Route Traffic Control
Center in Aurora, Ill., and created records to replace original,
shoddy documents.
   ``The committee feels very strongly that witnesses who give
perjured testimony during a congressional investigative hearing
should be prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law,'' Anderson
told Thornburgh. ``It would be astonishing to learn that the
Justice Department does not share this belief.''
   A Justice Department official said Monday that the case was not
closed.
   ``They want more information to see which way to go,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``There are a lot of
options.''
   During their probe, lawmakers were not judging the merits of the
nationwide strike, which left about 450 Chicago controllers out of
work. Rather, they said they were concerned with the actions of FAA
officials who were defending the firings before the Merit Systems
Protection Board.
   The letter also was signed by Reps. Guy V. Molinari of New York,
the senior Republican on the investigations and oversight
subcommittee, and James L. Oberstar, D-Minn., who led the
investigation.
</TEXT>
