<FIRST>r w PM-RadiationRecords     11-28 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radiation Records,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Urged to Release Secret Records on Atomic Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent researchers should be given access
to secret government files on worker exposure to radiation at
federal nuclear weapons plants, says an advisory panel to Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins.
   The recommendation, if accepted by Watkins, would mean a
historic shift in the government's stance on public access to
medical and radiation exposure records dating to the start of
American nuclear weapons production in the 1940s.
   The advisory panel of nine health and legal experts said in an
interim report to Watkins late last week that dropping the Energy
Department's long-standing ban on public access to the data would
help restore the department's sagging credibility.
   Watkins on Monday welcomed the report but did not say whether he
would accept the recommendation, which was among several aimed at
improving the department's health research activities.
   ``This is a highly qualified group of professionals,'' Watkins
said in a prepared statement. ``Their ideas are very much in line
with my own impressions of what we need to do to strengthen this
important research activity.''
   Watkins' statement said he instructed the department's acting
energy research chief, James Decker, to prepare a plan by Dec. 15
``for making those changes that can be implemented'' on the basis
of the advisory group's recommendations.
   Watkins assembled the group in August to advise him on ways to
restructure the department's health research program. Some members
of Congress are pressing for legislation to move the research
responsibility to another government agency, such as the Department
of Health and Human Services.
   The department for years has fought a Pennsylvania group, the
Three Mile Island Public Health Fund, over access to the medical
records, which are the most detailed collection of data on health
effects of long-term exposure to radiation.
   Daniel Berger, an attorney for the Pennsylvania group, said
Monday ``we're cautiously optimistic'' that Watkins will heed the
advisory panel's recommendation, which was based on more than two
months of study of the department's health research programs.
   ``It could be a major milestone in our quest for the data,''
Berger said in a telephone interview.
   The information includes death records and the historical
exposure to radiation of about 300,000 people who have worked at
the government's nuclear weapons plants and laboratories in 12
states over the past four decades.
   Government researchers under contract to the Energy Department
have published numerous studies based on the disputed data, but
independent researchers, without access to the material, have been
unable to form their own interpretations.
   The advisory group's report said Watkins should ``adopt a policy
of maximum possible openness with regard to the release of data to
the Three Mile Island Fund research workers.''
   The group said only two limitations should be placed on access
to the data by independent researchers: none of the workers'
identities should be disclosed, and the department should be
allowed to withhold files being analyzed for studies planned for
publication _ until they actually are published.
   The advisory group also recommended Watkins begin immediately to
secure agreements with states to provide for the release of death
certificates so that information derived from the certificates can
be made available to independent researchers.
   The group said it had come to no conclusion on whether the
department's epidemiological research activities should be
transferred to another government agency.
   The advisory panel is due to submit a final report to Watkins
next year.
</TEXT>
