<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     11-28 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Spending Reduced by $1 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture spending is being reduced by more
than $1 billion during this fiscal year under an agreement reached
by Congress to help lower the federal deficit.
   After weeks of negotiations, the House and Senate agreed to the
savings last week, just before recessing for the year. The fiscal
year began Oct. 1.
   The cuts are part of the massive bill, known as budget
reconciliation, that includes $14.7 billion in savings from all
departments of the federal government.
   ``The agriculture measures included in the reconciliation
conference report were the ones that we feel will achieve the
required savings in a fair and equitable manner with minimal
disruption of farm program objectives,'' said Rep. Kika de la
Garza, D-Texas, chairman of the House Agriculture Committee.
   A $235 million savings comes from reducing deficiency payments
for 1990 crops by:
   _2.33 cents per bushel for wheat.
   _2.33 cents per bushel for corn.
   _0.515 cents per pound for upland cotton.
   _5.15 cents per hundredweight for rice.
   Another $54 million is expected to be saved through repayment of
advance deficiency payments for 1988 crops of wheat, feed grain,
upland cotton and rice.
   However, those repayments would not be required before Dec. 31
if the producer suffered 1988 or 1989 crop losses because of a
natural disaster, or before July 31, 1990, for the portion of the
crop covered by the 1988 Disaster Assistance Act.
   About $116 million will be saved from the soybean, sunflower and
safflower planting program and the feed grain limitations program.
   That section requires the agriculture secretary to offer farmers
the chance to plant soybeans, sunflowers or safflowers during 1990,
similar to the provisions of the 1988 disaster aid act.
   Other savings include:
   _$143 million through reduction of Export Enhancement Program
and Targeted Export Assistance payments.
   _$500 million through purchases of Financial Assistance Corp.
stock by Farm Credit System Institutions.
   _$27 million through adjustments in dairy price support
programs, including setting the purchase price for price support
purposes for butter at no more than $1.10 per pound. It also makes
the 50 cents per hundredweight decrease in milk price supports
discretionary for 1990.
   _$25 million by altering the way the agriculture secretary
allocated butter and non-fat dry milk powder purchases between
April 1 and July 1, 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., wants U.S.
chemical companies to stop selling foreign countries pesticides
that are banned in the United States.
   ``In addition to protecting public health, the export of
dangerous pesticides creates a competitive inequity between foreign
and American farmers and growers,'' Wilson said at a news
conference Monday.
   He said U.S. growers were required to use what often are more
expensive pesticides to meet federal regulations against dangerous
chemicals, while foreign growers can use the less expensive
products that have been banned in the United States.
   Wilson, who is running for governor of California, introduced
federal legislation late last week that would stop U.S. companies
from exporting pesticides banned here.
   A spokeswoman from the Western Growers Association, in Irvine,
Calif., said competition from foreign growers is a big problem for
California farmers and will be a key issue in the gubernatorial
campaign.
   ``We've been letting Sen. Wilson know that we are under extreme
pressure from foreign farmers,'' said Barbara Buck, adding that
California farmers are experiencing ever-increasing costs of doing
business.
   ``Meanwhile, farmers in other countries are able to pay far less
in wages, have cheaper land, get chemicals very cheaply and can use
whatever they want in most cases,'' Buck said.
   ``In the frozen side of the business, there have been a lot of
broccoli, asparagus and cauliflower growers who have gone out of
business because they can't compete with the frozen vegetable
production in Mexico.
   ``In 1988, the value of all fresh produce imported to the United
States had risen to $602 million from $379 million in 1980,'' Buck
said, adding that the number of separate food products grew from 27
in 1980 to 40 in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
