<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-USDAYearbook     11-28 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USDA Yearbook,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Yearbook Designed to Aid Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department's new yearbook is
designed to help farmers be better managers.
   The 336-page book, ``Farm Management: How to Achieve Your
Business Goals,'' offers practical information from university and
extension experts, says editor Deborah Takiff Smith.
   More than 80 authors contributed to this year's edition,
focusing on individual farmers making decisions on the use of land,
labor, capital and managerial skills. A different topic is selected
each year.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, a Nebraska farmer, said
management is one of the reasons U.S. agriculture is so competitive
on the international market.
   ``Only talented managers can succeed in today's tough business
environment, where our farmers must face not only the competition
of their neighbors, but often that of the government treasuries of
other nations,'' Yeutter said in the foreward of the book released
Monday.
   The USDA yearbook officially began in 1894, although annual
volumes of reports were issued in the 1840s, when federal
agriculture was under the Commissioner of Patents.
   Annual reports were continued after the USDA was created in
1862, according to agency historical accounts. Copies of the
reports were distributed by Congress, a tradition that continues
today.
   Smith said 211,800 copies of the 1989 yearbook are being
provided to Congress, with each senator getting about 350 books and
each member of the House about 400.
   Constituents may obtain free copies of the yearbook from
senators and members of Congress, she said. The books may be
ordered for $10 from: Superintendent of Documents, Washington, D.C.
20402. The yearbooks also will be sold at government bookstores in
many cities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
