<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bogota Paper Gets Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. publishers are giving a Bogota newspaper
that was bombed because of its coverage of Colombia's drug trade a
helping hand in its effort to prevent bankruptcy.
   Thomas C. Fichter of the American Newspaper Publishers
Association, one of two trade associations coordinating a drive to
raise funds for El Espectador, said Monday the newspaper should
receive the initial loan installment this week.
   El Espectador has said it needs $2.5 million to continue
publishing; Fichter said $1.6 million had been contributed or
pledged to aid the newspaper.
   The president of El Espectador, Luis Cano, toured the United
States in October seeking support from news organizations. A car
bomb that exploded near the newspaper's offices Sept. 2 did $2.5
million worth of damage, he said.
   Cano's younger brother, Guillermo Cano, publisher of the paper,
was killed by drug traffickers in 1986. Two newspaper employees in
Medellin, where the drug cartel has its headquarters, were killed
in October.
   Fichter said ANPA is working with the Inter-American Press
Association of Miami in coordinating the fund-raising campaign. He
said money or pledges had been received from about 50 donors in the
United States, Canada, Europe and Asia.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Treasury Secretary To Undergo Hip Surgery</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F.Brady, who has
been plagued in recent months by arthritis, will undergo elective
surgery Dec. 14 to replace his right hip.
   The Treasury Department said Monday that the surgery, to be
performed in an undisclosed location, has been planned for a long
time. Recovery should take three to six weeks.
   Deputy Secretary John Robson will serve as acting secretary,
Brady said in a memo to top department officials.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Committee Switches Counsel</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Ethics Committee is changing its
outside counsel in a case involving Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.,
and allegations of wrongdoing related to the Department of Housing
and Urban Development.
   The committee said Monday that it had hired former federal
prosecutor Henry Schuelke to replace Robert Bennett.
   Bennett, who will continue to handle two other cases for the
committee, told the panel last week that his law firm's diverse
practice could lead to an appearance of conflict of interest in the
D'Amato case. Details of how such an appearance could arise were
not given.
   Mark Green, D'Amato's 1986 election opponent, filed a complaint
with the committee accusing him of breaking Senate rules in the
Reagan-era problems at HUD. D'Amato has denied any improprieties.
   Schuelke will help the committee determine whether to proceed
with a formal investigation.
   Bennett is still the committee's outside counsel conducting a
similar review in a case involving five senators who interceded
with banking regulators on behalf of a contributor whose savings
and loan was collapsing.
   Bennett also is the committee's counsel in an investigation of a
book deal by Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn.
