<FIRST>r w PM-Jesuits-Witness     11-28 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jesuits-Witness,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness to Jesuits' Murders Under Protection in Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says a cleaning woman
who witnessed the massacre of six Jesuit priests in El Salvador is
in protective FBI custody in Miami.
   Lucia Barrera Cerna, 40, will be interviewed by a Salvadoran law
enforcement official investigating the Nov. 16 massacre, said
agency spokesman David Runkel.
   FBI spokesman Milt Ahlerich confirmed that the woman is
considered a witness, but declined to discuss what the woman has
told investigators or the extent of her knowledge of the killings.
   Runkel said the woman was admitted to the United States last
week under a special parole immigrant status. He confirmed
published reports over the weekend that the witness was in
protective FBI custody in Miami.
   Mrs. Cerna was flown to Miami from San Salvador with the
assistance of the Spanish and French governments, according to a
U.S. official who spoke condition of anonymity.
   According to unidentified officials quoted by the Miami Herald,
Mrs. Cerna saw 30 to 40 men wearing Salvadoran military uniforms
carry out the massacre.
   Bernard Kouchner, the French minister for humanitarian affairs,
said he escorted the witness, her husband and daughter on a French
plane to the United States.
   Kouchner, who was in San Salvador to attend the funerals of the
slain Jesuits, helped arrange the woman's passage to Miami after
learning she was in the Spanish Embassy.
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani approved the relocation,
Kouchner said.
</TEXT>
