<FIRST>r w PM-Summit-Trident     11-28 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Trident,230</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government sources say the Bush administration
may postpone a scheduled test of the troubled Trident 2
submarine-launched ballistic missile on the eve of the Malta summit.
   The launch was to be Friday off the coast of Florida, sources
speaking on condition of anonymity said Monday.
   President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will
meet off the isle of Malta in the Mediterranean Sea on Saturday and
Sunday.
   ``Discussions are going as to whether to delay it until after
Malta'' so as not to spoil the atmosphere of the first summit of
the Bush administration, said one source.
   ``The date was set long before the summit'' was announced, the
source said.
   The Navy refused to confirm or deny plans to test the Trident 2
in keeping with its policy of announcing such launches 24 hours in
advance.
   The Trident 2 failed its most recent sea test, Aug. 15, passed
the one before that, on Aug. 2, and spectacularly failed its first
submarine-launched flight, March 21, cartwheeling out of control
four seconds after it was fired from the submarine the USS
Tennessee.
   It passed 16 of its first 19 tests, fired from land.
   The Trident 2, at $26.5 million per copy, is designed to replace
the Trident 1 submarine-launched ballistic missiles. Each of the
44-foot-long, three-stage Trident 2's can deliver three to 12
warheads to individual targets up to 6,000 miles away.
