<FIRST>u a AM-Obit-Eliana 1stLd-Writethru a0785 11-28 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Eliana, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0785,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Patient Who Won Landmark School Case Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS next-to-last graf to include that she got AIDS thru transfusion
of tainted blood.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eliana Martinez, an 8-year-old AIDS-afflicted
girl who won a landmark 2{-year court battle to attend public
school, died Monday, a spokesman said.
   Eliana died in her bed at home at about 5:30 p.m., said Dan
McClowry, Eliana's former speech therapist and a friend of the
family.
   ``She had been in and out of a coma for the last three days,''
he said. ``She had some good moments and some bad moments. Today,
she smiled at us and last night she even laughed.''
   Eliana's adoptive mother, Rosa Martinez, and a few family
friends had been sitting up with the child for the last few days
knowing death was near, McClowry said.
   Eliana's body would be taken Tuesday morning to the National
Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md., for an autopsy, McClowry
said. Funeral services were tentatively scheduled for early next
week in Tampa, he said.
   Doctors took Eliana off the experimental AIDS-fighting drug DDI
on Oct. 4, saying it wasn't protecting her from life-threatening,
AIDS-related infections. Eliana had been given AZT, the only
federally aproved AIDS drug, for two years and was switched when it
was no longer helping her.
   In April, Eliana went to class for the first time after her
mother won a court battle with the Hillsborough County School Board
to get Eliana enrolled in a school for ``special needs'' children.
   Education officials wanted the mentally disabled child kept on
homebound instruction until she was potty-trained and learned to
stop sucking her fingers. They feared she posed a risk of
transmitting acquired immune deficiency syndrome to classmates and
teachers.
   U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich ruled Eliana could
attend school if she stayed inside a specially-built glass booth.
   Mrs. Martinez said she wouldn't send her daughter to class to
sit in a cage. The child needed to be with other children to help
her develop, she said. Her attorney Steve Hanlon appealed, and won.
Eliana went to school without the glass enclosure.
   Psychologists and pediatricians who care for AIDS children said
the isolation booth setting would cause stress and be harmful to
the girl's already weakened immune system.
   Mrs. Martinez, a 37-year-old licensed practical nurse, adopted
Eliana in her native Puetro Rico. She responded to a radio appeal
for a sickly, homeless child living at a hospital. Eliana, who got
AIDS from a transfusion of tainted blood, was 11-months-old and
weighed only about 10 pounds when Mrs. Martinez took her home.
   At first doctors thought the baby might have cerebral palsy. It
wasn't until the spring of 1985 that Mrs. Martinez and her husband,
Jose, learned Eliana had AIDS-related complex or ARC, a precursor
to AIDS.
</TEXT>
