<FIRST>u a AM-Bus-TrainWreck 1stLd-Writethru a0408 11-28 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus-Train Wreck, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0408,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede: SAN FRANCISCO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bus and Commuter Train Collide, Two ABC Execs Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES through with victims ABC executives, identify bus driver,
no train passengers injured, train service restored.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A charter bus carrying ABC
employees to Monday night's National Football League game was
struck by a train, killing two people and injuring about 25, police
said.
   The bus had stopped between grade crossing gates for an unknown
reason during the evening rush hour, police said.
   One victim was an ABC Sports executive from New York and the
other a network sales executive based in Los Angeles, said Bob
Wheeler, ABC's manager of sports information. They were in town for
the broadcast of Monday Night Football, which was celebrating its
20th anniversary.
   The victims' names were withheld until relatives were notified.
   The bus was the third in a convoy of four vehicles full of ABC
employees and clients who had taken a cruise on San Francisco Bay
and were headed to Candlestick Park to watch the San Francisco
49ers play the New York Giants, Wheeler said.
   Train No. 58 was traveling at 60 mph when the collision
occurred, said Bob Hoppe, a spokesman for Southern Pacific
Railroad, which operates the line.
   The bus apparently stopped on the tracks behind a double
tractor-trailer truck shortly before the 5 p.m. crash about five
miles south of San Francisco, said police officer Greg Heard. The
CalTrain commuter train did not derail.
   ``The gates came down and the bus was stuck,'' said Heard. ``The
driver tried to get around and honked his horn several times to
clear traffic.''
   As many as 25 people were injured, Heard said. The two people
who died were ``thrown into the track area,'' he said.
   No one on the train were injured, according to spokesmen for
Southern Pacific.
   Hornblower Yachts, a San Francisco yachting service, chartered
the bus, the service said in a statement. The bus was owned by San
Francisco-based International Coach, said Daniel Coles, operations
manager for the bus company.
   The driver, Paul Cang, 33, of Foster City, was treated for
multiple injuries at Peninsula Hospital in Burlingame, hospital
spokeswoman Traci Ward said.
   The CalTrain commute service from San Francisco to San Jose is
offered by Southern Pacific through contract with the state
Department of Transportation.
   Passengers remained on the train and service was halted in both
directions for 90 minutes.
</TEXT>
