<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-28 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Market Again Hits Record High, Dollar Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange overcame
morning setbacks and reached a record-high closing Tuesday, while
the dollar edged up against the yen.
   The dollar ended trading at 143.65 yen, up 0.30 yen from
Monday's close of 143.35 yen. It opened lower at 143.33 yen and
gradually rose while ranging between 143.33 yen and 143.70 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 103.77 points, or 0.28
percent, ending at 36,985.30, yet another high. The index just
reached a record high the previous day, when it gained 397.06
points to a 36,881.53-point close.
   Securities dealers said the index, which fell marginally in the
morning, recovered in the afternoon when institutional investors
began buying as they were reassured by stability on the exchange
market and short term interst rates.
   Trading was hectic with an estimated 1.5 billion shares changing
hands on the market's first section.
   In currency dealings, the dollar, which was lower against the
yen in early trading, rose back as speculative investors bought the
U.S. currency, dealers said.
   The West German mark remained strong against other major
currency following recent moves toward democracy and economic
reform in Eastern Europe, they said.
   The Bank of Japan's governor, Satoshi Sumita, said Tuesday that
the central bank will conduct concerted intervention if the market
continues to fluctuate excessively, Kyodo News Service reported.
</TEXT>
