<FIRST>r i PM-Honecker     11-28 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honecker,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker: `Old, Broken' Man, Visited Only By Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erich Honecker, the Communist who ruled East
Germany for nearly two decades until his ouster last month, is a
``broken man'' whose only solace is visiting with his grandson, his
bodyguard says.
   ``What's he got to live for? Honecker is so sick that he cannot
show himself in public,'' the aide, Gen. Guenter Wolf, told Western
reporters outside Honecker's home in the former party elite's
exclusive Wandlitz compound.
   ``He is a broken man. For him the world has fallen apart,'' Wolf
told the reporters who were allowed to visit the wooded residential
compound just north of East Berlin for the first time Monday.
   The 77-year-old hard-line leader was ousted Oct. 18 following an
exodus of East Germans to the West and huge demonstrations for
democratic reform.
   He was replaced by his protege, Egon Krenz, who promptly
promised reform and has tried to distance himself from his
hard-line mentor.
   A party commission is conducting an investigation of Honecker
that could result in his ouster from the party. A special
parliamentary commission is also investigating charges of abuse of
power by his 18-year administration.
   Meanwhile, Honecker sits inside the two-story brown house,
waiting for a visit from his grandson, Wolf said.
   Reporters caught a glimpse of Honecker on the upper floor of the
house, apparently talking to a visitor and looking through some
papers at a table. No contact was possible.
   A young woman with a child in her arms could be seen in the
background. When she saw reporters outside, she pulled the shades
down.
   ``Honecker's daughter from Berlin takes care of him. And his
young grandson is everything to him,'' Wolf said. He said Honecker
received hardly any visits except from his family but offered no
further details about them.
   The house has no nameplate, only the number 11 on the short
sandstone wall around the building. It is one of 23 houses in the
compound _ once the secret pride of the country's Communist elite.
   Wolf assured reporters that Honecker's house contained ``no
Italian marble, no silk wallpaper and no sauna.'' It looked modest
by Western standards, but more than any ordinary East German could
hope for in a lifetime.
   A beige East German-made Wartburg was parked outside the house.
Wolf said it belonged to Honecker's wife, Margot, who lost her post
as education minister shortly after her husband's ouster.
   A week ago Krenz, understanding the resentment struggling East
Germans felt toward leaders who lived in luxury, moved to a modest
house in East Berlin and said other leading party officials would
follow.
   Wolf said Honecker and his wife want to move from Wandlitz
before the end of the year.
   Several other ousted Politburo members also still live in
Wandlitz, including former economic adviser Guenter Mittag and
former propaganda chief Kurt Hager.
   Wandlitz residents have been told to stop using French-made
Citroens and to use East German Wartburgs or Soviet-made Ladas when
going to East Berlin.
   Kiwis and pineapples have been removed from the exclusive shop
in the compound and replaced by products that can be found in
ordinary stores.
   A sales clerk, Jutta Wittig, said Honecker's preferred wine was
a dry white, Mueller-Thurgau from Miessen. She said the Honeckers
always ate healthy food, with lots of curds.
   She said Honecker had ``good taste,'' always ordering dark blue
suits with white shirts.
   Krenz's new leadership has blamed Honecker and Mittag for
plunging the country into the crisis and Mittag has been kicked out
of the party. Krenz, however, has said that Honecker is too ill to
be interrogated by the party commission.
   Honecker underwent two gall-bladder operations this summer and
his wife has also told East German media that he still has not
recovered fully.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
