<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-28 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Stocks Hit New High, Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index climbed to a
new high for the fifth consecutive trading day today, while the
dollar rose against the yen after a four-day decline.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell in morning trading but
ended up gaining 103.77 points, or 0.28 percent, closing at
36,985.30. The previous record high of 36,881.53 was set Monday,
when the index gained 397.06 points.
   After initial profit-taking sales, investors started buying a
wide variety of issues in the afternoon, dealers said.
   ``Institutional investors, who had remained on the sidelines for
a long time holding cash in their hands, finally started buying
issues because they thought they were going to miss an opportunity
to make money as share prices rise higher and higher,'' said a
Nomura Securities dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   An estimated 1.5 billion shares changed hands on the first
section, up from 1 billion the previous day. Among gainers were
real estate and trading house issues.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 143.65 yen, up 0.30
yen from Monday's 143.35-yen finish. The currency opened at 143.33
yen, its low for the day, and ranged up to 143.70 yen.
   The dollar had lost a total of 1.32 yen over the four previous
trading days.
   Although dollar-yen trading was quiet early today, the dollar
strengthened in the afternoon as speculative and institutional
investors, including trading houses, started buying the U.S.
currency, said Hisashi Matsuda, a trader with Daiwa Bank.
   Many investors who had been selling dollars to buy West German
marks were buying back dollars with yen for technical adjustments.
   ``Whenever there is no market-affecting news, Japanese investors
tend to buy the dollar, and that's basically what happened today,''
Matsuda said.
   ``The West German mark was weakening a little at one point as
market players sold the currency for profit-taking, but it soon
recovered,'' he said.
   Although the market had been expecting the yen's relative rise
along with the mark's recovery, the yen gradually fell, Matsuda
added.
   Market players have been buying the West German mark since a
series of recent democratic and economic reforms began in Eastern
European nations. Investors expect West Germany to benefit from
those reforms.
</TEXT>
