<FIRST>r i PM-India-HinduParty     11-28 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Hindu Party,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fundamentalist Party Biggest Gainer in Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-India-Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fundamentalist Hindu party has
catapulted into a key power-broking position after national
elections, and its leader pledges to end the rule of Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi.
   ``I will see to it that the prime minister falls,'' said Lal
Krishna Advani, head of the Bharatiya Janata Party, as dozens of
supporters flocked to his New Delhi home, draping him with garlands
of marigolds.
   The party registered huge gains in the elections for
Parliament's powerful lower house, winning at least 73 seats. In
the last election it won two.
   Analysts have linked its rise to a revival of Hindu
fundmentalism epitomized by plans to build a new Hindu temple on
the site of a 16th century mosque.
   The temple plans, which were supported by the party, sparked
riots this fall between Hindus and Moslems in which at least 300
people were killed.
   Advani said he opposes violence but added that the government
must stop its ``reverse discrimination'' against Hindus, who make
up 82 percent of India's 880 million people.
   As congratulatory phone calls came in and party activists
munched cakes and sweets Monday, the party chief said he was ready
to unite with other opposition groups to end ``a corrupt dynasty.''
The reference was to the Gandhi-Nehru clan that has occupied the
prime minister's office for all but five years since India won
indepenence in 1947.
   Gandhi's grandfather, Jawaharlal Nehru, was India's first prime
minister. The job later passed to his daughter Indira Gandhi,
mother of the present prime minister.
   Incomplete election results showed that Gandhi's Congress Party
would not win a majority in the 543-seat Lok Sabha, or House of the
People, the lower house of Parliament that chooses the prime
minister.
   But the main opposition group, the National Front, was running
behind Congress.
   The scene was thus set for Advani's party to play the crucial
power-broking role.
   Of all the main parties, Advani's is the most conservative. It
favors development of India's nuclear forces and strict policing of
border areas with Pakistan and Bangladesh.
   It also pushes Hindu rights, advocating the abolition of a
commission set up to protect minorities. In addition, it encourages
privatization. A large percentage of India's industry is state-run.
   Advani, 62, won a Parliament seat in New Delhi. Party colleagues
posted victories throughout the plains of northern India.
   Some political commentators are concerned that the rise of his
party symbolizes a growing split in the Indian political scene.
   But others welcome the inclusion of such elements in Parliament
because, they say, it forces them to compromise and thereby
modifies their fundamentalism.
   But at Advani's house Monday, there was little talk of
compromise.
   ``We are very powerful now,'' the party boss said. ``The people
have spoken.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
