<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     11-28 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunfire, Mortar Blasts Awaken Capital to Renewed Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mortars exploded and gunfire
resounded in northern San Salvador today, awakening capital
residents to renewed fighting between government forces and leftist
rebels.
   It was the first time this week that the fighting appeared to be
anything but brief exchanges between the two sides.
   About 10 flares were dropped by circling helicopters over the
northern neighborhoods of Mejicanos and Ciudad Delgado, and more
than two dozen mortar rounds shattered the pre-dawn silence.
   Because of a dusk-to-dawn curfew, the extent of the combat was
not immediately clear. Assault-rifle and occasional machine-gun
fire was heard, but those exchanges were not heavy or sustained.
   On Nov. 11, guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front launched their biggest offensive of the decade-old
civil war. More than 1,000 people died in 12 days of combat in San
Salvador and several provincial cities.
   The rebels have said that fighting, which turned the capital
into a battleground, was the first phase of a broader operation.
   The rightist government of President Alfredo Cristiani contends
it defeated the insurgent push. But Cristiani also said last week,
``They (the guerrillas) are doing some things that look more like
regrouping than retreating.''
   Despite $3.5 billion in U.S. aid, Salvadoran government forces
have been unable to defeat the rebels. The war has claimed the
lives of at least 71,000 people, mostly civilians.
   Thousands of civilians who lost their lives in the conflict were
slain by right-wing death squads early in the decade.
   This fall, attacks on leftist civilian leaders resumed and, on
Nov. 16, six Jesuit priests were murdered along with their cook and
her teen-age daughter.
   The military was widely blamed for the massacre and a cleaning
woman, Lucia Barrera de Cerna, has sworn she saw the the killers
wearing uniforms.
   Cristiani has promised a full investigation.
   Government and military officials have accused clergy and church
workers of sympathizing with and even supporting the rebels.
   On Sunday, an American church worker, Jennifer Jean Casolo, was
arrested after authorities raided her home and said they found
explosives and 80,000 rounds of ammunition for assault rifles.
   Ms. Casolo, 28, of Thomaston, Conn., was still in the custody of
the National Police on Monday, said Jeff Brown, a U.S. Embassy
spokesman in El Salvador.
   He said she was being questioned and had not been charged as of
late Monday. She works for the Christian Educational Seminar, based
in San Antonio.
   Under the state-of-siege imposed after the rebels launched their
offensive Nov. 11, authorities have up to 15 days to file charges
or release someone instead of the normal 72 hours.
   White House officials say the evidence against Ms. Casolo is
strong, but friends and associates say she was framed as part of
the government's campaign to discredit church workers.
</TEXT>
