<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Hoving     11-28 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Hoving,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Tiffany's Dies at 91</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Hoving, who enforced his standards of
taste in jewelry as head of Tiffany's for 25 years, has died. He
was 91.
   Hoving died Monday at Newport Hospital in Rhode Island, where he
had been a patient for two weeks, according to today's editions of
The New York Times. There was no word on the cause of his death.
   When he bought a controlling share of Tiffany and Co. in 1955,
it was doing $7 million worth of business a year and appeared to be
fading. But by 1980, the store and its five branches were taking in
$100 million.
   Among the breaches of taste Hoving forbade at Tiffany's were
silver plate and diamond rings for men.
   He would not make an exception to his ideas of propriety even
for President Kennedy. In one story told about Hoving, Kennedy
asked him for 32 lucite calendar memos to give to aides who had
worked with him during the Cuban missile crisis.
   But Hoving wouldn't hear of Tiffany's working in plastic, and
the request was changed to silver.
   ``Design what you think is beautiful, and don't worry about
selling it,'' he would tell his designers, like Elsa Perrett or
Jean Schlumberger. ``That's our job.''
   Hoving resigned as chairman in 1980, a year after the company
was bought by Avon Products. It is now publicly owned again and its
stock is listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Hoving was born in Stockholm in 1897 and came to the United
States with his parents in 1903. He earned a bachelor's degree from
Brown University.
   During his career, he worked at R.H. Macy &amp; Company, Montgomery
Ward &amp; Company and Lord &amp; Taylor, the latter as president.
   A private family service was to be held today in Newport.
</TEXT>
