<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-28 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major foreign
currencies except the Canadian dollar and the British pound in
light European trading, dealers said today.
   Gold and silver prices were sharply lower as profit taking
continued in the wake of last week's steep rise, bullion dealers
said.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's rise is only a pause in a
downward trend. They said the U.S. currency is under pressure from
confusion caused by the U.S. Federal Reserve's interest rate policy
and the bullish impact of East European reforms on the West German
mark.
   The pound moved higher after Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
reiterated her determination to remain head of the Conservative
Party.
   Traders said the markets will be watching Wednesday's scheduled
release of preliminary third quarter U.S. gross national product
figures. If the figures reflecting economic growth are lower,
dealers said the Federal Reserve could drop interest rates which
would weaken the dollar.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.30 yen to a closing 143.65 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.7965 West German marks, up from 1.7900
   _1.6060 Swiss francs, up from 1.6050
   _6.1310 French francs, up from 6.1125
   _2.0260 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0203
   _1,324.75 Italian lire, up from 1,321.25
   _1.1667 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1670
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5633 to buy one pound, more expensive for buyers than $1.5605
late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $408.70 a troy ounce,
down from $414.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $410.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $409.10, down from $414 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $8.83 to close at a bid $409.19.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $5.62 a troy ounce, down
from Monday's $5.73.
   END (jb)
</TEXT>
