<FIRST>r a PM-HazelwoodTrial     11-28 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hazelwood Trial,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Explain Why No Blood Test Taken After Exxon Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state official called to the wreck of
the Exxon Valdez said he wasn't prepared to take an immediate blood
alcohol test of Joseph Hazelwood because he was unaware a crime had
been committed.
   The blood test wasn't made until about 10 hours after the
grounding, too late, Hazelwood's defense attorneys claim, to prove
anything about his sobriety when the Exxon Valdez ran on a reef and
caused the nation's most disastrous oil spill.
   The testimony came Monday at a hearing where Hazelwood's lawyers
sought to get charges against him dismissed. In addition to
questioning the sobriety test, the attorneys claim Hazelwood
automatically received immunity from prosecution when he reported
the oil spill.
   Exxon fired Hazelwood soon after the March 24 wreck, which
spilled about 11 million gallons of crude oil in Prince William
Sound. Hazelwood, the tanker captain, was below decks when the
wreck occurred and a subordinate was at the helm.
   Assistant District Attorney Leonard Linton Jr. said discovery of
the huge spill was inevitable.
   Hazelwood, 43, a veteran mariner from Huntington, N.Y., is
scheduled for trial Jan. 22 on charges of reckless endangerment,
operating a vessel while intoxicated and negligent discharge of
oil, all misdemeanors, and three felony counts of criminal mischief.
   He faces a possible maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and
$100,000 in fines.
   Alaska Fish and Wildlife Protection Trooper Michael Fox said he
was called by the Coast Guard to the Exxon Valdez and assumed he
was wanted to help ``deal with a drunken sailor.''
   ``I got up onto the bridge fully expecting to have to deal with
a drunk-type situation, and it wasn't that at all,'' he said. ``It
was a very sad, quiet-type situation.''
   Fox said he was asked to obtain a blood sample, but wasn't
prepared to do so without evidence of a crime.
   Fox said he asked what caused the tanker wreck and Hazelwood
told him: ``You're looking at it.''
   Mark Delozier, a former Coast Guard investigator in Valdez, said
Capt. Hazelwood smelled strongly of alcohol, but Fox apparently
hadn't been informed about the need for blood samples.
   Expecting unruliness, Fox was carrying a gun and handcuffs when
he came aboard the Valdez, Delozier said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
