<FIRST>r i PM-France-Nuclear     11-28 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Nuclear,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Explodes Large Nuclear Device</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France today exploded one of its
largest underground nuclear devices in the South Pacific, drawing a
sharp reaction from New Zealand.
   The test, the eighth this year, was measured at 90 kilotons _
the equivalent of 90,000 tons of TNT _ and New Zealand Prime
Minister Geoffrey Palmer vowed to continue his efforts to end the
program.
   France has detonated 111 nuclear devices in the South Pacific
since 1975 despite growing regional opposition. The blast was
monitored at Raratonga, Cook Islands, by a New Zealand
seismological station.
   Palmer condemned the test, saying his labor government would
continue to urge a halt of the weapons' testing program in French
Polynesia. He dismissed French arguments that the program was
needed to maintain a deterrent force and guarantee its national
security.
   Warwick Smith, head of the Department of Scientific and
Industrial Research which monitors seismic activity, said it was
France's biggest blast this year and second only to a 115-kiloton
explosion on July 25, 1979.
   France two years ago began using Fangataufa atoll for its bigger
tests. It normally uses Mururoa atoll, 800 miles south. Both atolls
are east of Tahiti, or roughly midway between Australia and Chile.
</TEXT>
