<FIRST>u a PM-Obit-Eliana 1stLd-Writethru a0483 11-28 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Eliana, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young AIDS Patient Whose Mother Battled School Officials Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with comment from mother; PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `Mrs. Martinez ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retarded AIDS victim whose adoptive mother
successfully challenged a judge's ruling that the youngster attend
class in a glass booth has died of the disease. She was 8.
   Eliana Martinez, who contracted AIDS as an infant from a tainted
blood transfusion, died in her mother's arms at home Monday
evening, surrounded by family members and friends.
   ``She died like she lived _ fighting every inch of the way,''
said her mother, Rosa Martinez. ``She opened her eyes and looked
right at me. Then she closed them and she died.''
   Eliana had been monitored around the clock since a brush with
death three weeks ago from a feeding-tube infection
   ``She never snapped back from that,'' said Dan McClowry,
Eliana's former speech therapist and a friend of the family. ``She
had been in and out of a coma for the last three days ... running a
fever of up to 105 with an accelerated heartbeat.''
   Mrs. Martinez adopted the girl as an 11-month-old child
abandoned in a Puerto Rico hospital.
   Mrs. Martinez, a licensed practical nurse, once said of Eliana:
``She was deprived of family and we became that. She was deprived
of health and we gave her the best medical attention she could.''
And finally, she saw to it Eliana wouldn't be deprived of an
education.
   Hillsborough County School Board officials had wanted the child
kept home, fearing she posed a health risk. A judge ruled Eliana
could attend school if she stayed inside a special glass booth.
   But Mrs. Martinez said she wouldn't send her daughter to class
under such conditions. Her attorney appealed and won. In April,
Eliana went to school for children with special needs, without the
enclosure.
   Mrs. Martinez, her 20-year-old son, Joseph, and a few family
friends and caretakers had been sitting up with the child for the
last few days knowing death was near, McClowry said.
   Eliana's body was to be taken today to the National Institutes
of Health in Bethesda, Md., for an autopsy, said McClowry. The
funeral will be next week in Tampa.
   Doctors took Eliana off the experimental AIDS-fighting drug DDI
on Oct. 4, saying it wasn't protecting her from life-threatening
infections. Eliana had been given AZT, the only federally approved
AIDS drug, for two years and was switched when it was no longer
helping her.
   Mrs. Martinez, 37, adopted Eliana in her native Puerto Rico
after responding to a radio appeal for the homeless child. Eliana
weighed only about 10 pounds when Mrs. Martinez took her home.
   At first, doctors thought the baby might have cerebral palsy.
   It wasn't until the spring of 1985 that Mrs. Martinez and her
husband, Jose, learned Eliana had AIDS-related complex or ARC, a
precursor to AIDS.
</TEXT>
