<FIRST>r i BC-Czech-Text     11-28 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Czech-Text,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister's Announcement Of New Communist Concessions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, as translated by The
Associated Press, is the announcement by Communist minister without
portfolio Marian Calfa on the creation of a coalition government:
   The negotiations of the Civic Forum and the delegation of the
National Front and the federal government lasted two hours, with
two breaks. The introduction to the negotiations took place in a
rather excited atmosphere, especially because opinions were
exchanged on the situation ... and the approach was not identical.
   After an exhaustive exchange of opinions, the delegation of the
National Front and the federal government acceded to a constructive
agreement and accepted the following conclusions.
   I will inform you only about those conclusions which the federal
government can fulfil according to its position in the constitution
of the Czechoslovak Socialist republic.
   The premier promised that by Dec. 3, 1989, he will ask the
president to appoint a new government. This government should be
based on a broad coalition representing non-party members, other
political parties and naturally the Communist Party of
Czechoslovakia.
   It will be a government constituted primarily of experts and
professionals.
   The federal government will use its constitutional authority to
propose new laws and will suggest to the Federal Assembly
(Parliament) changes in the Czechoslovak constitution in three
articles:
   No. 1, dropping the clause guaranteeing the leading role of the
Communist Party, so far included (in the constitution);
   Leaving out a clause about the closed character of the National
Front and the leading role of the Communist Party in it (The
National Front is a Communist-dominated umbrella organization of
all political parties and social groups permitted in
Czechoslovakia);
   Leaving out the clause stipulating education in the spirit of
Marxism-Leninism. This concept will be replaced by a concept of
education based on scientific knowledge and the principles of
humanitarianism.
   The Premier promised he would ask the National Committee of
Prague (Prague local government) to provide the necessary premises
for the Civic Forum to carry out its activities.
   The original excited atmosphere has turned during the talks into
a constructive atmosphere in a mutual endeavor to find ways out of
the present political situation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
