<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0513-a0440,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Physician Said to Report Mayor Used Cocaine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 13th graf, The Washington, with report of two more
overdoses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The office of District of Columbia Mayor
Marion Barry is branding as ``character assassination'' a televised
report that Barry was hospitalized for treatment of a drug overdose
in 1983.
   WUSA-TV said Monday that it had obtained a police report quoting
a Howard University Hospital physician as saying Barry was
hospitalized for a drug overdose.
   Psychiatrist Alyce Gullattee, who directs the hospital's
Institute of Drug Abuse and Addiction, was interviewed twice by
police investigators in June 1984, the station said.
   ``When Mayor Marion Barry was hospitalized ... his illness was
the result of an overdose of drugs (cocaine) that occurred while he
was in the company of a female companion who also overdosed,''
Gullattee told police, according to the report.
   ``Barry overdosed a second time; however, he was taken to the
District of Columbia General Hospital for treatment,'' she was
quoted as saying.
   The station did not say how Gullattee would know about treatment
for a drug overdose at another hospital.
   Barry was taken to Howard University Hospital by ambulance Sept.
23, 1983, complaining of chest pains and shortness of breath after
a party with friends at a Washington hotel.
   Initially, doctors feared the mayor had suffered a heart attack,
but a mayoral spokesman later told reporters that Barry had been
hospitalized for a hiatal hernia, an abnormality of the digestive
tract where part of the stomach protrudes through the diaphragm.
   WUSA-TV did not say whether Gullattee was involved in the
mayor's treatment. Gullattee declined repeated attempts Monday for
an interview.
   The mayor has acknowledged being hospitalized at D.C. General
twice after his release from Howard. But Barry said on all three
occasions that he was treated for his hernia problem, not cocaine
abuse.
   At least two people have said they provided drugs for the mayor.
The U.S. attorney's office has investigated, but no drug charges
have been brought against him.
   The station said the police report of the Gullattee interview
was never given to the U.S. attorney's office.
   The Washington Times today quoted sources as saying Barry was
hospitalized two more times for drugs _ once at a Washington
hospital on an undisclosed date and in January 1987 while he was in
Los Angeles to attend the Super Bowl.
   Barry was out of town Monday, but his office called the
allegations an ``outrageous character assassination'' and said his
medical records reveal he did not overdose on drugs.
   Dr. Vincent Roux, the mayor's personal physician, said Gullattee
did not treat Barry and has no knowledge of his condition. Roux
said he had no way of knowing whether the mayor overdosed on
cocaine.
   Former Police Chief Maurice Turner, who is expected to run
against Barry, confirmed that Gullattee made the allegations,
WUSA-TV said.
   One of the two lieutenants who spoke with the doctor declined to
comment and the other could not be reached, the station said.
</TEXT>
