<FIRST>r w PM-Stello-Nuclear     11-28 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stello-Nuclear,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled Nominee Given New Title in Nuclear Arms Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's embattled nominee to head the
nation's nuclear weapons production will take a lower-ranking post
in the arms program until the Senate acts on the nomination early
next year, the Energy Department said today.
   The decision to appoint Victor Stello Jr. as principal deputy
assistant secretary for defense programs suggested that Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins is committed to trying to overcome
Senate opposition to the nomination.
   The new appointment does not require Senate confirmation.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee held two days of hearings on
Stello's nomination as assistant secretary for defense programs
earlier this month, then decided not to act on the matter until
after Congress reconvenes in January. The panel held open the
possibility that Stello would be asked to testify again.
   The job for which Stello was nominated last July is responsible
for managing nuclear weapons production at 17 major plants and
laboratories in 12 states. Part of the production complex is shut
down for safety and mechanical upgrades.
   In a memorandum to managers of the nuclear weapons program,
Under Secretary John Tuck announced that Stello would be his main
deputy for an ``interim period'' pending Senate action, which he
said was likely shortly after Congress returns.
   Tuck said he was confident the new appointment ``will enable
defense programs to more readily meet the wide range of demands
facing the nuclear weapons complex in the foreseeable future.''
   Stello has been working as an adviser to Watkins on nuclear
weapons issues since his nomination was announced last July. During
this period he has been on loan to the department from the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission, where he held the title of executive
director for operations, the top-ranking executive post.
   Joseph Fouchard, an NRC spokesman, said Stello gave up his
commission job as of Monday. Stello worked for the NRC and its
predecessor, the Atomic Energy Commission, for 24 years as a
regulator of commercial nuclear power plants.
</TEXT>
