<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Ventures     11-28 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Ventures,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Sign Joint Ventures With Americans, Italians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and American partners today signed a joint
venture deal to build and operate a $2 billion petrochemical
complex in western Siberia.
   The plant in Tobolsk will process petrochemicals that will be
used to make consumer products, largely automotive and medical
items, for both Soviet and foreign markets, according to a news
release put out by the project.
   A consortium of Western firms, led by Combustion Engineering of
Stamford, Conn., entered the deal with the Tobolsk Petrochemical
Company, a subsidiary of the Soviet Ministry of Chemical and Oil
Refining Industries.
   The first phase of the project, construction of the plant, is
expected to be finished by 1993, the release said.
   The plant, which will process Siberian oil and gas, will adhere
to environmental standards as strict as any of those in the West,
it added.
   The announcement came on the same day the Soviet Union and the
Italian automobile giant Fiat signed a joint venture in Rome to
produce 300,000 cars for Soviet consumers.
   The Soviets will hold 70 percent of the $1.3 billion venture,
with the Italians holding the rest. The plant will be located in
Yelabuga, southeast of Moscow.
</TEXT>
