<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SeditionTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0480 11-28 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sedition Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0480,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Clears Three Radicals of Attempting to Overthrow U.S. Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with deliberations resuming; PICKS
UP 3rd graf pvs, `Prosecutors alleged ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury today grappled with
racketeering charges against three radicals, one day after clearing
them of trying to overthrow the U.S. government.
   The partial verdict acquitting the defendants of seditious
conspiracy Monday came on the 19th day of deliberations in the
yearlong trial. The jury said it had not reached agreement on five
other charges against the 1970s militants.
   Prosecutors alleged the defendants, in their early 40s, were
members of a terrorist group that plotted bombings and bank
robberies on the East Coast from 1976 to 1984 in a conspiracy to
topple the U.S. government.
   Two defendants, Raymond Levasseur and Richard Williams, already
are serving lengthy terms for convictions in connection with some
of the bombings. Patricia Levasseur is free on bail after serving
3{ years of a five-year term for harboring a fugitive, her husband,
Raymond.
   The partial verdict also cleared Mrs. Levasseur of racketeering.
Yet to be decided were charges of racketeering against the two men
and charges of racketeering conspiracy against all three. Each
count carries a maximum penalty of 20 years and $20,000 in fines.
   The jury may have had trouble accepting the prosecution's
argument that the little-known defendants were a serious threat to
the government, said Arthur Wolf, professor at Western New England
College of Law.
   ``I think the government was really over-reaching frankly,''
Wolf said.
   An April 1976 bombing at the Suffolk County Courthouse left one
man with his leg severed below the knee, but many of the bombings
failed because of ineptitude.
   ``I can't help believing that when you're talking about
seditious conspiracy that the jurors would take into account in
some respect the inability to carry out the plan,'' Wolf said.
   ``The fact is that conspiracy to overthrow the government by
violence is a ridiculous charge. The government had no right to use
it,'' said Elizabeth Fink, a defense attorney.
   ``These are very broad statutes,'' said Mrs. Levasseur. ``People
get convicted of these charges without ever leaving home.''
   Prosecutors declined comment on the partial verdict.
   The trial began in January after being moved from Boston; jurors
got the case Nov. 6. Nearly 200 witnesses appeared and more than
1,700 exhibits were introduced.
   There were seven defendants at the time of the initial jury
selection in March 1988, part of a band whose members sometimes
called themselves the United Freedom Front. Prosecutors dropped
charges against two defendants, a third pleaded guilty to sedition
and other charges, and a separate trial was ordered for a fourth.
   Prosecutors built their case around notebooks allegedly written
by the defendants that the government charged provided a written
record of meetings and plots.
   But defense attorneys made light of the handwritten notebooks,
with one lawyer saying they might be a ``memoir glorifying
revolutionary action either real or wished for.''
   Levasseur, who represented himself, delivered an intense speech
explaining his political evolution from his service in Vietnam in
the late 1960s, describing himself as ``a soldier that's still at
war.''
   While he did not admit to any of the charges, he did speak about
his desire to cry out against injustices in Central America and
South Africa and said he had never betrayed his values.
</TEXT>
