<FIRST>r a PM-DeafSuit     11-28 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaf Suit,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deaf Law Student to Be Given Classroom Notes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deaf Rutgers University law student has
won a court order forcing the school to provide her with classroom
notes.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley S. Brotman on Monday ordered Rutgers
University School of Law not to hold two classes attended by Karen
Prince unless she receives notes within 24 hours of each class.
   ``It's all I wanted _ a note-taker,'' said a tearful Ms. Prince.
``I'm very satisfied.''
   Ms. Prince, a third-year student who represented herself, had
sued under federal Rehabilitation Act of 1973, which requires
recipients of federal funding to ensure that handicapped people
receive equal benefits from programs.
   The school had agreed to provide a note-taker or interpreter in
a 1988 settlement of a lawsuit she filed in 1987. University
attorney Aron Schwartz said the school spent about $10,000 a year
to provide sign language interpreters and note-takers for Ms.
Prince but has had trouble finding qualified candidates. At one
point Ms. Prince rejected notes she said were illegible.
   School officials last week circulated a request asking Ms.
Prince's classmates to provide her with notes. Brotman said no one
complied.
   ``To leave it with the way it's been done _ a hit-or-miss kind
of thing _ we're not getting anywhere,'' said Brotman. ``I've got
to satisfy that she gets that information.
   ``It may cost Rutgers some money, but that's my least concern
now. Rutgers gets plenty of money from the government,'' he said.
   Ms. Prince, 39, who expects to graduate in December, said the
case marks the first time federal civil rights provisions have been
used to force a university to supply assistance for a deaf student.
   ``It would be my hope that they would say, `Wow, there's a deaf
person in law school _ I can do it too,''' said Ms. Prince, who
lost her hearing in 1972.
   She is the only deaf person attending the 700-student law school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
