<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Vatican-Gorbachev     11-28 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-Gorbachev,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Seeking Permanent Ties With Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II will ask Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to agree to permanent ties for the first time
between the Kremlin and the Holy See, a top Vatican official said
today.
   Gorbachev will arrive in Italy on Wednesday and meet with
Polish-born John Paul on Friday for the first talks between a
leader of the world's Roman Catholics and a Soviet Communist Party
chief.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro, briefing reporters on the
visit, indicated that the issue of Vatican-Moscow ties, broken
after the Russian Revolution in 1917, would be high on the pope's
agenda.
   ``The Holy See is asking for the possibility of a type of
permanent, stable relationship,'' Navarro said.
   The official said it was premature to discuss the matter further
but noted the United States was represented at the Vatican by a
personal envoy of the president even before diplomatic relations
were established in 1983.
   The historic audience on Friday will cap a dramatic warming in
Vatican-Soviet relations, which were marked for decades by mutual
hostility.
   Soviet rulers have viewed religion as a barrier to their
nation's revolutionary goals, while Roman pontiffs have preached
that Communism is evil.
   Navarro praised efforts under Gorbachev to create a new
relationship between the Soviet state and believers.
   But he said problems remain and that the Vatican was waiting for
the Supreme Soviet to take up a new law that would permit various
sects to teach religion as well as practice it. Proselytizing is
now banned.
   The pope's goal for the Catholic Church in the Soviet Union is
the same as for any other country, Navarro said, meaning it wants
to freely nominate bishops, open seminaries and control its own
churches.
   Soviet spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov, in Rome preparing for the
visit, said the papal meeting was particularly important because
``it's the first time ever.''
   ``They have talked for years about dialogue between Christians
and Marxists. This time it will be real,'' Gerasimov said.
   ``Christian values are human values and they are the same as
socialist values,'' he said.
</TEXT>
