<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-AriasNavarro 1stLd-Writethru   11-28 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Arias Navarro, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0472,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias Navarro, Last Prime Minister Under Franco, Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with burial; SUBS last 2 grafs with 1 graf
with burial details.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Arias Navarro, the last prime
minister appointed under the authoritarian rule of Gen. Francisco
Franco, died of a heart attack and was buried today, his family
said. He was 80.
   A niece, who asked not to be identified, said Arias Navarro died
at 10:20 p.m. Monday at his suburban Madrid home. He had been in
poor health for several years, she said.
   Franco named Arias Navarro, a conservative lawyer and former
mayor of Madrid, as prime minister in December 1973. Arias Navarro
appeared on national television to announce Franco's death on Nov.
20, 1975.
   He was reappointed to the post by King Juan Carlos, who
immediately began dismantling Franco's authoritarian apparatus.
   In July 1976, Arias Navarro resigned and gave way to the
peaceful transition to democracy carried out under the king and
leading to the 1977 general elections, the first since the end of
the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War.
   Arias Navarro, who began his career as a prosecutor, was
appointed mayor of the Spanish capital in 1965 and held the post
until 1973, when he became interior minister.
   He was survived by his wife, Maria Luz. The couple had no
children. He was buried today in a cemetery outside the capital.
</TEXT>
