<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-NATO     11-28 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Defense Chiefs Meet to Hear More About Planned U.S. Defense
Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney today
filled NATO allies in on American plans for military spending
reductions in coming years, officials said.
   Meanwhile, in Budapest, Hungary, the defense ministers of the
seven Warsaw Pact nations began a three-day meeting to discuss
military policies in light of improved East-West relations and the
political upheaval in the East bloc.
   Hungarian Defense Minister Ferenc Kapati said at the opening
session that the ministers would ``put forward and discuss five
important and topical issues that serve the modernization of the
joint armed forces and their defensive doctrine,'' the state MTI
news agency reported. Further details were not immediately provided.
   Defense ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
eagerly awaited Cheney's briefing at the start of their two-day
meeting.
   Reports of the spending cuts have raised concern about whether
the United States intends to pull out some of its more than 300,000
troops in Europe before an agreement is reached on reducing
conventional arms on the continent.
   Talks are being held in Vienna and an accord is expected next
year.
   But German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg said of U.S.
proposals, ``We are talking about plans for the mid-1990s.''
   Officials did not immediately provide details of Cheney's
remarks. He was expected to try to ease any fears about the U.S.
commitment to NATO in the face of the momentous political and
social changes in Eastern Europe.
   Cheney, who stopped in the Netherlands on his way to Belgium,
promised no troops would be pulled out of Europe without an
East-West agreement on conventional arms reductions, the Dutch
government said in The Hague.
   Norwegian Gen. Vigleik Eide, chairman of NATO's panel of top
military commanders, said the Soviet Union and its allies remain
militarily powerful.
   ``The Berlin Wall ... has not much to do with military realities
and does not change the military forces,'' he said. He was
referring to East Germany's decision to let its citizens travel
freely and the opening of the Berlin Wall on Nov. 9.
   The NATO defense ministers' talks are the first in a series of
high-level discussions that will be held in the coming weeks at
alliance headquarters.
   Leaders of the 16 member nations will meet Dec. 4 to learn the
results of President Bush's shipboard summit with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev in the Mediterranean off the island of Malta.
</TEXT>
