<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Poland     11-28 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Poland,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delegation Taking Food Aid to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, head of
a U.S. delegation bound for Poland, announced today he will present
a $20 million food-for-peace installment to the Poles during the
visit.
   But Yeutter cautioned against raising unrealistic expectations
for the economies of Poland or other Eastern European countries,
saying economic reform is bound to lag behind political advances.
   ``Economic reform is not an overnight proposition,'' Yeutter
said. ``It will take time. It would be tragic indeed if all the
magnificant emotion of the moment is channeled into frustration.''
   Yeutter spoke with reporters at a White House briefing as the
delegation prepared to leave for its five-day trip to Poland.
   Besides Yeutter, the delegation includes Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher and an
assortment of U.S. business and labor leaders.
   Mrs. Dole told the briefing that there will be ``initial pain,''
including increased unemployment, for a workforce ``used to the
communist system _ low wages, little room for advancement and no
encouragement for individual initiative or innovations.''
   She said the administration was prepared to offer Poles
``assistance in easing this pain,'' including consultations on
establishing worker training and retraining programs.
   Mosbacher said he will spend part of his time in Poland pursuing
opportunities for U.S.-Polish business ventures and agreements.
   Yeutter said that, during the visit, he would announce a $20
million installment in U.S. food aid to help Poland get through the
winter. The aid is part of $100 million in food aid announced by
the administration last summer.
   At the same time, Yeutter sounded a pessimistic note on short
term prospects for the economies of Poland and its neighboring East
bloc states.
   ``We just be careful that economic expectations do not become
unrealistic,'' he said. ``In the kind of emotional environment that
exists today, that can very readily occur.''
   ``Each of these countries has experience 40 years or more of
ignominious failure of the communist system. They are now seeking
to convert overnight into a system that is much more nearly
comparable to one we've been honing for 200 years.''
   The delegation was to leave tonight and return back to
Washington on Saturday. Yeutter said a report would be delivered to
President Bush before Christmas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
