<FIRST>u i PM-Nall-PlaneCrash 5thLd-Writethru a0565 11-28 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nall-Plane Crash, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0565,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Light-Plane Crash Kills NTSB Member, Injures at Least Four</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs with 2 grafs to CORRECT last name to Bond
sted Bond-Zerhusen and ADD background; pickup 13th graf pvs, `Null, a...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the U.S. National
Transportation Safety Board was killed along with two Venezuelan
pilots when their small plane crashed in hills west of the city,
U.S. Embassy officials said today.
   There were conflicting reports about the number of injured and
their identities.
   Embassy officials said five U.S. diplomats aboard the
twin-engine Cessna 402 were seriously injured in the crash, which
occurred Monday evening, apparently in bad weather.
   In Washington, NTSB spokesman Alan Pollock said four passengers
were injured.
   Killed in the crash was Joseph Trippe Nall, 47, who served on
the five-member NTSB since 1986, officials said. The plane's
pilots, Dickson Naranjo and Jose Vargas, also were killed, embassy
officials said.
   The plane apparently was headed to the Charallave municipal
airport, in the hills west of Caracas, when it crashed, Venezuelan
transportation officials said.
   Pollock said Nall was in Caracas to give a speech to the
Venezuelan Aeronautical Congress and that he and his party were on
a Cave Airlines flight around the Caracas area. The plane crashed
as it tried to land in fog.
   Investigators from the Venezuelan transport ministry were on the
scene today. Pollock said the board would send an investigating
team to Caracas later today and that NTSB Chairman Jim Kolstad
would accompany the investigators.
   U.S. Embassy officials said five survivors, a woman and four
men, were being treated in a Caracas hospital and apparently were
in grave condition.
   Nall's assistant, Kenneth Peppard, was among the injured,
Pollock said.
   John Leyden, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said in Washington that two FAA employees also were
among the injured. He identified them as David Hanley, who worked
at an FAA hangar at Washington National Airport, and Jerri Alles,
an employee of the agency's international aviation office.
   A fourth passenger was identified as Kay Bond, a producer at
Maryland Public Television for the show ``AM Weather,'' an in-depth
weather program that is distributed nationwide.
   ``It is our understanding that she has not sustained any
injuries, although she is still in the hospital being checked,''
said Sharon Philippart, national promotions manager for Maryland
Public Television. ``It was my understanding that she was on
vacation. She was not traveling for MPT.''
   Nall, a lawyer from Smithfield, N.C., was appointed to the board
April 11, 1986, by President Reagan. His term was due to expire
Dec. 31, 1992.
   He was a native of Atlanta, had a master of divinity degree, and
had preached at Baptist churches in Halifax, Va., and Smithfield.
   Nall also was a pilot and had operated Nall Aviation
Enterprises, a ground school at Johnston County Airport in
Smithfield, the NTSB said.
   Nall's death leaves a vacancy on the five-member board which
must be filled by presidential appointment. By law, the position
must go to a Democrat to keep a political balance on the board,
which now has three Republicans and one Democrat.
   The safety board investigates transportation accidents and
incidents, determines their cause and makes recommendations to
other agencies and organizations to increase safety.
</TEXT>
