<SECOND>PM-Summit-Warships, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 5 grafs new with Pentagon comments; pick up 3rd graf pvs,
``Another ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Navy is expected to have four
combat ships capable of using nuclear weaponry in the Mediterranean
during the upcoming Bush-Gorbachev saltwater summit, a Pentagon
spokesman said today.
   ``The Soviet Union is expected to have four nuclear-capable
combatants and four auxiliaries in the Med during the Malta
meeting,'' spokesman Fred Hoffman told reporters.
   The statement followed a published report that the Pentagon had
observed a withdrawal of such Soviet vessels, possibly in
anticipation of a Gorbachev initiative to declare the region a
nuclear-free zone.
   Hoffman said the Soviet group will include three guided missile
frigates, the Slava guided missile cruiser _ which will be the site
of talks on Saturday between Presidents Bush and Gorbachev _ and
four other support vessels.
   ``There is no evidence that the Soviets plan to vacate the Med''
during the weekend summit, said one defense official Monday,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said on Monday.
   Another official, who also spoke privately, said the Soviets
``still have a submarine presence'' in the Mediterranean, and are
expected to continue to do so through the Dec. 2-3 shipboard summit
off Malta.
   The two leaders are scheduled to share a dinner Saturday night
aboard the U.S. host vessel, the USS Belknap, the guided missile
cruiser that is a command ship for the U.S. Sixth fleet in the
Mediterranean.
   The U.S. Navy will be out in force during the summit,
represented in the Mediterranean by some 25 combat ships _
including the aircraft carrier USS Forrestal and the dozen
destroyers, cruisers and frigates that compose its battle group.
   Also in the area is an amphibious ready group composed of five
ships ready to deploy some 2,400 Marines, said Navy spokesman Cmdr.
Craig Quigley.
   While the defense official confirmed there is ``a slight
depression'' in the number of Soviet combat ships present in the
area compared to about a year ago, he argued that such a cut could
be due as much to economical as political considerations.
   About a year ago, the Pentagon counted about six to 10 Soviet
combatants in the region, with a range of 12 to 24 support ships.
During the summit, the number is expected to range from about four
to six major combat ships, with ``a few more'' support vessels, the
official said.
   All of the Soviet combat ships are capable of using nuclear
weapons, the official said.
   ``Our intelligence tells us that this dip appears to be part of
a normal rotation. Whether it is a permanent retrenchment, or a
temporary aberration, we just don't know,'' the official said.
   The official noted that during the past months, the United
States has received evidence of a worldwide downturn in Sovet naval
activity, a step that was widely interpreted as being taken due to
pressures on the Soviet economy.
</TEXT>
