<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     11-28 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large Group of Vietnamese Refugees Resettled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 Vietnamese refugees who had
waited two years in this British colony boarded a plane Tuesday for
their journey to the West in the largest one-day resettlement of
refugees from Hong Kong in seven years.
   Most of the Vietnamese will go the the United States after six
months in the Philippines to study English and learn about life in
the United States.
   Others were sent to Sweden and Australia. Government statistics
showed that was the largest one-day resettlement of Vietnamese
refugees in seven years.
   Another 12,700 Vietnamese refugees still are waiting in Hong
Kong to be resettled in the West.
   More than 5,000 will be resettled in mid-1990, said Alfred
Kottek, the regional representative of the Intergovernmental
Committee for Migration who organized the refugees' transportion.
   The refugees in Hong Kong either arrived before June 1988 or
were classified as refugees under a screening policy.
   In June 1988, the government adopted a policy that treats all
Vietnamese boat people as illegal immigrants unless they prove they
are fleeing persecution. Those classed as illegal immigrants face
repatriation to their Communist homeland.
   Nearly 44,000 Vietnamese boat people in Hong Kong are waiting to
be screened. So far this year, 33,889 have arrived, compared with
18,052 in the same period of 1988. Most won't be classified as
refugees.
   Francis Maude of the British Foreign Office said forcible
repatriation of Vietnamese boat people from Hong Kong will begin by
February or March.
   On Thursday, 132 Vietnamese boat people, including 12 babies
born in Hong Kong, will fly back to their homeland voluntarily, the
sixth such group.
   Since March, 507 Vietnamese have volunteered to go back under a
plan monitored by the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees, whose office pays each one $50 before departure.
</TEXT>
