<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--LeaningTower     11-28 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Leaning Tower,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Suggests Closing Leaning Tower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top government commission for public
works suggested Tuesday the famed leaning tower of Pisa be closed
for restoration work.
   The recommendation by the Superior Council of Public Works was
passed along to Parliament, which must make the final decision.
   Experts recently have voiced alarm about decay in the 162-foot
tower, completed between 1360 and 1370. Local officials counter
that the monument, which attracts thousands of tourists every
month, is not in any immediate danger.
   The commission did not say it could collapse. It said the
closure would allow conservation work to begin.
   Its tilt has been increasing by an average 0.047 inches a year
since measurements began in 1918. It has remained open to tourists,
even through World War II.
   Gero Geri, a professor of topography, has said it will take more
than 100 years before the tower reaches the point where it will
likely fall.
   The government allotted funds for the conservation and
strengthening of the tower but experts have been stumped on how to
save the building, which a popular Italian song says ``leans,
leans, but never comes down.''
</TEXT>
