<FIRST>r w AM-StateBoundary     11-28 0121</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Boundary,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill Setting South Dakota-Nebraska River Boundary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation Tuesday
approving a boundary compact between South Dakota and Nebraska
involving a 12-mile stretch of the Missouri River.
   The compact sets the boundary at the midpoint of the main river
channel between Union County, S.D., and Dakota County, Neb.
   The two states originally agreed to set the border at the
midpoint of the Missouri River channel in 1905, but since then the
river has shifted due to both natural causes and Corps of Engineers
navigation and flood control projects.
   The new compact establishes the current midpoint of the river as
the boundary. It provides for future adjustments should the river
shift again.
