<TEXT>
   A Vermont foundation to help black
students attend Catholic universities has been named after Sister
Thea Bowman, the only black member of the Franciscan Sisters of
Perpetual Adoration.
   ``I was skeptical at first,'' said Bowman, 51, of Canton. ``Poor
people have had so many things promised. I don't mean a handout, I
mean an opportunity, a chance. You don't raise people's hopes
without the real possibility of doing something that's going to be
successful.''
   Bowman pioneered the use of both African-American spirituals and
African rituals and dance in Mass. She directs the Inter-Cultural
Awareness office for the Jackson Diocese and released an album of
spirituals last year.
