<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Parkway     11-28 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Parkway,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Founder Honored With Clara Barton Parkway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation Tuesday
renaming the Maryland and District of Columbia portion of the
George Washington Memorial Parkway as the Clara Barton Parkway.
   Clara Barton was the 19th century nurse and founder of the
American Red Cross who was called the ``Angel of the Battlefield''
for her efforts during the Civil War.
   She lived at Glen Echo, Md., midpoint of the seven-mile stretch
of parkway now named in her honor.
   Rep. Connie Morella, R-Md., instigated the name change both to
honor Barton and to help motorists who confused the
Maryland-District stretch of the parkway with the longer, better
known portion of the George Washington Memorial Parkway on the
Virginia side of the Potomac River.
   The 27-mile Virginia portion runs from McLean, Va., on the
western end down to Washington's homestead in Mount Vernon, Va.,
with a break in Alexandria, Va.
   Bush also signed separate legislation approving the location of
a memorial within the 2.2-acre Vietnam Veterans Memorial site on
the Mall honoring women who served in Vietnam.
</TEXT>
