<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Scene     11-28 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Scene,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avid Public Debate on New Freedom Brightens Wenceslas Square</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The streets of Prague were quiet
Tuesday for the first time since a crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators 11 days ago drove the people to demand reform.
   The main opposition group Civic Forum called for a temporarily
end to the mass demonstrations that set the city center in motion.
Small groups nevertheless continued to gather in Wenceslas Square
to discuss the changes.
   ``We have courage again,'' a student said. ``I don't think
anyone can shut us up again.''
   Czechs and Slovaks, who once before lived through democratic
reforms of 1968, long were reluctant to challenge the hard-line
leadership put in place after Soviet-led troops crushed the
``Prague Spring.''
   But that changed after Nov. 17, when hundreds were beaten in an
unmatched display of brutality, as police broke up a crowd of
50,000 who dared call for reforms.
   The student was one of hundreds who gathered on Wenceslas
Square, the heart of the pro-democracy movement, to discuss the
changes that brought down the leadership of Milos Jakes and forced
Premier Ladislav Adamec to talk to the opposition.
   After a meeting with the opposition Tuesday, Adamec pledged to
form a coalition government by Dec. 3, and Prague residents clearly
were elated by the thought of non-Communists sharing power for the
first time in decades.
   ``After years of silence, we can talk freely again,'' said an
old woman, who, like the others at the square spoke rapidly,
without taking the time to give her name. ``Democracy has already
won.''
   The crowd repeatedly sang the national anthem and waved their
hands in ``V'' for victory signs, doffing their hats despite the
freezing temperatures.
   The statue of King Wenceslas _ a towering figure on horseback _
was draped with flags and banners. Candles flickered along its base.
   Lines formed outside shops along the square to read the daily
pro-democracy bulletins taped in the windows, and people eagerly
read new leaflets printed during the night.
   One young warehouse worker, referring to Adamec's promise of a
new government, said it would be ``transitional,'' but was
nevertheless positive.
   ``More important is the promise that the Communist Party will
give up its leading role,'' he said, alluding to agreement to
remove such language from a new constitution.
   Many older people joined the students on the square. It was
largely the students, backed by artists and intellectuals, who have
carried the democracy movement.
   A box for donations to the students' movement was quickly
filled. Nearly everyone who stopped on the square to join the
discussions or passed by threw in money. Even pensioners dropped in
a few coins.
   ``It's as though the people of Prague have suddenly awakened,''
said a woman listening nearby. ``Only a few weeks ago they were
only interested in their car, their weekend house and food. Now
politics is at the forefront, like in 1968.''
   People have been reluctant to get involved in politics, after
their experiences 21 years ago. The country has one of the highest
living standards in the Soviet bloc and consumer goods are more
plentiful than elsewhere.
   ``We've fought ourselves free!'' a worker on the square
exclaimed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
