<DOCNO> AP891128-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovietConference     11-28 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Conference,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets in U.S. for Alcoholism Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alcoholism centers from New England to
Arizona are opening their doors this week to 110 Soviets eager to
see how the disease is treated in this country.
   The Soviets were to spend Monday and Tuesday in Stamford before
splitting into groups to tour treatment centers in 11 states over
two weeks.
   American and Soviet views of alcoholism differ. In the United
States, where an estimated 18 million adults have a drinking
problem, the disease is seen as societal and affecting the
drinker's family. Treatment focuses on why one drinks.
   The Soviets have placed more attention on physical approaches,
such as acupuncture and liver dialysis. Only 5 million Soviets are
recognized officially as alcoholics needing treatment, but
conference delegates estimate an additional 15 million or more are
problem drinkers.
   ``I hope that while they're here they will learn a great deal
how the family gets enmeshed in the disease and needs its own
recovery,'' said Anne Geller, a director of a New York treatment
center who helped organize the conference.
   ``They also, I hope, will learn the importance of destigmatizing
alcoholism and treating it as any other disorder,'' she said. ``No
one in the Soviet Union would get up and say, `I'm a recovering
alcoholic,' whereas people here do it all the time.''
   Betty Ford, the former first lady who has reinforced that
approach by proclaiming she is a recovering alcoholic, greeted some
of the delegates Sunday night. The Betty Ford Treatment Center in
Rancho Mirage, Calif., is among the conference hosts.
   This is the second meeting for the experts, who first exchanged
information at an April conference in Moscow attended by about 100
Americans.
   The conference was the brainchild of Father Luis Dolan, a Roman
Catholic priest who coordinates Soviet exchanges for the Wainwright
House in Rye, N.Y. Dolan, who has visited the Soviet Union several
times, said some of the questions he heard most often on his early
trips had to do with alcoholism.
   ``Something just touched me here,'' he said, striking his chest
with a fist, ``when they said, `Can we organize a conference?'''
   The Soviet delegates include scientists, recovering alcoholics
and treatment specialists as well as ballet dancers who belong to
an anti-drug and alcohol group.
   Delegation leader Levon Badalyan, president of the European
Association of Neurologists, said he admires the American concept
of using the schools to teach young children about drug and alcohol
abuse. He also approves of President Bush's attacks on drugs and
the use of actors, athletes and other prominent citizens to
discourage drug abuse.
   He was not impressed by a Soviet effort to crack down on
excessive drinking by raising prices, restricting where liquor is
sold and raising the drinking age for liquor to 21.
   ``The point is that such restrictive measures breed bootlegging,
production of homemade alcohol, and worse cases of alcoholism
appear,'' he said.
   ``The way to overcome alcoholism, in my view, is through raising
the general cultural level of society, raising it spiritually, ...
providing a person with specific goals in his life, and finally,
impressing on the person that alcoholism is a bad habit,'' he said.
   The conference will take Badalyan and other delegates to halfway
houses, outpatient clinics and other treatment centers, which are
much smaller than those in the Soviet Union, where the largest
alcoholism facility has 6,000 beds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BlinkDeath     11-28 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blink Death,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted by Eye Blink Testimony Gets 6 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose fatally wounded victim
used deathbed eye blinks to identify him as the assailant was
sentenced Tuesday to six months in jail.
   ``God brought him back for a few moments to communicate with
detectives,'' Westchester County Court Judge John LaCava said of
Frederick Sannicandro, 38.
   Sannicandro died six hours after he was shot in the abdomen by
his friend, Frank Zollbrecht, 45, as they were working in a Yonkers
bakery last year.
   While he was being wheeled into surgery, detectives and an
attending physician questioned Sannicandro and asked him to respond
with one blink for ``yes'' and two blinks for ``no.''
   Sannicandro blinked ``yes'' when asked if Zollbrecht had shot
him and ``no'' when asked if the shooting was accidental, according
to trial testimony.
   He could not speak because he had a breathing tube in his throat.
   Zollbrecht had a history of alcohol abuse, according to
testimony. During drunken horseplay, he got a gun his boss had
hidden and shot Sannicandro.
   The defense maintained that Sannicandro's deathbed testimony
should not have been allowed because Sannicandro also was drunk.
   Zollbrecht, convicted of criminally negligent homicide, could
have been sentenced to four years in prison. Assistant District
Attorney Michael Romano argued for a one-year term, saying the
defendant had ignored warnings about drinking and the gun.
   Zollbrecht's lawyer, Anthony Morosco, said his client had been
traumatized at age 7 by the death of an older brother. ``He's a
good person who has suffered a series of great tragedies in his
life,'' Morosco said.
   A tearful Zollbrecht told the judge, ``I would never hurt
Freddy. I'm sorry for what happened. What can I say? I'm sorry I
touched the gun. I'm sorry.''
   LaCava ordered that Zollbrecht spend five years on probation
after his prison term, do 1,000 hours of community service and get
treatment for his drinking and any psychological problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     11-28 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Briefs NATO Allies on Defense Spending</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney pledged
Tuesday the United States won't withdraw troops from Europe without
consulting the allies, officials said at the first NATO meeting
since the Berlin Wall was opened.
   ``The United States will continue to have its forces in Europe
as long as our NATO allies want them (and) need them there,'' said
a senior U.S. defense official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``We are in Europe to stay,'' the official quoted Cheney as
telling other defense ministers at the start of two days of talks
at the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Reports about U.S. plans to reduce its military spending in the
coming years have prompted concern that the United States intended
to pare its commitment to the defense of the European continent.
More than 300,000 U.S. troops are based in Europe, most in West
Germany.
   But Cheney used the meeting to explain to his colleagues the
U.S. budget process and calm any fears about U.S. intentions in the
future.
   Britain's secretary of state for defense, Tom King, said Cheney
``gave clear assurances of an absolute commitment to consultation
... that the United States is here, ready to play its full part in
NATO (and) in Europe.''
   German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg said, ``We are
talking about plans for the mid-1990s.''
   ``I take the position that the United States will not change its
stance in the current (conventional arms) negotiations,'' he said.
   The 16 nations of NATO and the seven of the Soviet-led Warsaw
Pact are holding negotiations in Vienna, Austria, to reduce sharply
conventional, or non-nuclear, arms in Europe.
   President Bush proposed in May that as part of those talks, the
Soviet Union and the United States cut their forces in Europe to
275,000 soldiers each. That would require a cutback of 300,000 in
Soviet forces and 30,000 in U.S. troops.
   Those negotiations are expected to end with an agreement in the
last half of 1990.
   Cheney told the ministers that speculation about U.S. troop
cutbacks stemmed from the Defense Department's look at its budgets
in the 1992-1995 period, according to the U.S. official. No final
budget decisions have been made.
   He promised the allies, the official said, that the United
States ``will not make any unilateral reductions (in troops) and
that any reductions would be considered in the NATO context and in
full consultation with our allies.''
   No figure was given for possible troop cuts in the future, he
said.
   He noted Congress has in recent years sliced the Pentagon's
budget requests and that trend was likely to continue.
   Moreover, the budget plans were being drawn up, he said, based
on assumptions of a conventional arms agreement, a superpower
accord on long-range nuclear missiles, no major military conflicts
in the Third World and continued political reforms in Eastern
Europe.
   The worst case projection, he said, was likely for $180 billion
in reductions over four years. Still, he said the United States
intended to spend $300 billion a year on defense in the mid-1990s.
   The official said no troops would be pulled out of Europe in the
1990 fiscal year, which began Oct. 1, except for those reduced
because of the 1987 superpower treaty on intermediate-range nuclear
forces.
   The 1991 defense budget, which will be sent to Congress in
January, was not expected to trim U.S. forces in Europe, he said.
   With the dramatic events unfolding in Eastern Europe, NATO
officials have been concerned that Western nations will lower their
defense spending even before an arms deal is struck.
   Norwegian Gen. Vigleik Eide, head of NATO's panel of military
commanders, said the Soviet Union and its Eastern allies remain a
powerful military might.
   He acknowledged the startling reforms in the Soviet Union and
Eastern Europe have lowered public perceptions of the military
threat from the East.
   ``Support for defense efforts in the future will be problematic
because of the perception of the threat as already gone,'' he said.
   But he insisted the West's policy should be guided by force
levels.
   ``The Berlin Wall ... has not much to do with military realities
and does not change the military forces,'' he said.
   Leaders of the NATO nations will meet Monday to learn the
results of Bush's shipboard summit Dec. 2-3 with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   NATO defense ministers meet twice a year in their role as the
Defense Planning Committee. France, which is outside NATO's
military structure, does not attend. Iceland, which has no armed
forces, has observer status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
