<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru a0550 11-28 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Crash, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0550,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Doubt Terrorists Caused Crash That Killed 107</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with officials saying passengers
had donned oxygen masks, doubting terrorists blew up plane, quotes; Picks
up 13th graf, `Colombian officials ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian jetliner lost cabin pressure
before it was destroyed by an explosion, and the 107 people aboard
had time to don oxygen masks before they were killed, investigators
said today.
   Authorities were skeptical of claims that terrorists had caused
the explosion, but said they had not determined how the 26-year-old
plane was destroyed on Monday.
   ``The explosion might have been caused by depressurization or by
other causes,'' said Col. Jorge Aurelio Gonzalez, director of
Colombia's Civil Aviation operations. ``A depressurization ... made
the use of oxygen masks necessary.''
   The Boeing 727-100 took off Monday at 7:13 a.m. from Bogota for
Cali, a Colombian city 200 miles to the west. It crashed seven
minutes later, enveloped in flames.
   Hundreds of witnesses saw the jet disintegrate in midair and
many said there were two explosions, with flames and smoke pouring
from the plane.
   Investigators today worked at the hilly site just south of
Bogota where the Avianca Airlines jet crashed. Pieces of the plane
were found up to six miles from the main point of impact, police
said.
   Earlier, Gonzalez said investigators believed that pilots did
not have enough time to report the explosion to ground controllers.
The plane had been climbing at 4,600 feet above the valley.
   ``Given the circumstances of the crash, I would say that it was
a terrorist attack,'' a spokesman for Colombia's Pilots Association
said in an interview. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Hours after the crash, a caller to the Caracol radio network
said the Extraditables, a terrorist group linked to the Medellin
cocaine cartel, had blown up the plane in order to kill six police
informants aboard.
   The caller said the informants had told police the location of
the jungle hideout of cocaine trafficker Pablo Escobar.
   Police on Nov. 22 raided the camp 70 miles east of Medellin, but
Escobar and another cartel leader, Jorge Luis Ochoa, narrowly
escaped capture.
   There was no way to check the authenticity of the call. Col.
Gustavo Leal of the national police said a terrorist attack ``could
not be ruled out.''
   ``I don't believe this accident was caused by terrorists,''
Civil Aviation Director Yezid Castano said today. But he admitted
``what happened to the plane has no explanation.''
   Daniel Eramian, a U.S. Justice Department spokesman in
Washington, said DEA investigators have discounted the telephone
caller's claim as bogus.
   Castano told Radio Caracol the plane was in perfect condition
mechanically and had been subjected to all examinations recommended
by the manufacturer, according to maintenance records.
   Gonzalez said investigators had found no traces of dynamite or
other explosives.
   He said reported indications of metal fatigue were being checked
out. The plane had made 59,139 landings in 46,000 hours of flight
time. A notebook carried by the crew said a 3-inch crack in the
fuselage had been found on Nov. 24, according to the newspaper El
Tiempo.
   Colombian officials said they would send the flight recorder to
the United States, where investigators from the Seattle-based
Boeing Co. and the Federal Aviation Administration would examine it.
   Late Monday, authorities finished recovering the bodies of six
crew members and 101 passengers, many found strewn along the
hillside. Only 16 of the victims had been identified.
   At least one U.S. citizen, Andres Escabi, was among the victims,
a U.S. Embassy spokesman said. Escabi, born in Puerto Rico, also
held Colombian citizenship and lived in Bogota, the spokesman said.
   Police at the crash site said 120 people had been arrested for
looting the bodies, suitcases, packages, and mail. Several of the
looters were caught removing rings and gold chains from the
corpses, police said.
   The government of President Virgilio Barco declared war on drug
traffickers in August, and since then there have been nearly 200
bombings and other attacks that killed 29 people and wounded 236.
   None was on as large scale as Monday's plane crash.
   The Extraditables takes it name from the U.S. Justice
Department's list of 12 Colombian drug suspects most wanted in the
United States. Escobar, the reputed head of the Medellin cartel,
tops the list.
   The last major passenger jet crash in Colombia occurred March
17, 1988, when an Avianca Boeing 727-100 crashed into a mountain
near the northern city of Zulia, killing 138 people.
</TEXT>
