<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WorksiteMammography     11-28 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Worksite Mammography,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worksite Mammography Doubles Breast Cancer-Screening Rate, Report
Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women who were offered low-cost breast X-rays at
work were willing to undergo the cancer-detection procedure at more
than double the rate of women in general, a radiologist says.
   ``By offering a low-cost program at the worksite, we reduced two
of the most significant barriers _ expense and inconvenience _ that
prevent women from obtaining routine mammographic examinations,''
said Dr. Howard B. Kessler.
   In a report Monday to the 75th scientific assembly of the
Radiological Society of North America, Kessler said the program
involved taking a 32-foot mobile mammography van to 53 worksites in
Pennsylvania and four in Delaware.
   Mammographic examinations were offered to female employees and
male employees' spouses over age 35 by Bell of Pennsylvania and
Diamond State Bell, subsidiaries of Bell Atlantic Corp., he said.
   Women were charged $30 each for the standard two-view
mammograms, with the corporations paying the remaining $30 for each
procedure, said Kessler, director of breast imaging at the Fox
Chase Cancer Center in Philadelphia, which ran the program.
   During the first year, 3,627 women _ more than a third of the
approximately 10,000 eligible _ received mammograms at the
worksite, he said.
   From that group, 63 biopsies were recommended. Of those, nine
cancers were identified _ all in early stages _ about the same
prevalence that occurs statewide for the disease, Kessler reported.
   ``I believe nationally about 15 (percent) to 20 percent of women
in age-eligible populations seek out a screening examination,''
Kessler said.
   Breast cancer killed 40,354 U.S. women in 1986, the last year
for which figures are available. A least 19 percent of the deaths
could have been prevented with recommended mammograms, federal
researchers have estimated.
   Doctors agree that women should get mammograms according to the
following timetable, Kessler said: an initial breast X-ray between
the ages of 35 and 39; subsequent breast X-rays every two years
from ages 40 to 49; and annually after that.
   No figures were available on how many companies provide
breast-screening at work nationwide, but it's rare, said Kessler.
   Part of the success of the program outlined by Kessler was due
to the companies' commitment to promote and support mammography, he
said.
   Also, results of the screenings went to the women's private
physicians, rather than to their employers, so privacy was assured,
Kessler said.
   While many employee-insurance plans may cover the costs of
mammograms if they are used in the process of making a diagnosis,
such as by ruling out a suspicious physical sign, few plans cover
them as routine screening procedures, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1503EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Trade     11-28 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit, after improving for
six months, deteriorated slightly to $27.75 billion in the third
quarter, fed by America's appetite for imported goods and by flat
exports, the government reported Tuesday.
   Analysts do not see much improvement in the near future. Imports
may drop somewhat because of a slowing U.S. economy, they say, but
exports also are likely to fall because of a strong dollar and
moderating economies overseas.
   The Commerce Department said the gap between imports and U.S.
exports edged up 0.7 percent in the July-September quarter from the
second quarter's $27.55 billion. The April-June gap deficit was the
narrowest since a $27.7 billion imbalance in the first quarter of
1985.
   Imports posted a 0.3 percent gain to a record $119.3 billion,
while exports rose only 0.2 percent to $91.6 billion, also a
record. Both imports and exports have reached record levels during
each of the last five quarters.
   But analysts worry that exports, which sustained much of the
U.S. economy last year, will remain unchanged in the months ahead.
   ``The trade report substantiates what we've already seen ...
export growth simply has flattened out after booming previously and
is a major source of the wave of weakness rippling through the U.S.
economy, particularly the manufacturing sector,'' commented Allen
Sinai, chief economist of The Boston Co.
   Samuel D. Kahan, chief financial economist for Kleinwort Benson
Government Securities Inc. in Chicago, agreed that the pace of
exports is ``probably coming to the end of its run due to the
dollar.''
   A stronger dollar makes U.S. goods more expensive and thus less
competitive overseas, while making imported goods cheaper and thus
more attractive to American buyers.
   Kahan also suggested that ``as the (British) economy slows,
which seems likely, and some of the other industrial countries,
particuarly Japan, moderate their (economic) activity, that should
hurt our exports.''
   Sinai also said that ``as the U.S. economy weakens more, as will
probably be the case over the next few quarters, imports too will
probably decline.''
   But Lawrence Chimerine, senior economic advisor for the WEFA
Group in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., pointed to the high level of oil
imports, which he said will continue and further aggravate the
trade deficit.
   The Commerce Department said the average number of barrels
imported daily increased 8.5 percent to 8.65 million barrels in the
third quarter _ the highest level since the third quarter of 1977.
   But despite the increase, oil imports showed a July-September
numerical decrease of 1 percent because of lower prices. The
average price per barrel fell from $18.46 to $16.85.
   Non-oil imports rose 0.5 percent to $106 billion, led by
consumer goods, including clothing and household goods. Imports of
industrial supplies and materials fell while both capital goods and
automotive products were virtually unchanged.
   Non-farm exports increased 2 percent to a record $81.8 billion.
The sector was boosted by shipments of capital goods, including
aircraft and parts to Western Europe, Japan and newly
industrialized countries in the Far East.
   Shipments of non-farm products such as industrial supplies and
materials and automotive parts fell. Farm products also fell, down
10 percent to $9.8 billion.
   For the first nine months of the year, the overall deficit was
running at an annual rate of $111.6 billion, down 12.3 percent from
the $127.2 billion trade gap registered in all of 1988.
   Today's report on merchandise trade, which is calculated on a
balance of payment basis, is slightly different from the Commerce
Department's monthly merchandise trade reports because it excludes
U.S. military sales to foreign governments and makes other minor
adjustments in the monthly figures.
 
</TEXT>
