<FIRST>r a AM-MechamForeclosure     11-28 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mecham Foreclosure,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDIC Forecloses On Impeached Governor's Headquarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal banking regulators have begun foreclosure
proceedings on an office building owned by former Gov. Evan Mecham,
who uses the building as his headquarters.
   Mecham owes $461,864 on a $406,000 mortgage he took out from
North American Bank of Phoenix on Dec. 30, 1985, before the bank
failed and was taken over by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   The amount Mecham owes exceeds the original loan amount because
he is behind on the $4,200-a-month payments. Mecham said he had
made payments on the building but confirmed he is behind. He
disputed the amount the FDIC said he owes.
   ``I'll arrange something with them,'' Mecham said. ``I don't
know where they get their figures. They haven't done me the
courtesy of giving me their accounting.''
   Mecham has until the day of the sale, Feb. 23, to work out an
agreement with the FDIC and said ``I don't anticipate losing the
property.''
   Mecham said he used the mortgage money to pay for remodeling and
moving his office into the building after his ouster from the
governor's office. The building serves as his gubernatorial
campaign headquarters but has found few other tenants.
   The one-story building covers 7,300 square feet and was
estimated to be worth $512,289 in 1984, according to county records.
   Mecham wracked up hundreds of thousands of dollars fighting his
impeachment, a criminal charge and a recall election effort last
year and continues to pile up new bills while he fights to get his
impeachment overturned and seeks re-election next year.
   ``I'm a million and half (dollars) out of what I used to have.
It's cost me a lot of money, what's happened in the last two
years,'' he said.
   But he also said he was ``not in trouble'' financially and that
his campaign would not be effected by the foreclosure.
   Mecham campaign spokesman Max Hawkins said he could not comment
on the foreclosure, but believed the Legislature was slowing
Mecham's comeback by refusing to pay his recall campaign expenses
or legal fees incurred from his impeachment.
</TEXT>
