<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-India     11-28 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centrist Opposition Moves to Form Gov't But Divisions Surface</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A centrist opposition alliance moved
Tuesday to form India's first minority government since
independence, but divisions began to surface among potentional
supporters.
   The Congress Party of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi could
conceivably try to form a coalition, but it said it will become the
opposition as the National Front attempts to form a government.
   The Congress Party, which has led the government for all but 2{
years since India gained independence from Britain in 1947, won
more parliamentary seats than any single party in elections that
ended Sunday. But it fell far short of a majority.
   ``That is the verdict of the people,'' said party spokesman
Anand Sharma.
   ``We sat in the opposition once before and we can do it again,''
said Arjun Singh, a powerful Congress Party boss, referring to the
1977 election loss. After 29 turbulent months, that government fell
apart and Congress returned to power.
   The centrist National Front alliance expressed confidence it
could form the next government.
   ``The people of India want a non-Congress government to replace
the corrupt and inefficient Congress government. It is therefore
the sacred duty of the National Front to respect this mandate,''
the National Front said in a statement read by its chief spokesman,
Dinesh Goswamy.
   The National Front said its new Parliament members would meet
Wednesday to select their choice for prime minister. Among the
leading candidates were three former Congress members: Vishwanath
Pratap Singh, Ramakrishna Hegde and Chandra Shekhar.
   The front's strategy is to opt for a minority government with
the tacit support of an array of parties ranging from the
Communists to Hindu fundamentalists.
   Opposition parties have been plagued by highly publicized
internal feuds. But they set aside their differences several months
ago to unite and oust Gandhi's government, alleging corruption and
ineptitude.
   Differences among the parties started to emerge Tuesday when the
right-wing India People's Party said it would not support any
government that included communist parties.
   With 473 of the 525 seats declared, the Congress Party and its
allies had 202 seats, according to state-run TV. Gandhi was ahead
in his own race for re-election to Parliament, leading by more than
135,000 votes over opponent Raj Mohan Gandhi, the grandson of
India's beloved independence leader Mohandas K. Gandhi.
   The National Front had 115 seats and the Indian People's Party
81. The Communist and leftist parties had 44.
   Together those seats would give the National Front and its
allies 240 spots, but the front could be hard-pressed to preserve
such an ideologically diverse group.
   The remaining seats were held by smaller, regional parties and
independent candidates. The winners included the father and the
widow of Beant Singh, one of the gunmen who killed Gandhi's mother
and predecessor, Indira Gandhi, and the man suspected of
masterminding her assassination.
   Seating of a new government began Monday night when President
Ramaswamy Venkataraman dissolved Parliament.
   The president normally would ask the party with the most seats
to try to form a government, but the constitution does not
specifically require this.
   Rather than rush into a coalition attempt of his own, however,
Gandhi appeared willing to wait to see whether the National Front
would founder in its efforts.
   ``The alliance, if any, will be ill-matched and bound to result
in a divorce sooner or later,'' said Murlidhar Bhandare, a Congress
Party lawmaker. The party was to meet Wednesday to elect a
parliamentary leader. That post and party president are separate,
although one person can hold both.
   Asked if Gandhi would offer to resign as party president because
of the election losses, party spokesman Sharma said: ``The question
does not arise. All party men have affirmed their full faith in
Gandhi's leadership.''
   Gandhi was swept into power in December 1984 on a wave of
sympathy following the assassination of his mother two months
earlier.
   But support for him declined in the face of allegations of
government corruption. Gandhi has denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
