<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0499,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Say They Found Cold Beer Beside Driver in Crash That Killed 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with trial recessed after defendant
breaks down again; more testimony; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Mahoney is ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of causing the nation's
worst drunken-driving disaster broke down in tears for a third day
as a coroner today described seeing the charred bodies inside a
church bus where 27 people died.
   Circuit Judge Charles Satterwhite ordered a recess after Larry
Mahoney began sobbing during county Coroner James B. Dunn's
testimony.
   ``I couldn't believe what I had seen,'' Dunn testified. ``I
thought I was having a nightmare.''
   Mahoney, 36, also broke into tears Monday as witnesses described
the screams and agony of the injured and dying. He also wept
earlier when the murder trial began last week.
   Dunn was describing what he saw when he entered the former
school bus shortly after the fiery 1988 crash on Interstate 71
south of Carrollton. He said about 17 children were sprawled in the
aisle and on seats in the rear of the bus.
   The bus, owned by Radcliff First Assembly of God Church, was
returning from an outing at an amusement park north of Cincinnati.
Sixty-three youngsters and four adults were aboard. Three adults
and 24 youngsters were killed.
   William Summers, Mahoney's lead attorney, said Monday that
``time will tell'' how Mahoney holds up when children who survived
the crash testify.
   In other testimony today, State Police Sgt. Jim Sharon compared
what he saw at the crash to carnage he witnessed in Vietnam.
   ``Bodies were black and charred, skin burned, and (emergency
medical technicians) were working on them,'' Sharon said of the
victims lying on a median strip.
   The first police officer to reach the accident testified Monday
that he found cold beer inside Mahoney's pickup, which rammed the
bus head-on while traveling the wrong way on the interstate.
   A paramedic also said the remainder of a 12-pack of Miller Lite
beer was still cold on the floor of the truck.
   Mahoney is charged with 27 counts of murder, 12 of assault, 42
of wanton endangerment and one of drunken driving.
   Robert Strong, a former state trooper, said he was the first
emergency official to reach the crash but couldn't get close enough
to help in a rescue.
   ``It was an intense _ you might say inferno,'' said Strong. ``I
was actually, verbally praying that there wasn't anyone left on the
bus.''
   Mahoney was still pinned in the cab of his pickup, an opened
12-pack of beer on the floor, Strong said.
   One can of beer was open, Strong said. He said he could feel two
other cans inside the carton, still cold.
   Tommy Webb, a paramedic, said he saw three cans of beer in the
crushed cab as he struggled to give first aid to Mahoney, who was
pinned by the crumpled dashboard.
   Jack Armstrong of Patriot, Ind., testified that he and his wife,
Joan, had seen Mahoney driving in the wrong lanes for about two
miles before the crash.
   ``My wife screamed, `Oh my God, that's a school bus,'' recalled
Armstrong, who like his wife was once a school bus driver.
