<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Kennedy     11-28 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Kennedy,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Visits Site of Brother's Famous Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BER5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy on Tuesday visited the
spot of his brother's famous speech denouncing the Berlin Wall, and
he said the barrier's opening will lead to the reunification of
Germany.
   He also laid two white lilies on the steps of West Berlin's
Schoeneberg City Hall, where President John F. Kennedy stood on
June 26, 1963, and declared: ``Ich bin ein Berliner,'' _ ``I am a
Berliner.''
   During a one-day visit, the Massachsetts Democrat also met in
West Berlin with East German opposition groups, including New
Forum. The West Berlin city government said the groups told Kennedy
that reforms in their homeland were being overshadowed by West
German-led debate on reunification.
   ``I think that is an inevitable course of history,'' Kennedy
said after crossing briefly into East Berlin for talks with
Lutheran church leaders. ``The question of timing and the rest ...
these are questions that really have to be determined by the people
in these communities.''
   Kennedy also laid flowers at the Reichstag in East Berlin in
tribute to the more than 80 people killed trying to escape after
East Germany built the wall in 1961.
   East German border guards stared silently as the senator walked
alongside the wall and looked at spots where souvenir hunters have
chipped away pieces of concrete.
   East Germany, bowing to a citizens uprising demanding reforms,
lifted travel restrictions and opened the wall and other borders on
Nov. 9.
   In a welcoming ceremony at Schoeneberg City Hall, Kennedy said:
``I come here today, on behalf of my family and country, on a
journey of memory and hope.''
   ``You have opened the way to a new world of freedom,'' he said.
``Today, in that world of freedom, the proudest boast is `Ich bin
ein Berliner.''''
   He was flanked by former West German Chancellor Willy Brandt,
who as West Berlin mayor accompanied President Kennedy in 1963.
   ``The peaceful men and women moving by the thousands through
Checkpoint Charlie are at the center of the greatest march of
liberty of modern times _ and perhaps of all time,'' the senator
said.
   ``Many assumed the concrete could never be breached, the stones
never thrown down, the Iron Curtain never lifted. Lass sie nach
Berlin kommen. Let them come to Berlin,'' he added, echoing his
brother's words once again.
   Many West Berlin residents remember John F. Kennedy's words
fondly, and the city has honored the slain president with a plaque
at city hall.
</TEXT>
