<HEAD>Hafer Announces Candidacy For Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania Auditor General Barbara Hafer
has joined the ranks of announced candidates seeking the Republican
nomination for governor in 1990.
   The former registered nurse, who has had a 13-year political
career, made her formal announcement Monday at a rally in her
hometown, a Pittsburgh suburb.
   As a nurse, she said, she learned to take a pulse and she has
done the same with public sentiment. ``Pennsylvania wants a new
choice, a new leader, a better way of doing things,'' she said.
   Incumbent Democratic Gov. Robert P. Casey is expected to seek
re-election but has not made an announcement.
   The Republican State Committee meets Saturday to endorse a
candidate for the May primary. Also seeking backing are James O.
Pickard of Lancaster, a commerce secretary in Gov. Dick
Thornburgh's Cabinet, and former state Rep. John Kennedy of
suburban Harrisburg.
   Hafer, 46, already has the support of top Republican Party
leaders, including U.S. Sens. John Heinz and Arlen Specter.
   Party conservatives say she is too liberal, and they especially
dislike her pro-choice stand on abortion, an issue some observers
think will be a key in the contest.
