<HEAD>Irate Woman Holds Shotgun On Daughter's Eighth-Grade Class</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLOSTER, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An irate woman allegedly held her
daughter's eighth-grade class at gunpoint for 20 minutes, claiming
her daughter had been harassed by boys at the school.
   No one was injured in Monday's incident at Gloster Elementary
School in southwest Mississippi.
   Roxie W. Monk, 36, surrendered to police and was being held in
lieu of $5,000 bail Tuesday on a charge of aggravated assault,
officials said.
   Officers said Monk held a loaded shotgun on teacher Lee Anderson
and about 30 students, trying to find the boys bothering her
14-year-old daughter and make them leave her alone.
   Amite County Sheriff Gerald Wall said one boy reportedly stood
during the incident, admitted to harrassing Monk's daughter and
apologized.
   Police Officer Tom Poster took the gun from the woman, whom he
described as ``upset, but not hysterical.''
   ``I opened the door (to the classroom) and stepped in. She was
standing right inside the door and I just took the gun out of her
hands,'' Poster said. ``She didn't resist.''
