<FIRST>r a AM-TridentProtest     11-28 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trident Protest,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenpeace Says It Will Protest Missile Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-nuclear activists from
Greenpeace USA will try to halt the launch of a Trident 2 missile
from a submarine off the Florida coast, which they said is
scheduled Friday, a spokeswoman said Tuesday.
   ``Coming on the eve of the Mediterranean summit, this test is a
slap in the face to the world's hopes and expectations for
meaningful arms reductions,'' said Greenpeace spokeswoman Shannon
Fagan.
   President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev meet
Saturday and Sunday off the island of Malta in the Mediterranean.
   The Navy refused to confirm or deny that it planned a Trident 2
launch Friday.
   Greenpeace was successful in stopping a Trident 2 test from the
nuclear submarine Tennessee last July 28, maneuvering small Zodiac
rafts close enough to the sub to attach ``Nuclear Free Seas'' flags
to its hull and mast.
   The anti-nuclear activists left the area, declaring they had
made their point that the Trident 2 should be eliminated as a
weapons system, and the Navy was able to launch the missile five
days later.
   That was the only success in three submarine test-launches. The
other two ended in explosions just seconds after the missiles
cleared the ocean surface.
   In Washington, a government source said the Bush administration
might delay the test until after the summit. ``Discussions are
going on as to whether to delay it until after Malta,'' said one
source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Trident 2, at $26.5 million a copy, is designed to replace
the Trident 1 submarine-launched ballistic missiles. Each
44-foot-long, three-stage Trident 2 can deliver as many as 12
nuclear warheads to individual targets up to 6,000 miles away.
</TEXT>
