<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Husak     11-28 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Husak,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Silent While Nation is in Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The white, gold and red flag atop Hradcany castle
indicates the president is in town.
   But since a peaceful, countrywide revolt against Communist rule,
no word has been heard from the head of a state that is swept by
crisis.
   At 76, Gustav Husak must be a bitter man in the sprawling castle
that dominates Prague and was the seat of an empire 600 years ago.
   He was stripped of his seat in the Communist Party's ruling
Politburo on Friday. He has been the target of derisive jeers from
hundreds of thousands, and he must be aware of growing popular
demands that the man he once called a ``traitor'' replace him.
   The name most often chanted by demonstrators as their favorite
to succeed him is that of Alexander Dubcek, the best-known figure
in the short-lived ``Prague Spring'' of 1968 that was turned into
winter by a Moscow-led invasion.
   Husak, himself a one-time victim of Stalinist purges in the
1950s returned from oblivion in 1968, rising to the post deputy
premier.
   But he steered a cautious middle course between Dubcek's
reformers and the conservative elements in the party. Such tactics
were rewarded by Leonid I. Brezhnev, the Soviet leader who had
ordered the invasion.
   Unlike Dubcek and his closest associates, Husak never was
summoned to Moscow following the invasion. And he missed, allegedly
for lack of transport and communications, taking part in an
emergency Communist Party congress that branded the invasion
illegal.
   Only once does he seem to have been carried away by the wave of
nationalism in the country after the Soviet tanks rolled into
Prague. ``I stand and fall with Dubcek,'' he stated, words cited
ever since by his critics.
   Dubcek was allowed by the Soviets to hang on until April 1969
but then Husak replaced him as party chief. In 1975 he became
president of Czechoslovakia as well, capping an ambition-filled
career.
   Since then, Husak was twice re-elected, with his third term due
to end in June 1990.
   After Dubcek, whom he had expelled from the party in 1970,
criticized the new leadership, Husak publicly denounced him as a
``traitor of communism and Czechoslovakia.''
   Dubcek was never arrested or charged. Some credit Husak for
that, saying he recalled the nine years he spent in jail on
political charges.
   For many years, Dubcek remained in seclusion, employed by the
forestry service in Slovakia, the native state of both himself and
Husak. But last week, he rose from oblivion, addressing giant
pro-democracy demonstrations in Prague where hundreds of thousands
chanted his name.
   ``Dubcek to the castle,'' they shouted. Another slogan,
addressed to Gustav Husak , was ``Gustl, look what a big crowd we
are.''
   ``Dubcek had nothing new to say,'' said Martin Palous, a member
of the Civic Forum opposition group. ``It was just the old jargon
when he spoke. But as president he would be an important symbolic
link between the past and the future.''
   On the vast, but almost empty square in front of Hradcany
Castle, groups of Soviet and Yugoslav tourists were told of the
building's history.
   A Czech who carried the tricolor ribbon identifying him as a
sympathizer of the pro-democracy movement, said: ``Husak? He is
old, he can hardly walk, he had a stroke. And he will be out soon.''
   ``Can you in the West imagine that a president keeps silent at a
moment like this ?,'' asked Roman Polak, a fellow supporter of
reform.
   Asked whether he had heard of Husak recently, Polak shook his
head.
   ``Everything (is) normal up there,'' he said, pointing to the
castle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
