<FIRST>r a AM-GroundedShip     11-28 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grounded Ship,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil-Leaking Cargo Ship to Remain Grounded in Bering Sea Until Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek cargo ship that ran aground and
spewed more than 237,000 gallons of fuel and oil into the Bering
Sea will remain there until spring because it is too dangerous to
move it.
   Until then no attempt will be made to remove the 140,000 gallons
of oil still in the ship's tanks, despite the threat of more
leakage if winter storms and icing further damage the ship,
officials said Monday.
   Coast Guard Capt. Richard Asaro, the federal cleanup
coordinator, also said no spill cleanup or rescue of oiled birds
will be attempted. The remote location, temperatures in the low
20s, strong winds and seas swelling eight to 15 feet make such
efforts too dangerous, he said.
   On Sunday, a diver surveying damage to the ship's hull was
trapped briefly in a depression on the sea floor when the 485-foot
Milos Reefer rolled to one side, Asaro said. About five minutes
later, however, the ship rolled to the other side and freed diver
John Whitekettle, who was unhurt, Asaro said.
   Asaro said the two Coast Guard vessels at the site will remain
just long enough for officials to complete their survey.
   The ship ran aground Nov. 14 on a reef off St. Matthew Island in
the Bering Sea National Wildlife Refuge 400 miles west of Bethel.
The cause of the grounding remains under investigation.
   The weather improved enough during the weekend to allow
officials to board the ship and determine how much oil remained.
   Asaro said that of 237,343 gallons that leaked, about 170,000
was intermediate fuel oil and the rest was diesel. Environmental
officials are most concerned about the fuel oil, which has the
consistency of molasses.
   Bruce Erickson, western Alaska supervisor for the state
Department of Environmental Quality, said the fuel oil is washing
up on beaches and poses a threat to marine life, including the
area's blue crab population.
   Most of what remains on board the ship is fuel oil, about
112,000 gallons. The rest, about 29,000 gallons, are various
lubrication oils used to run the ship, Asaro said.
   ``There is still some occasional leakage,'' he said. ``We're
talking a sheen as distinct from slicks.''
   Erickson said a coat of oil 20 feet wide and four to five inches
deep is spread along about a mile of the island beach. Four oiled
bird carcasses were found on the beach, while sea lions and a fox
seen on the island appeared unaffected, he said. Overall there
appeared to be little wildlife in the area.
   Pack ice, which forms over that area of the Bering Sea by
mid-January, could move and further damage the ship, trapping any
additional oil that leaks. That would pose a lingering threat to
the island's birds, most of which probably will return in the
spring before the ice melts, Erickson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0120 </DOCNO>
