<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Editor     11-28 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Editor,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalist Gets 3 Years for Slander, Resisting Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of an unofficial Siberian journal was
sentenced to three years in a labor camp Tuesday, activists said,
in a case that has drawn the attention of Andrei D. Sakharov and
other human rights campaigners.
   Sergei Kuznetsov was found guilty of slandering a local Interior
Ministry official and resisting arrest in the Siberian city of
Sverdlovsk, said Andrei Mironov, a Moscow-based journalist and
human rights activist.
   Human rights activists say the charges were trumped up to
silence Kuznetsov, 32.
   He is editor of his own unofficial journal as well as a
contributor to some of the best-known non-official publications
that have sprung up in Moscow in the freer atmosphere of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   Mironov said the trial showed that despite Gorbachev's reforms
that freed hundreds of political prisoners, ``the system of
repression has been preserved.''
   Kuznetsov attended his trial lying down because of a prolonged
hunger strike against the accusations, Mironov said.
   Several weeks ago, Moscow activists quoted Kuznetsov's lawyer as
saying the editor had been pushed down a flight of stairs at the
Sverdlovsk courthouse by police after a court hearing.
   Sakharov and other human rights activists issued a protest after
that, and Mironov on Tuesday quoted the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize
winner as saying he could not support an international human rights
conference in the Soviet Union in 1991 if Kuznetsov was imprisoned.
</TEXT>
