<FIRST>u w AM-FBI-DrugTesting     11-28 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Drug Testing,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI to Begin Random Drug Testing of Employees Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William S. Sessions told the
bureau's employees that random testing for possible use of illegal
drugs may begin early next year, the bureau said Tuesday.
   Sessions informed the bureau's 9,700 agents and nearly 13,000
support personnel of the random testing program in a notice dated
Nov. 14, said FBI spokesman Mike Kortan.
   The random testing is expected to begin sometime after Jan. 14,
Kortan said.
   Under the plan, a computer program will be used to randomly
select the names of employees who will be required to undergo urine
testing to determine if they have used illegal drugs, Kortan said.
   Employees who test positive for illegal drug use could be
suspended or dismissed from their jobs but ``each case would be
evaluated individually in the context of all the circumstances,''
Kortan said.
   Refusal to provide a urine sample would also result in
disciplinary action that could include dismissal, he said.
   The random testing at the FBI is being started under a 1986
executive order by President Reagan to kick off his initiative for
a drug-free workplace.
   A number of federal agencies have instituted similar programs,
which have met with mixed reviews in court decisions resulting from
lawsuits filed by affected employees.
   The Justice Department is seeking Supreme Court review of an
appellate court decision that restricted testing of career lawyers
in Washington to those with access to top-secret information. Those
lawyers, in turn, have asked the high court to review the same
decision by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here.
   So far, no Justice Department attorney has been tested under the
program unveiled in 1988. But the department recently began testing
job applicants, said department spokeswoman Amy Brown.
   Since 1986, the bureau has tested FBI job applicants for drug
use. In 1987, the bureau began testing new agents during their
one-year probationary period, Kortan said.
   In addition, the bureau tests volunteers as well as employees
suspected of illegal drug use.
   As of Nov. 21, 9,540 employees or applicants were tested and
only 34 showed evidence of drug use, Koran said. Figures on the
number of employees dismissed as a result of positive tests were
not available, Kortan said.
   Sessions also announced that he had established a program to
assist all employees with substance abuse, Kortan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     11-28 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thanksgiving `Tune Out' Bad for NBC, Good for ABC</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC can thank the Thanksgiving holiday for
putting ``Roseanne'' back in first place in the Nielsen television
ratings for the week ended Nov. 26.
   ``Roseanne'' was first and ``The Wonder Years'' was second as
NBC's strongest night, Thursday, suffered from holiday tune out.
``Coach,'' which made its debut behind ``Roseanne'' in place of
``Chicken Soup,'' tied for eighth place.
   No NBC Thursday show made the Top 10. ``Cheers'' was 13th and a
rerun of ``The Cosby Show,'' first in recent weeks, was 14th.
``L.A. Law'' tied for 17th, ``A Different World'' tied for 22nd and
``Dear John'' tied for 25th.
   Although NBC had only two shows in the Top 10, ``Empty Nest''
and ``The Golden Girls,'' it still won the week. Viewership for the
entire week was down by about 2 million households.
   NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey with an average of
13.8. The previous week NBC had an average of 16.0. ABC was second
with 12.9 and CBS was third with 12.3. The ratings represents the
percentage of the nation's 92.1 million television households tuned
to a show.
   Here are the Top 10: ABC's ``Roseanne''; ABC's ``The Wonder
Years''; CBS' ``60 Minutes''; ABC's ``Who's the Boss?''; NBC's
``The Golden Girls''; NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and CBS' ``Murder, She
Wrote'' tied; CBS National League Football Sunday overrun and ABC's
``Coach'' tied; ABC's ``America's Funniest Home Videos''; and ABC's
NFL Monday Night Football, tied.
   NBC leads in both the season-to-date ratings and in the November
sweeps. In the first 10 weeks of the season, NBC is ahead with
15.0, ABC is second with 13.5 and CBS is third with 12.4.
   Here are the ratings for the sweeps: Arbitron (another ratings
service) for 26 days, NBC 15.0, ABC 12.8, CBS 12.0. Nielsen for 25
days, NBC 15.1, ABC 12.6, CBS 12.1.
   The CBS special ``50 Years of Television'' was in 27th place for
the week.
   ABC and CBS tied for first place among the evening news shows,
which also had a loss of viewers because of the holiday. ABC and
CBS registered a rating of 10.0, while NBC had 9.3
   The lowest rated show of the week was ABC's ``PrimeTime Live.''
The five bottom network shows were: CBS' ``Grammys' Living
Legends,'' NBC's ``Sister Kate,'' ABC's ``Living Dolls,'' ABC's
``Mission: Impossible'' and ``PrimeTime Live.''
