<FIRST>r a AM-PreschoolMolest     11-28 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Preschool Molest,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Has One Verdict, Deadlocked on One, Still Debating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the 2{-year-old McMartin preschool
molestation trial returned one verdict under seal Tuesday but
indicated they are deadlocked on one of the 65 molestation counts
against two defendants.
   ``They've said only that they've taken several ballots and
cannot reach a verdict on a count,'' said Superior Court Judge
William Pounders. ``Given the fact there are 65 counts, that is not
too significant.''
   Raymond Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 63,
are charged with conspiracy and child molestation at their
family-owned preschool in Manhattan Beach. Their trial is the
longest in U.S. history and has cost Los Angeles County over $15
million.
   Jurors have been deliberating since Nov. 2.
   The judge has instructed the jurors to give him each verdict,
once it is final, sealed in an envelope. He said he would begin
reading the verdicts as early as next week even if all 65 charges
had not been decided.
   The jury's predicament came to light when they sent a note to
the judge asking if a deadlock should be submitted as a sealed
verdict.
   Pounders told the jurors they should not seal any non-decision.
   ``You do give us only the final decisions you make, the
unanimous decisions,'' he said.
   The panelists then returned to their jury deliberation room, and
within about two minutes they buzzed for the court clerk who
returned with a single verdict they had given him to seal in an
envelope.
   The unusual process, the judge said, is warranted by the unique
nature of the case. Pounders has been worried that at least one
juror may drop out of the deliberations before all of the charges
are resolved. Since there are no alternates remaining, that would
result in a mistrial on the unresolved matters.
   ``We have an unusual circumstance because we have 65 verdicts to
take,'' he said. ``Taking them one at a time is an insane process.
But waiting for all of them is just as insane because we may lose a
key juror before that time and thus lose all of those verdicts.''
</TEXT>
