<FIRST>r a AM-SeditionTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0647 11-28 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sedition Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0647,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Takes Up Racketeering Charges in Trial of Three Radicals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with jury retiring without reaching
a verdict, defense attorney quote. Picks up 2nd graf, `While clearing....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury deliberating
racketeering charges that remain against three people it acquitted
of conspiring to overthrow the U.S. government went home Tuesday
without reaching consensus.
   Attorneys said they didn't know how to interpret the apparent
deadlock.
   ``The only thing I am sure of is they'll be back at 9 a.m.,''
said defense attorney William Newman.
   While clearing Raymond Levasseur, his wife, Patricia Gros
Levasseur, and Richard Williams of seditious conspiracy charges,
jurors indicated Monday that they seriously doubted they could
reach agreement on the racketeering counts in the yearlong trial.
   U.S. District Judge William Young, who Monday urged jurors to
try again, made little comment as he sent the jurors Tuesday to
their 20th day of deliberations. Once they were out of the
courtroom, however, he said he would consider a motion for a
mistrial if the jury remains deadlocked.
   Young said if the government then requests a new trial, it would
be held in Boston and probably would be much shorter.
   Jurors have cleared Mrs. Levasseur of racketeering and were
deciding the same charge against the two men as well as a charge of
racketeering conspiracy against all three. Each count carries a
maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and $20,000 in fines.
   Prosecutors suggested that a request jurors made Tuesday to
review defense testimony by corporate executives indicated they
mistakenly believe each act in the indictment has to be proven as
affecting interstate commerce.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Loucks has failed to persuade
the judge to give the jury a clarification about the federal
racketeering law. It requires proving a criminal enterprise as a
whole affects interstate commerce, which could simply mean that it
buys goods in more than one state.
   The government has maintained that the defendants were part of a
group operating under the names United Freedom Front and Sam
Melville-Jonathan Jackson Unit that they said took responsibility
for a string of bombings and bank robberies along the East Coast
from 1976 to 1984.
   Originally, eight people were indicted, but only three are left
in the trial, which was moved from Boston to Springfield.
   Levasseur and Williams already are serving lengthy terms as a
result of separate trials in some of the bombings. Patricia
Levasseur is free on bail after serving 3{ years of a five-year
term for harboring a fugitive, her husband.
   The Springfield prosecution was intended to pull the case
together through racketeering laws that allow several people to be
tried for incidents occurring in several states.
   The racketeering charges include 15 successful or attempted
bombings of courthouses, banks, corporate offices and military
recruiting and reserve centers. One of the bombings, at the Suffolk
County Courthouse in Boston in April 1976, left one man with his
leg severed below the knee, but some of the other devices failed to
explode.
   Of the seven defendants at the time of the initial jury
selection in March 1988, prosecutors dropped charges against two, a
third pleaded guilty to sedition and other charges, and charges
were dropped against a fourth after a judge suppressed evidence
seized at her house.
</TEXT>
