<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Israel     11-28 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Israel,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland, Israel to Establish Diplomatic Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland will restore full diplomatic
relations with Israel next year, a government spokesman said
Tuesday, and Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki said later he would
like to visit the Jewish state.
   Mazowiecki said he was invited to Israel by Israeli Vice Premier
Shimon Peres, who is on the second day of a three-day visit to
Poland.
   Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski on Monday informed Peres
of Warsaw's decision to restore relations broken off 22 years ago,
said Foreign Ministry spokesman Stefan Staniszewski.
   ``The resumption of relations can take place in the first
quarter of next year,'' Staniszewski said. After the meeting with
Peres, Mazowiecki said the date for the resumption of relations is
not yet fixed.
   Except for Romania, all Warsaw Pact nations severed diplomatic
relations with Israel following the 1967 Middle East War.
   Hungary on Sept. 18 became the first Warsaw Pact country to
restore relations. Poland has had low-level ties since 1986,
allowing Israel to maintain a diplomatic office in Warsaw, while
the Soviet Union renewed low-level relations last year.
   Mazowiecki expressed Poland's will to resume relations with
Israel in an address to parliament after his election as the East
bloc's first non-communist leader Aug. 24.
   Mazowiecki said Peres had invited him to visit Israel and that
he ``would very much like to be in Israel for many reasons.''
   Relations between the two countries have improved steadily in
recent years with senior Israeli and Polish officials, cultural
figures and private groups exchanging visits. Israel's El Al
Airlines recently established regular service between Warsaw and
Tel Aviv.
   Mazowiecki said his talks with Peres were ``sincere and very
deep. We touched on the history of Polish-Jewish relations our
spiritual roots.''
   Poland had the largest Jewish population in Eastern Europe until
the Holocaust claimed 3 million of Poland's 3.5 million Jews during
World War II, with nearly all the rest emigrating after the war.
   Peres, born in the Polish town of Vishneva, now part of the
Soviet Union, is the highest-ranking Israeli official to visit
Poland since relations were severed.
   He arrived in Warsaw on Monday for a three-day visit aimed at
developing cooperation between Israel and Poland.
   Peres said he planned to discuss agricultural aid, industrial
cooperation and perhaps cooperation in the Third World with Polish
officials. He met President Wojciech Jaruzelski and Leszek
Balcerowicz, the minister of finance, at the start of the visit.
   Polish trade with Israel will amount to $40 million this year,
compared with $22.3 million last year, the official PAP news agency
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
