<FIRST>r i AM-WarsawPact     11-28 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warsaw Pact,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Ministers Meet In Budapest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense ministers from the seven Warsaw
Pact countries Tuesday opened a three-day meeting to update their
defense policies in light of improved East-West relations,
Hungary's defense minister said.
   At the opening session, Defense Minister Ferenc Karpati said the
ministers would ``put forward and discuss five important and
topical issue that serve the modernization of the joint armed
forces and their defensive doctrine,'' the state MTI news agency
reported.
   In his address to the meeting, also attended by Soviet Gen.
Piotr Lushev, the Warsaw Pact chief commander, Karpati praised the
easing of East-West relations which he attributed to greater
flexibility of the Soviet leadership and the change in Western
attitudes, MTI said.
   ``The new security policy concept and statements of principle of
the socialist countries should be reinforced not only from the
political side of doctrines but also from military-technical
aspects,'' MTI quoted Karpati as saying.
   It was the second meeting of the Soviet bloc's defense chiefs
following a disarmament plan announced in December 1988 by Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev for the unilateral withdrawal of
500,000 troops by the end of 1990.
   This includes the pullout of 50,000 Soviet troops and 5,000
tanks from Eastern Europe.
   At an East bloc summit in Romania last summer, the Soviet Union
and its allies signed an agreement to seek a nuclear-free Europe
with significantly fewer soldiers and arms.
   Gorbachev said then that the accord contained the Warsaw Pact's
answer to President Bush's May 29 proposal for reductions in
conventional forces. Bush called for cuts in U.S. and Soviet troops
in Europe outside the Soviet Union to 275,000 soldiers each, and
for reductions in weapons and combat aircraft.
   Karpati said an agreement at the East-West talks on conventional
disarmament in Vienna ``requires profound changes in the doctrines
of both NATO and the Warsaw Treaty,'' MTI reported.
</TEXT>
