<FIRST>r a AM-ClemencyDenied     11-28 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clemency Denied,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prejean To Die For Cop Killing, Governor Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer on Tuesday rejected
the recommendation of the Louisiana Pardon Board and refused to
halt the execution of a man convicted of killing two men before he
was 18.
   Dalton Prejean, now 30, is to die early Thursday for the 1977
murder of state Trooper Donald Cleveland.
   Roemer acted shortly after the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeal
threw out the latest of Prejean's numerous appeals, rejecting,
among other things, claims that he is retarded and a victim of
racial discrimination.
   Andrea Robinson, one of Prejean's attorneys, said she would go
to the U.S. Supreme Court, which has twice refused to hear his
appeals.
   The Pardon Board voted 3-2 Monday to recommend reducing the
death sentence to life in prison for Prejean, who killed Cleveland
six months after being released from a juvenile institution where
he was sent at age 14 for the murder of a taxi driver.
   The majority of the board voted for clemency based on testimony
that Prejean had been abused as a child, that he probably suffered
some brain damage as a child, that he had a good prison record and
showed remorse, board Chairwoman Yvonne Foreman said.
   Roemer said he talked with defense attorneys and witnesses and
studied the decision of the pardon board.
   ``With a handgun he shot three times a state trooper in the
chest and face and killed him,'' Roemer said at a news conference.
``It was not his first murder.''
   Roemer noted the background of abuse as a child and reduced
intelligence, but added that ``standards of age, of intelligence,
meet those standards set forth by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   ``And finally, I would say there is a special circumstance in my
position, to have a state trooper in the line of duty in uniform to
be brutally and maliciously murdered.''
   Prejean and his brother had been drinking, left a bar in their
car and were stopped by Cleveland. Prejean said the trooper
manhandled his brother and that he feared for his brother's life.
   In appeals, defense lawyers pointed to evidence that Prejean had
an I.Q. of 76 and that, according to a psychiatrist, he performed
on tests ``at a level of borderline retardation.''
   But the three-judge 5th Circuit panel said that neither
Prejean's limited mental ability nor his age at the time of the
crime constituted reasons to reverse the death sentence.
   ``Prejean is not `mentally retarded' as that term is defined by
the American Association on Mental Retardation as one with an I.Q.
of 70 or below,'' wrote Chief Judge Charles Clark.
   The 5th Circuit also rejected arguments that the execution
should be stopped because Prejean, who is black, had an all-white
jury, saying lawyers failed to prove blacks were eliminated from
the jury in a discriminatory manner.
   Prejean was sent to prison in March 1980 and has been on death
row longer than any of the other 35 condemned men. He has had eight
stays of execution in the last 10 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
