<HEAD>Pope's Assailant Says He Could Lead Islamic World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mehmet Ali Agca, who tried to kill Pope
John Paul II in 1981, now says he could lead the Moslem world if he
decided to take up politics, the Istanbul newspaper Sabah reported.
   ``The quality and belief of a Moslem is in his heart. ... You
have to know that if I get into politics one day I can become the
leader of the Islamic World, because I am a true Moslem,'' it
quoted the Turkish gunman as saying in an interview, published in
installments Sunday through Tuesday.
   Agca shot and wounded John Paul on May 18, 1981, in St. Peter's
Square and is serving a life term in a prison at Ascoli Piceno, 85
miles northeast of Rome, where he was interviewed.
   He first said he had acted alone, but later claimed Bulgarian
agents had planned the attack with Soviet help. In 1986, three
Turks and three Bulgarians were acquitted of involvement.
   A life sentence really means 30 years in Italy and Agca could be
paroled in the year 2001. Agca said he wanted to live in a country
that would accept him after his parole, and ``if Italy allows me to
stay I want to stay here. ''
   ``In fact I want to return to Turkey, but this is impossible,''
Sabah quoted him as saying.
   A Turkish court condemned Agca to death, in absentia, for
killing Abdi Ipekci, editor of the daily Milliyet, in 1979. He was
arrested in June 1979 and confessed, but escaped from prison before
the year was out.
