<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-28 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parts Of The South Get A Soaking, Temperatures Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell across the South on Tuesday along the leading edge of
cold air washing in from the Arctic, and parts of southern
California were buffetted by high wind.
   A cold front ushered cold dry air into the northeastern part of
the nation and showers and thunderstorms developed along that
curving front from northern Georgia across the central Gulf Coast
region.
   Enough rain fell at New Orleans during the morning to push the
city's rainfall total for the month to nearly 20 inches. That not
only exceeds the previous November record of 14.58 inches, set in
1947, but also surpasses the previous record for any month of the
year _ 19.09 inches in March 1948.
   During the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 0.92 of an inch of rain
fell at Mobile, Ala., and 1.44 inches fell at New Orleans.
   The northwesterly wind produced snow squalls in the Great Lakes
region, with 6 to 8 inches possible in snowbelt areas of Michigan.
Heavy snow blanketed parts of northern Michigan late Monday with 7
inches reported at Marquette and Gwinn.
   Also late Monday, thunderstorms that developed along and ahead
of the cold front produced damaging wind in Michigan, indiana and
Ohio.
   Strong, gusty Santa Ana wind blew across parts of southern
California. Wind gusted to 51 mph at Sandberg, Calif., and a truck
on the Cajon Pass was reportedly blown over by wind, the National
Weather Service said.
   Snow that fell over northern New England during the night
diminished during the morning or changed to light rain and drizzle.
   Warm weather continued ahead of the cold front in parts of the
East. Temperatures warmed into the 70s across the Southeast, and in
the 80s over the Florida Peninsula, and the middle Atlantic states
reached the 60s.
   But behind the front, strong northwesterly wind brought cold
arctic air and afternoon temperatures were generally still below
freezing from eastern Montana through the middle and upper
Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes, and only in the single
digits across Minnesota, eastern North Dakota, northeastern South
Dakota and northwestern Wisconsin.
   From Monday night into Tuesday morning, readings below zero were
reported in parts of Nevada, Wyoming, Colorado, North Dakota, South
Dakota and Minnesota.
   Tuesday's low for the Lower 48 states was 12 below zero at
Gunnison, Colo., and Warroad, Minn.
</TEXT>
