<FIRST>u i AM-AbuNidal     11-28 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abu Nidal,0821</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Officials Say Terrorist Abu Nidal Under Medical Supervision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian master terrorist Abu Nidal is
under medical supervision at his home in Libya after recurrence of
a heart ailment, but his life is in no immediate danger, two senior
PLO officials said Tuesday.
   The officials, interviewed separately by telephone from
Palestine Liberation Organization headquarters in Tunis, Tunisia's
capital, called ``inaccurate'' reports from Algeria that Abu Nidal
was dying of cancer.
   They also denied reports he was under house arrest.
   Abu Nidal, 52, tops U.S., European and Asian most wanted lists.
His henchmen stand accused of killing nearly 1,000 people, most of
them civilians, in attacks around the world.
   An Algerian medical source who recently returned home from Libya
said Abu Nidal _ real name Sabri al-Banna _ ``is in a military
hospital in Libya suffering from a cancerous metastase that is
probably terminal.''
   A metastase is cancerous tissue that spreads the disease
throughout the body.
   ``It's not cancer. It's his heart,'' said one of the PLO
officials, who insisted on anonymity. ``He has been bedridden for
two weeks.''
   The PLO sources said their information was based on reports from
``reliable'' Libyan security officials.
   The other official said Abu Nidal complained of chest pains for
weeks, and Libyan physicians initially attributed it to ``mere
exhaustion.''
   But he said the terrorist began complaining of breathing
difficulties, ``prompting doctors to confine him to bed after he
refused to be taken to a hospital.''
   Dissidents reported this month that Abu Nidal had become
``increasingly paranoid'' after a bloody split in the ranks of his
Fatah-Revolutionary Council in which at least 200 activists died.
   They said he never leaves his home in a fenced training base on
the outskirts of Tripoli. He has lived in Libya since Syria
expelled him in 1987.
   The New York Times reported in Tuesday's editions that Libyan
leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi, under pressure to rein in the terror
network that damaged the Palestinian crusade for statehood, had put
Abu Nidal under house arrest.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said in
Washington Tuesday, ``We don't know'' if Abu Nidal was under house
arrest.
   ``One report today has that he has cancer and is in a
hospital,'' she said. ``We don't know. One report has that he's
arrested. We just ... don't know.''
   The PLO officials said Abu Nidal underwent open-heart surgery in
Bulgaria in 1984.
   ``But doctors reported only 70 percent success after the double
bypass operation. ... He has had one or two mild heart problems,
but nothing too serious,'' one source said.
   He said the latest setback ``may be more complicated because of
the physical, mental and psychological stress he's been under'' _ a
reference to the split in Abu Nidal's organization.
   Abu Nidal gained popularity among the frustrated youth of
Palestinian refugee camps in Lebanon after the 1982 Israeli
invasion.
   His group grew that year from 300 to about 1,000 young men
pledged to an armed struggle against Israel.
   But later, many followers began questioning the link between
terrorist attacks they were ordered to undertake and the liberation
of their homeland.
   Complaints increased after a puzzling alliance that Abu Nidal
struck in 1985 with Hezbollah, or the Party of God. Abu Nidal
preaches Maoism. Hezbollah is a pro-Iranian fundamentalist Moslem
group in Lebanon.
   Abu Nidal was born in Jaffa in 1937, the 14th child of a
prominent landowner, and taught school in Jerusalem. He joined
Fatah, the mainstream PLO faction, after leaving for Saudi Arabia
following the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
   He is married and has at least two children, a son and a
daughter. A short, stocky, balding man, the elusive Abu Nidal
seldom appears in public or gives interviews.
   He reportedly played a leading role in the massacre of Israeli
athletes at the 1972 Olympic Games in Munich, West Germany.
   Abu Nidal, whose war name means ``father of the struggle'' in
Arabic, split from Fatah in early 1973 with another officer, Ahmed
Abdul-Ghaffour.
   That August they killed five people and wounded 55 in a grenade
and pistol attack at Athens airport. PLO chairman Yasser Arafat
publicly said then that the two must be sought and executed.
   Ghaffour was killed a month later. Abu Nidal pledged to kill
Arafat, blaming him for Ghaffour's death.
   Abu Nidal gunmen proceeded to kill at least 16 top aides of
Arafat in Europe and the Middle East.
   Notorious attacks by Abu Nidal's terrorists included the
November 1985 hijacking of an Egyptian airliner to Malta in which
59 people died; twin raids on Rome and Vienna airports that killed
20 people on Dec. 27, 1985; and a Pan Am jet hijacking in Karachi,
Pakistan, in September 1986 that killed 21 people.
</TEXT>
