<FIRST>r w AM-GeneralAviation-Military     11-28 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-General Aviation-Military,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Aviation Industry Official: Use Military Airports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon should consider moving military
units out of bases in highly populated areas to make room for
increased civilian aviation, a general aviation industry official
proposed Tuesday.
   ``Some would say that this is a radical and unrealistic
suggestion,'' said Max E. Bleck, chairman of Beech Aircraft Corp.
``But, until a few weeks ago, anyone who suggested that East
Germany would punch holes in the Berlin Wall would have been called
radical and unrealistic,'' said Bleck.
   Bleck said units at bases in highly populated and congested
areas could be moved to bases the Defense Department is closing in
less populous areas.
   Both Bleck, who also is chairman of the General Aviation
Manufacturers Association, and Edward W. Stimpson, the
organization's president, called for increased civilian use of
military airports. They addressed an aviation industry meeting.
   Transportation officials estimate that the demand for commercial
aviation will double in the next 10 years, while it will take
longer than that for any new airports to be approved and built.
   Bleck said President Bush and the secretaries of Defense and
Transportation should draw up a plane for the civilian use of
nonstrategic military airfields around the country.
   Stimpson said the new spirit of cooperation between the United
States and the Soviet Union and potential defense cutbacks could
lead to unemployment in defense industries. But he said a
resurgence of general aviation could supply thousands of jobs to
trained workers.
</TEXT>
