<FIRST>u a AM-SexualPredators     11-28 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sexual Predators,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor's Committee Takes Aim At Sexual Predators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   SEA-TAC, Wash. (AP) _ Sex offenders would get sentences of up to
life in prison and be required to register with the police under
recommendations of a state task force formed after two shocking sex
crimes.
   Gov. Booth Gardner endorsed the recommendations
``unequivocally'' on Tuesday, and the measures are expected to sail
through the Legislature after it convenes on Jan. 8.
   The panel's recommendations came after months of public hearings
in which residents recounted family tragedies at the hands of
sexual predators. The families also complained about a corrections
system they contended could not protect them from habitual
criminals.
   The panel was spurred by the sexual mutilation of a Tacoma boy
in May and the rape and murder of a Seattle businesswoman nine
months earlier.
   During the committee's work, three boys in Vancouver and
Portland, Ore., were slain, allegedly by a sex offender, and an
18-year-old female jogger was slain near Acme.
   King County Prosecutor Norm Maleng, who heads the 24-member
committee, referred to the Vancouver and Acme slayings as he sat
next to Gardner at the task force's final meeting.
   The murder of Amanda Stavik occurred ``about a quarter-mile from
my boyhood home. That hit home for me personally,'' Maleng said.
   Police are still seeking leads in the case. An autopsy report
released Tuesday was inconclusive but said the circumstances of her
death were consistent with drowning. Police consider the case a
homicide.
   In the Vancouver case, Westley Allan Dodd pleaded innocent to
three counts of first-degree murder Tuesday and was held without
bail.
   Gardner called the panel's recommendations a broad and
comprehensive approach to getting predatory sex criminals off
Washington streets.
   ``Step two is to take this and put it into legislation,'' he
said.
   Key lawmakers, including Senate Law and Justice Committee head
Gary Nelson, said it will be a top priority from the first day of
the session.
   The committee included victims and relatives of sex criminals.
One of them, Ida Balliasiotes, said she thought the package was ``a
good first start but may be some of the sentencing provisions could
have been tougher.''
   Her daughter, Diane Balliasiotes, was raped and slain after
being kidnapped from in September 1988. Gene Raymond Kane is
serving a life sentence for her murder.
   Another panel member, Lucy Berliner, of the Sexual Assault
Center at Harborview Hospital in Seattle, acknowledged that the
package would not have stopped the state's most notorious sex
killer, Ted Bundy, who was executed in Florida earlier this year
after a string of slayings in the West and in Florida.
   The recommendations, which are expected to cost $15 million in
the coming year and about $55 million in subsequent years, would:
   _Empower judges to sentence repeat rapists and child molesters
to life in prison. These crimes now carry a 10-year maximum
sentence.
   _Permit prosecution as adults of 15-year-olds who commit sex
crimes of a heinous nature and 16-year-olds who commit lesser sex
offenses.
   _Require convicted sex offenders to register with the Washington
State Patrol and the sheriff. Failure to register would be
punishable by up to five years in prison.
   _Improve treatment of sex offenders, including closely monitored
post-release treatment.
   _Empower juries to indefinitely commit for treatment any sex
offender found incompetent to stand trial. Maleng and Gardner
acknowledged possible civil rights concerns with the provision, but
said it would be used with discretion.
   _Create a $2.5 million-a-year fund to cover medical and other
expenses of sex crime victims.
</TEXT>
