<FIRST>r a AM-AparoSlaying     11-28 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aparo Slaying,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Gets 34 Years in Killing of Girlfriend's Mother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man described as the sexual slave
of his former girlfriend was sentenced to 34 years in prison
Tuesday for killing the girl's mother.
   Superior Court Judge Raymond R. Norko expressed compassion and
outrage before imposing the sentence, telling Dennis Coleman, 21,
that ``whatever I do to you, I'm basically throwing away your
youth.''
   ``Your youth will be spent at Somers (State Prison),'' Norko
said, his eyes filling with tears. ``I find Somers probably the
most dangerous place I know of on earth. Part of me goes with you.''
   But, Norko said, testimony from Coleman and his friends about
the Aug. 5, 1987, killing of Joyce Aparo ``sent a chill up my
spine.''
   ``You and they come from a very middle class community ... yet
your peers spoke of murder as if it was a candy bar on a shelf that
could be reached by anybody.''
   Coleman showed no emotion as Norko passed the sentence.
Coleman's mother, who sobbed quietly through the sentencing
hearing, buried her face in her hands as her son was led away.
   Coleman pleaded guilty to murder and conspiracy to commit murder
in the stangulation of Joyce Aparo in her apartment. Under a plea
bargain, he had faced 30 to 42 years in prison.
   Coleman claimed that Joyce Aparo's daughter, Karin Aparo, now
18, begged him to kill her abusive mother.
   Assistant State's Attorney James E. Thomas argued for the full
42-year sentence, reminding Norko that Coleman struggled with Joyce
Aparo for 10 minutes before killing her.
   ``This isn't something that took place in a split second,'' he
said. ``This is a brutal, cold-blooded murder that took a long
time.''
   Calm and composed, Coleman addressed the court before being
sentence.
   ``If I could turn back time, I would,'' he said. ``Mr. Thomas
says it was a cold-blooded crime. I'm not a cold-blooded murderer.
It was the opposite of cold-blooded. It was passion.''
   Prosecutors contend Coleman and Karin Aparo plotted Joyce
Aparo's killing for more than a year. Karin Aparo is awaiting trial
in her mother's death after a Superior Court judge rejected her
request for special probation earlier this month. Coleman is
expected to testify against her.
   Coleman's lawyer, M. Hatcher Norris, said Coleman will likely
spend about 20 years in prison.
   A tall, slender redhead, Coleman appeared composed as he waited
outside the courtroom with family, friends and his new girlfriend
before the sentencing.
   He said he hasn't seen Karin Aparo since several weeks after
Joyce Aparo's slaying. Asked what he thought should happen to Karin
Aparo, Coleman said: ``I don't care. She'll be going to prison one
way or another, I guess. She deserves it.''
   Norris on Tuesday portrayed Aparo as manipulative, calculating
and amoral _ ``what I can only describe as a girl without a heart.''
   On the first day of a two-day sentencing hearing last week, Dr.
Gerald A. Faris, a Glastonbury psychologist who has treated Coleman
for two years, testified that Coleman was pressured into the murder
by his domineering girlfriend.
   ``Enslavement, I guess you could call it,'' Faris said.
   Before Coleman met Aparo, he had been suffering from a
personality disorder that filled him with a deep emptiness, leaving
him vulnerable to obsessive love and even to being seduced into
committing criminal acts, Faris testified.
   At age 15, Aparo sent Coleman descriptive letters and pictures
of sexual acts they would perform together, witnesses testified. By
age 16, she had recorded in her diary about 100 times they had sex,
witnesses testified.
</TEXT>
