<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Eliana     11-28 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Eliana,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autopsy To Be Performed at National Institute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of an 8-year-old whose landmark
legal battle opened schools to mentally disabled AIDS victims was
flown Tuesday to Maryland for an autopsy her mother hopes will aid
research into the incurable disease.
   Eliana Martinez, whose weight had dropped to about 15 pounds,
died of heart failure Monday, cradled in the arms of her adoptive
mother.
   ``She opened her eyes and there were tears in them. She looked
at me to help. I could not,'' Rosa Martinez said Tuesday. ``It was
not a peaceful angel-like death. It was agonizing.''
   Mrs. Martinez won a court battle to let Eliana go to school
without being sealed in a glass box to ensure that she would not
infect her classmates.
   Funeral services were planned for early next week in Tampa. The
date will depend on how much time doctors need at the National
Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md., said Mrs. Martinez.
   ``She died like she lived _ fighting every inch of the way,''
Mrs. Martinez said.
   ``Her body couldn't take it anymore,'' said Dan McClowry,
Eliana's speech therapist and a close friend of Mrs. Martinez.
   Over the last few days, Eliana had slipped in and out of coma.
   ``Seeing the joy she won't have makes you realize it's not a
house or money that's important,'' Mrs. Martinez said. ``Whatever
you're doing you should enjoy it. Life is so short.''
   Mrs. Martinez, a licensed practical nurse, answered a radio plea
about an abandoned baby and adopted Eliana as a sickly 11-month-old
from a hospital in Puerto Rico.
   She then led the precedent-setting struggle to get Eliana into
public school with children her own age. She said Eliana needed to
be with children her own age.
   Eliana's two-year federal court fight against the Hillsborough
County School system drew national attention.
   Fearing Eliana posed a risk of transmitting AIDS to classmates
and teachers, education officials put the child on homebound
education.
   They feared Eliana might transmit bodily fluids because she was
not toilet trained and sucked her fingers, but Mrs. Martinez sued.
   U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich ruled in August 1988
that Eliana could attend a special-needs school only if she sat
inside a specially built, $10,000 glass booth.
   Mrs. Martinez appealed, and the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta ordered a rehearing last December. Kovachevich
reversed her decision last spring, saying the health risk was
remote and theoretical.
   Eliana went to school and sat at desks with classmates in April
at Manhattan Exceptional Center, but after only a few weeks she
became too ill for school.
   ``She fought for her life all her life,'' said teacher Peggy
Kelly.
   Doctors believe she contracted the AIDS virus from tainted blood
transfusions as an infant. She was diagnosed with AIDS-related
complex, a precursor to AIDS, in 1985.
   Eliana had been treated with the experimental drugs AZT, then
DDI, but was taken off both when they failed to control the
disease. Her condition steadily worsened in the last two months and
she was hospitalized at least twice with bacterial infections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
