<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru a0723 11-28 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former New York State Senator Picked</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS graf 4: ``Meanwhile, Bush,'' with Bush extending life
of civil rights commission; SUBS 12th graf: ``Lucas, a,'' to note how nomination
blocked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has chosen former New York
State Sen. John R. Dunne as assistant attorney general for civil
rights, the post left vacant all year after William Lucas failed to
win Senate confirmation, administration sources said Tuesday.
   Dunne belongs to the all-male Garden City Golf Club on Long
Island and has said he would resign that membership if nominated to
the Justice Department post.
   Dunne, 59, of Garden City, is credited with helping reform the
state's prison system following the deadly riot at Attica Prison in
1971.
   Meanwhile, Bush signed legislation Tuesday extending the life of
the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights through Sept. 30, 1991. The
panel, shrouded in controversy during the Reagan years, had been
faced with extinction.
   The sources, who insisted on anonymity, said Bush has settled on
Dunne for the civil rights job and Dunne is undergoing a background
clearance check before the White House formally announces the
nomination.
   That check could take up to two months.
   Dunne, a graduate of Georgetown University and Yale Law School,
resigned from the New York Senate in September after losing a
contest for majority leader in the Republican-controlled chamber.
   After a 24-year legislative career in which chaired the
Judiciary Committee and rose to deputy majority leader, Dunne
returned to practice law full time in Uniondale.
   A secretary who answered the telephone at Dunne's office said
only, ``The senator has no comments and is referring all calls to
the people in Washington.''
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., an old friend of Dunne's, said in a
telephone call from his New York office, ``If the president has to
pick a Republican, he couldn't pick a more decent person than John
Dunne.''
   Rangel said Dunne has the legal experience and training ``that
the previous candidate lacked.''
   Lucas, a former sheriff and county executive from Detroit, was
charged by critics with lacking credentials for the post. His
nomination was blocked in August on a 7-7 vote in the Senate
Judiciary Committee.
   Dunne has a reputation as a maverick in the Nassau County
Republican Party who ran on several occasions against its powerful
GOP machine.
   During most of his 24 years in the legislature, a part-time
post, he lived in Albany at the Fort Orange Club, which admitted
women to membership only last year.
   Dunne told Newsday in an interview last week that he would
resign his membership in the all-male Garden City Golf Club if
nominated to the Justice post. ``It would send the wrong message to
stay,'' he said. ``It would be inappropriate.''
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh had backed Dunne for the post.
</TEXT>
