<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Afghan     11-28 0120</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0122</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Soldiers in Afghanistan Offered Amnesty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislature on Tuesday offered amnesty to
Soviet soldiers who committed crimes in Afghanistan, where Soviet
troops fought anti-Marxist rebels, the Soviet news agency Tass
reported.
   The Supreme Soviet resolution, which applies to servicemen who
were in Afghanistan between December 1979 and February 1989, takes
effect Dec. 15.
   It is the second amnesty involving Afghan war veterans.
Prosecutor Alexander Sukharev said in July 1988 that soldiers who
turned against their country during the Soviet intervention in
Afghanistan would be offered an amnesty.
   More than 100,000 Red Army troops began rolling into Afghanistan
in December 1979 to replace one communist government with another
and fight a growing Moslem insurgency.
