<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Indians     11-28 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Indians,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Chief Demands End of `Extermination' of Tribe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Single name Raoni is cq</HEAD>
<UNK>By JORGE MEDEROS ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chief Raoni on Tuesday demanded that
President Jose Sarney's government act to stop the
``extermination'' of the Yanomami Indian tribe.
   ``President Sarney has no words and does not care that our
brothers are dying,'' Raoni, chief of the Txukarramae tribe, told a
news conference.
   Raoni toured 15 countries this year with British rock musician
Sting to raise funds for a 300-mile-by-435-mile reservation for
Indians.
   Raoni demanded that the government immediately remove an
estimated 40,000 gold prospectors he said were in the Yanomami
reserve in remote Roraima state on Brazil's northern border with
Venezuela.
   He said miners spread disease, made game scarce and contaminated
rivers with mercury used in panning.
   ``Our brothers are peaceful, they do not know how to fight to
defend themselves. Those who remain alive are only skin and
bones,'' Raoni said.
   Environmental and Indian protection groups told Congress this
week that 280 of the 9,000 Yanomamis had died in the last two years.
   An additional 170 Yanomamis are being treated for malaria,
venereal diseases, dysentary and malnutrition, said Maria Gorete
Goncalves of the Support Center of Indigenous Tribes at the
University of Brasilia.
   Brazil's native Indian population has dropped from an estimated
5 million when Portuguese explorers discovered the country in 1500
to about 220,000 today.
   ``Enough of death. We do not want our families to go on dying,''
Raoni said, adding that the Yanomamis need an emergency health plan.
   ``The Yanomamis are being decimated by a government that cares
only about the money of the miners,'' he said.
   Iris Pedro de Oliveira, president of the government's National
Indian Foundation, told a Senate Justice Committee Monday that the
Yanomamis' situation was desperate.
   He said the government lacks the resources to remove the miners
from the region.
   Raoni said, ``Use the army, the federal police, but Sarney must
comply with the constitution and revoke the genocidal decrees.''
</TEXT>
