<SECOND>AM-Britain-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dog Lovers Protest South Korean President's Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 7 grafs SUB for grafs 4-5, Roh arrived ... UPDATING with Roh,
Thatcher comments. Picks up 6th graf, The protesters ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal rights activists appealed Tuesday to
visiting South Korean President Roh Tae-woo to curb the cruel
methods used in his country to kill dogs and cats for consumption.
   ``They boil them alive, hang them, and even blowtorch them to
death,'' said Richard Moore, director of the International Fund for
Animal Welfare.
   Moore was one of 50 protesters who gathered outside the Lord
Mayor's residence where Roh was speaking during a four-day visit to
Britain.
   Roh, who arrived in Britain on Monday, made no mention of the
issue in his lunch-time address in which he announced an
unspecified reduction in South Korean import tariff on Scotch
whisky.
   Roh held talks with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Tuesday
evening before attending a dinner in his honor at her official
Downing Street residence.
   Mrs. Thatcher expressed hope that barriers between North and
South Korea may be dismantled.
   ``With so many barriers now coming down, it may not be too much
to hope that North Korea will also be ready to respond to your
efforts to open a dialogue,'' she told her dinner guests.
   Roh said his support for democratic reforms in South Korea in
1987 effectively broke a political deadlock there.
   ``Democracy has just begun to take root in Korea,'' he said.
``We have turned our backs on the authoritarian rule which held
sway for so many years.''
   Earlier, demonstrators said 2 million cats and dogs are killed
cruelly each year in South Korea, where the meat is considered by
some to be a good protein source with a delicate taste.
   The protesters said they were not objecting to consumption of
dogs and cats, but to the means used to kill them. The South Korean
Embassy said the methods have become more humane.
   ``Problems arise because of some of the killing methods used by
elderly people in the countryside who don't know how to kill more
humanely, but in cities more sanitary and modernized practices are
used,'' said spokesman Byung Ho-suh.
   Kim Keran, who is trying to set up a Korean chapter of the
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, gave a letter to
a South Korean delegation calling for new laws to ensure that dogs
are killed humanel.
   ``Dog meat was first used when the country was very poor and
there was no other alternative,'' she said. ``But now the economy
is stronger there is no excuse to carry on this cruelty.''
   South Korean officials say international protests are based on a
misunderstanding that South Koreans eat their pets, rather than
dogs and cats bred for their meat.
</TEXT>
