<FIRST>r a AM-Kemp-Cities     11-28 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp-Cities,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Pushes Anti-Poverty Proposals to Receptive City Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 2,000 city officials from around the country
meeting Tuesday gave President Bush's housing secretary a standing
ovation for a emotional speech about a new housing and jobs program
for the poor.
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp said
anti-poverty legislation enacted in the 1960s was ineffective and
based on ``paternalistic'' policies that promoted a permanent
underclass.
   ``Noble goals were frustrated by over-reliance on government
entitlements, over-reliance on the redistribution of wealth and an
attitude that poor people were unwilling or unable to become
entrepreneurs, producers, job holders and homeowners,'' Kemp told
the session of the National League of Cities convention.
   Kemp's talk focused the ``HOPE'' program unveiled earlier this
month by Bush. He also called on the cities to eliminate the
``outrageous red tape and regulations,'' such as some zoning and
rent control laws and that he said limit affordable housing.
   He said he has seen, through visits to housing projects across
the country, evidence that poor people can pull themselves out of
poverty with the type of programs Bush is now promoting.
   ``I reject the attitude that nothing can or should be expected
from poor Americans,'' Kemp said.
   Bush's $2.1 billion program provides grants for non-profit
housing groups, rehabilitation of vacant public housing units,
anti-drug programs and service-supported housing for the homeless,
Kemp said.
   Kemp said he also has directed the Federal Housing
Administration to set aside 10 percent of FHA-foreclosed housing
for lease to non-profit groups to help the homeless.
</TEXT>
