<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Plane     11-28 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Plane,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says El Salvador Using Weapons Plane to Deflect Attention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega has accused
the Salvadoran government of using the case of an arms-smuggling
plane as a way to deflect attention from the violence wracking El
Salvador.
   The Nicaraguan leader said the problem in neighboring Salvador
is the ``need to have a cease-fire, to reach a peace agreement.''
   A twin-engine plane painted black and without registration
numbers crashed Saturday in southern El Salvador and the four
crewmen perished. It was found to be carrying weapons and
ammunition including 24 Soviet-made anti-aircraft rockets.
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani suspended diplomatic
relations with Nicaragua Sunday, saying he had no doubt the plane
was from Nicaragua and the weapons were for Salvadoran rebels.
   Ortega, speaking to a group of church leaders Monday, did not
comment directly on Cristiani's accusations.
   He said the plane was not the problem, ``The problem is that the
people of El Salvador are being murdered, their human rights
violated. The Salvadoran government bombs the population and kills
Jesuits priests.''
   He referred to the Nov. 16 slayings of six Jesuit educators in a
house in San Salvador. Witnesses said men in military uniforms
killed the priests.
   The Foreign Ministry issued a statement saying the Salvadoran
government was trying to create a new ``Hasenfus'' case.
   Eugene Hasenfus was an American aboard a cargo plane downed Oct.
5, 1986, in Nicaragua.
   Nicaragu said the plane had taken off from a Salvadoran airport
and was carrying weapons to Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras.
Hasenfus was convicted of arms smuggling but was released in
December 1986 and returned to the United States.
   Ortega said that in the Hasenfus case ``there was clear evidence
that the Contras were being supplied with the cooperation of the
Salvadoran military.
   ``We did not break relations then. On the contrary, we have
always sought a negotiated solution.''
   The Salvadoran Foreign Ministry on Tuesday said the pilot killed
in Saturday's crash was a Nicaraguan air force captain and
identified him as Mauricio Quiroz Garcia, 36.
   But a man with that name was alive and well in Managua.
   Mauricio Quiroz Garcia, 36, told The Associated Press in Managua
he had been piloting a commercial flight from Managua to San Jose,
Costa Rica, for Aeronica, the national airline, on Saturday.
   ``I'm totally baffled,'' he said.
   The Salvadoran Foreign Ministry was asked about the case and
said it would check again with the armed forces.
   In New York, El Salvador's ambassador to the United Nations,
Ricardo G. Castaneda, relayed his government's request for an
emergency Security Council meeting to deal with Nicaragua's
``aggression.''
</TEXT>
