<SECOND>AM-Pregnant Murder, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husband, Two Men, Arrested in Death-for-Hire of Pregnant Woman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 7th, `Anthony Pfaaf...' to UPDATE with
information on Pfaaf's relationship to Johnson family.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MERRIMACK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man and the two teen-agers he allegedly
hired for $10,000 to stab and strangle his pregnant wife were
charged Tuesday with capital murder.
   Kenneth Johnson, 37, and the two teen-agers entered no pleas and
were ordered held without bail. The charge carries the death
penalty.
   Andrew Serell, the assistant attorney general in charge of the
case, would not disclose a motive, saying only, ``We have some
theories.''
   The partially clothed body of Sharon Johnson, 36, who was seven
months pregnant, was found in a gravel pit near a Bedford
construction site in July 1988.
   Johnson, who had lived with his wife in Bow and later moved to
Warwick, R.I., was arrested without incident Tuesday in Warren,
R.I., at the restaurant where he worked part-time, said Warren
Police Chief Robert Pare.
   Johnson waived extradition and was rushed to New Hampshire.
   Anthony Pfaaf, 19, of Wallace, N.C., and formerly of Manchester,
and Jason Carroll, 19 and the son of a Bedford police officer, were
arrested Monday night. Police Chief David Bailey said Carroll's
mother was not involved in the investigation.
   State Police Sgt. Roland Lamy said Pfaaf knew the Johnsons from
``having impregnated'' Johnson's daughter from a previous marriage,
Lisa, when she was 16.
   Lamy said Lisa left the Johnson household in May 1988 to live
with her mother, Bernadette Paquette, in Warwick, R.I. Lisa Johnson
and her child are living in Rhode Island.
   ``Bernadette Paquette was very helpful in the investigation,''
Lamy said.
   Pfaaf ``was approached by Johnson and Pfaaf then approached
Carroll,'' Serell said.
   As he was being led from the courtroom, Pfaaf told reporters he
is innocent.
   ``I didn't have anything to do with this,'' he said. ``You can
put that on your TVs.''
   The night she was killed, Mrs. Johnson left her job at a
computer company, drove to Massachusetts to buy a lottery ticket,
then headed north to a shopping mall in Manchester, where her car
was later found.
   Her body was found the next morning by a construction worker.
   At the time, Johnson told police he assumed his wife was working
late and that he was angry she had not called to say where she was.
He has said he fell asleep on the couch around midnight.
   When he awoke the next morning, he assumed she had come in
during the night and left again for work, he said.
   Johnson said someone who worked with his wife called around 9
a.m. to say she hadn't come to work. At that point _ after her body
had been discovered _ he reported her missing to police.
</TEXT>
