<HEAD>Senator Blasts Administration Comments </HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Saturday to Sunday in 4th graf: ``Jennifer J.,''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said Tuesday
he was outraged that Bush administration officials had suggested
publicly that a Connecticut woman is guilty of aiding rebels in El
Salvador.
   ``When an American is in legal trouble in another country,
particularly a country in which the tradition of equal justice is
not firmly established, the U.S. government ought to either
publicly insist on its citizen's innocence or keep its official
mouth shut,'' Dodd said in a written statement.
   ``It may be news in some quarters of the White House and the
State Department, but we have a tradition in this country of
presuming the innocence of persons who have been arested unless and
until they are proven guilty,'' added Dodd, who chairs the Senate
Foreign Relations subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere.
   Jennifer J. Casolo, 28, a native of Thomaston, Conn., was
arrested Sunday and Salvadoran police confiscated tons of
ammunition buried in the garden of her home in San Salvador. They
said the arms were stored there by guerrillas. Ms. Casolo had
rented the house for three months with a roommate who left the
country the morning before the raid.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said of Ms. Casolo on
Monday: ``There are indications of her involvement, that's for
certain.
   `It's fairly clear that these weapons were found there. I mean,
we're not talking about a small package of pistols here. We're
talking about tons of equipment and mortars and dynamite and rounds
of ammunitions and explosives. This is hardly a case of someone
having a few things flipped in their shopping bag on the way home.''
   On Tuesday, a Justice Department official said that agency is
trying to determine whether Ms. Casolo should be charged with
violating the Neutrality Act, which prohibits private U.S. citizens
from taking sides in wars in which the United States is not
involved.
   Justice Department prosecutors and FBI agents were reviewing the
circumstances of the case but had not opened a formal
investigation, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   To establish a violation of the Neutrality Act, prosecutors
would probably have to show that the woman was part of an effort to
ship arms from the United States to the Salvadoran rebels, the
official said.
   Evidence that a person stored weapons for rebels would not
necessarily constitute a violation of the law, the official said.
   U.S. authorities had not eliminated the possibility Ms. Casolo
was framed, the official said.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Ms.
Cosolo technically is being held incommunicado by the National
Police but is being allowed regular visits by a U.S. consular
officer. Salvadoran officials said she has not been charged.
   Ms. Casolo was visited by Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash. A doctor
who examined her at the request of the U.S. Embassy reported she is
in good health.
   Ms. Casolo's friends say she was framed by Salvadoran
authorities as part of an effort to discredit the church. She
provides tours of El Salvador as a representative of the San
Antonio, Texas-based Christian Education Seminars, to visiting
church members and others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
