<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 3rdLd-Writethru a0736 11-28 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0736,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prominent Rightist Assassinated in San Salvador Ambush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with breakdown on wounded. Picks
up 8th graf, `Both areas ... with minor editing thereafter to trim</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent right-wing
politician was assassinated Tuesday morning by gunmen who ambushed
his car on a busy San Salvador street.
   The victim, Francisco Jose Guerrero, was a former presidential
candidate and served as foreign minister and chief justice of the
Supreme Court.
   Police said a bodyguard shot to death one attacker and another
was wounded. But the military said later one attacker was killed
and a Guerrero bodyguard was wounded.
   The military said four assailants were involved and blamed
leftist guerrillas. No group claimed responsibility.
   Witnesses and officials said the attack occurred at 9:40 a.m.
and Guerrero, shot once in the throat, managed to drive several
hundred yards to a hospital, where he died.
   Rebels and soldiers battled again early Tuesday in the capital's
northern neighborhoods of Mejicanos and Ciudad Delgado.
   After the fighting died down, reporters saw the bodies of eight
guerrillas. Government casualties were not reported.
   The battle began about 3 a.m. with mortar barrages and
machine-gun and rifle fire. Three helicopter gunships strafed
guerrilla positons. Shooting tapered off in midmorning.
   Both areas had been scenes of heavy fighting during the
offensive the rebels launched Nov. 11. Most of the rebel force
withdrew last week but guerrilla patrols had been seen in both
Mejicanos and Ciudad Delgado.
   It was the first time this week that fighting in the capital
zone was more than brief exchanges of gunfire.
   Guerrero, 64, represented conservative landowners in their
successful bid to remove a key phase of the land reform program in
the 1970s.
   He was a founder of the National Conciliation Party, the
government party during military rule in the 1960s and '70s.
   Guerrero served as foreign minister in 1968-71 and ran for
president in 1984 against Jose Napoleon Duarte, a centrist
Christian Democrat, who won in a runoff. Guerrero was president of
the Supreme Court for five years during the Duarte administration.
   The Christian Democrats were defeated in an election this year
by the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance.
   In another development, the rebel high command denied any
connection with Jennifer Jean Casolo, an American arrested Sunday
by police who said they found tons of ammunition buried in the
garden of her home in San Salvador. A broadcast on the rebels'
clandestine Radio Venceremos said the rebels deny ``any link
between this North American citizen and our vanguards and regards
this as a vulgar frame-up by the armed forces and the government
... as part of their persecution of churches, humanitarian
organizations and everyone else connected with aiding the poor.''
   Ms. Casolo, 28, a native of Thomaston, Conn., represented the
Texas-based Christian Education Seminars.
   Police said the arms were buried by rebels on the grounds of the
house that Ms. Casolo had rented for three months.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday of Ms.
Casolo, ``There are indications of her involvement, that's for
certain.''
   Also Tuesday, diplomatic and church sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said American Baptist Church missionary
Ruth Mooney was arrested, held overnight by Treasury Police and
released on condition she leave the country.
   They said she was arrested Monday in Santa Ana, 35 miles
northwest of San Salvador, and brought to the capital Monday
evening, where a U.S. consular official met with her at Treasury
Police headquarters.
   President Alfredo Cristiani's government contends most
humanitarian organizations linked to foreign churches are little
more than guerrilla front groups.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said Tuesday in Washington he
was outraged by comments by Bush administration officials.
   ``When an American is in legal trouble in another country,
particularly a country in which the tradition of equal justice is
not firmly established, the U.S. government ought to either
publicly insist on its citizen's innocence or keep its official
mouth shut,'' Dodd said.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Ms. Casolo
technically is being held incommunicado by national police but is
being allowed regular visits by a U.S. consular officer.
   A U.S. Justice Department official said the agency is trying to
determine if Ms. Casolo should be charged with violating the
Neutrality Act, which prohibits private U.S. citizens from taking
sides in wars where the United States is not involved.
   He added U.S. authorities have not eliminated the possibility
Ms. Casolo was framed.
</TEXT>
