<HEAD>US Official, Two Pilots Killed in Crash of Small Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 4 `Joseph Trippet ...' to CORRECT spelling of middle
name to Trippe. Picks up graf 5 pvs, `Joseph Trippe ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the U.S. National
Transportation Safety Board and two Venezuelan pilots were killed
when their plane crashed during a rainstorm in mountains west of
Caracas, it was reported Tuesday.
   The U.S. Embassy said four other U.S. citizens survived the
crash Monday night, but were injured. They were returning from a
weekend visit to Angel Falls, the highest waterfall in the world,
at Canaima, 400 miles southeast of Caracas.
   The Venezuelan Civilian Aviation agency said the twin-engine
Cessna crashed as it approached the Charallave municipal airport,
apparently because of the weather.
   Joseph Trippe Nall, 47, the NTSB member who perished, was in
Venezuela to attend a transportation seminar, said Barbara Moore of
the U.S. Information Service. The pilots were identified as Dickson
Naranjo and Jose Vargas.
   Civil Aviation officials identified the survivors as Jerri
Alles, an official of the Federal Aviation Administration; her
husband, David Halley, who worked at an FAA hangar at Washington
National Airport; NTBS member Kenneth Pepper, Nall's assistant, and
Kay Bond. Ms. Bond, a producer at Maryland Public Television for
the show ``AM Weather,'' apparently was on vacation.
   They were taken to the Hospital de Clinicas in Caracas with
``burns and other injuries,'' said Cesar Jara, Civil Aviation
director. `They are all out of danger and they'll probably be
released from the hospital tomorrow,'' he said.
   Transport Ministry officials said the plane was approaching the
airport about 30 miles west of Caracas when it crashed at 7:30 p.m.
La Carlota airport in Caracas is not equipped for night landings
and planes coming in after sunset are sent to Charallave.
   They said Civil Aviation investigators went to the scene to try
to determine the specific cause of the accident.
   The National Transportation Safety Board has five members and
Nall's successor will be named by presidential appointment. By law,
the position must go to a Democrat to keep a political balance on
the board, which now has three Republicans and one Democrat.
   Nall was appointed to the transportation board April 11, 1986,
by President Reagan. The NTSB investigates transportation accidents
and incidents, determines their cause and makes recommendations to
other agencies and organizations to increase safety.
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., a member of the Senate Commerce
Committee, called Nall ``a public servant of the highest
distinction.''
   ``Mr. Nall participated in a number of accident investigations
and testified before the Senate Commerce Committee on a number of
occasions,'' Ford said. ``In this capacity, he provided a
tremendous service to the safety of our transportation system.''
   Nall, a lawyer from Smithfield, N.C., was a native of Atlanta.
He also was a pilot and operated Nall Aviation Enterprises, a
ground school at Johnston County Airport in Smithfield, the NTSB
said.
</TEXT>
