<FIRST>r a AM-Bus-TrainWreck     11-28 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus-Train Wreck,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Probe Fatal Bus-Train Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ABC-TV charter bus en
route to a Monday night football game had ``nowhere to go'' when a
commuter train slammed into it, killing two network executives, a
police spokesman said.
   It appears that the bus driven by Paul Cang, 34, of Foster City,
got caught in heavy traffic while trying to cross the Southern
Pacific tracks at the Oyster Point Boulevard railroad crossing,
less than two miles from the Candlestick Park game site, Police
Sgt. Mike Guglielmoni said.
   ``The gates came down, the lights went on, the bells started
ringing and there was no place to go,'' said John Sanchez, 45, who
was at the wheel of a tractor-trailer in front of the International
Coach Co. bus. ``The train was blowing its horn continuously, and I
pulled up as far as I could.
   ``I couldn't go any farther without climbing the car in front of
me. The bus was trapped, because there were cars stopped in the
other direction, so he couldn't go around me.''
   Said Guglielmoni: ``He just had nowhere to go _ there was a
large truck in front of him.''
   The Caltrain diesel locomotive, traveling from San Francisco to
Burlingame, hit the bus at 60 mph, pushing it 50 feet down the
tracks and spinning it 180 degrees.
   Killed in the accident were Kurt Michael Sanger, 50, of New
York, and Adele Roffis, 61, of Culver City, Calif.
   The bus carried part of a group of ABC employees and guests who
had taken a cruise on San Francisco Bay and were headed to
Candlestick Park to watch the National Football League game between
the New York Giants and San Francisco 49ers, said Bob Wheeler,
manager of sports information for ABC.
   Cang was reported in stable condition with cuts and head
injuries Tuesday at Peninsula Hospital in Burlingame.
   The California Highway Patrol was summoned to help with the
police investigation. Guglielmoni said the CHP report, plus
toxicology tests voluntarily taken by Cang to check for traces of
drugs or alcohol, will be forwarded to the San Mateo County
district attorney's office for review.
   There was no indication that drugs or alcohol were involved in
the accident, police said.
   Records at the California Department of Motor Vehicles show Cang
has been convicted three times in the past 17 months for traffic
violations, two of which occurred while he was driving a bus.
   International Coach declined to comment on the accident or
Cang's driving record.
   A state Public Utilities Commission survey, released last June,
listed the railroad crossing as in urgent need of improvement
because of heavy traffic, and 11th-ranked of the 82 crossings most
needing repair throughout California.
</TEXT>
