<FIRST>r i AM-Netherlands-SAfrica     11-28 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands-SAfrica,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Claiming to be Cousin of SAfrican Minister Seeks Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soldier claiming to be the
cousin of South Africa's defense minister is seeking asylum after
accusing his army unit of killing and torturing civilians, an
Amsterdam organization said Tuesday.
   The Dutch Anti-Apartheid Movement identified the man as Corp.
Mervyn Malan, 27, and said he had served with a reconnaissance unit
known as Recce 5.3 that was part of South Africa's special forces.
   A statement issued by the movement quoted Malan as saying Recce
5.3 engaged in systematic ``torture ... bombing of villages and .
.. burning of women and children'' in Namibia and Angola.
   It reported he said, ``I have seen and done terrible things. I
will never be part of any killing again.
   ``My cousin, the general (Defense Minister Magnus Malan),
doesn't protect me. He's the one who wants me killed.''
   Anti-Apartheid Movement spokesman Bart Luirink told The
Associated Press the self-professed defector described himself as a
``full cousin'' to the defense minister but did not know the exact
family links.
   He reported South African Defense Ministry officials said they
had never heard of a Corp. Malan.
   The statement reported the defector gave this account about
leaving South Africa:
   He fled to Swaziland in 1988 after ignoring a callup for a
second tour of duty with the special forces in which he served from
1982-85.
   He was pursued to Swaziland by a special forces group and
decided to come to the Netherlands in December 1988.
   The decision to request political asylum was made several months
ago because the publicity ``could serve his cause.''
   The Justice Ministry was closed at the time the statement was
distributed and it could not be determined if an asylum request had
been received and was being processed.
   Malan decided to quit the army after being involved in an April
1988 raid in Namibia where he was ordered to throw phosphorous
grenades into a civilian truck carrying women and children,
according to the statement.
   Luirink reported Malan said all of the people were killed, but
he had no figures.
   Namibia is a territory that was administered by South Africa's
white-minority government until this fall when elections were held
under a U.N.-sponsored agreement. The accord provides for
independence for the territory, also known as South-West Africa.
   Namibia is sandwiched between South Africa and Angola, and for
years South African forces went into Angola to attack bases of
South-West Africa Organization guerrillas fighting for independence.
</TEXT>
