<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrashTrial     11-28 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Age Survivors Take Stand in DUI, Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen survivors of the nation's worst
alcohol-related traffic disaster on Tuesday recounted the panic on
a burning church bus after it collided with a pickup truck headed
the wrong way down an interstate highway.
   ``It looked like somebody was standing in the front of the bus
with a flamethrower,'' said Jess Durrance, 17, of Radcliff,
describing the May 14, 1988 accident that killed 27 people on
Interstate 71, about five miles south of Carrollton.
   Durrance said he tried in vain to kick out windows to escape the
flames and smoke, then ran to the back of the bus where he found
``everybody was trying to squish and push through'' a rear
emergency exit.
   His testimony came in the trial of Larry Mahoney, 36, of rural
Owen County, who is charged with 27 counts of murder, 12 counts of
first-degree assault, 42 counts of wanton endangerment and one
count of drunken driving.
   Mahoney broke into tears as Carroll County Coroner James B. Dunn
gave graphic descriptions of bodies found inside the bus. His
sobbing prompted Carroll Circuit Judge Charles Satterwhite to order
a recess.
   ``I couldn't believe what I had seen,'' Dunn said. ``I thought I
was having a nightmare.'' He said the bodies of 17 children were
found sprawled in the aisle and on seats in the rear of the bus.
   Families of the victims clasped hands tightly and dabbed tears
with handkerchiefs during Dunn's testimony.
   Russell Baldani, one of Mahoney's three attorneys, said during
recess he didn't know what effect Mahoney's sobbing would have on
the jury.
   ``It's nothing staged. I'm sure they don't think that,'' Baldani
said. ``Hopefully, they will sympathize with Larry and what he's
going through.''
   In other testimony, Sgt. Jim Sharon of the Kentucky State Police
compared what he saw at the crash to carnage he had seen in Vietnam.
   ``Bodies were black and charred, skin burned, and (emergency
medical technicians) were working on them,'' Sharon said.
   Mahoney's attorneys, during cross-examination, began building
their case that the former school bus carrying 67 people was unsafe.
   The survivors described climbing over seats to sit with friends
and people lying in the aisles during a trip home from a
Cincinnati-area amusement park.
   ``It's no secret that's a big factor in our favor,'' said
Baldani.
   William Summer, Mahoney's lead attorney, pointed out
contradictions in testimony the young witnesses gave to state
police troopers and to National Transportation Safety Board
investigators.
   Summer cross-examined Jamie Hardesty, 17, of Radcliff, about
statements given to the NTSB that he had seen bus seats and plastic
on the floor burning. Hardesty said he was not sure if he had seen
seats and the plastic burning.
   ``Everything seems to be forgotten unless it is right around
Larry Mahoney,'' Summer said.
</TEXT>
