<FIRST>d e BC-Theater     11-28 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playwright Writes about Writing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Often, rock performers' least interesting songs
are about the hardships of touring. Playwright Kathleen Tolan has
brought a similar concept about her craft to the stage in ``Kate's
Diary,'' with similar results.
   The play opened Tuesday night off-Broadway in the Public
Theater's small Susan Stein Shiva Theater. David Greenspan directed.
   The play mixes scenes from Kate's ``real'' life and from a play
she has written. There is some cleverness in the juxtaposition of
scenes. Although the scenes aren't labeled, a viewer doesn't get
mixed up. But neither does a viewer get involved.
   In the first scene, Kate, acted by Lizbeth Mackay, sits on her
double bed as Michael Bryan French and Laura Hughes enact a murder
scene from her play.
   French also plays Frank, who lives with Kate. Hughes also plays
Kate's friend, to whom Kate complains about Frank. The bloom has
long gone from Kate and Frank's romance and the two constantly
irritate each other. It's a surprise when we learn in the last
scene that they've gone ahead with their planned marriage.
   One scene from Kate's play has Rafael Baez as Pablo, a
Salvadoran peasant, recount how, as a soldier for the government,
he had to shoot villagers chosen for sacrifice by their villages,
until he broke down. It's a moving monologue.
   However, when a successful playwright (John Griesemer)
condescendingly tells Kate that her play's characters and
situations don't add up, he seems to have the right idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
