<FIRST>r i AM-Shevardnadze     11-28 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shevardnadze,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Comments on 1968 Invasion of Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze appeared
to criticize the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia in an
interview published Tuesday in the Italian Communist Party
newspaper L'Unita.
   ``If there is an organic link between what is happening now and
what happened in 1968, I believe that the Czechoslovaks themselves
must respond,'' Shevardnadze was quoted as saying.
   ``You know that we respect very much this principle and we place
a lot of value on it: It is the principle of freedom of choice, of
non-interference. These principles were always proclaimed, but not
always respected. Now we are scrupulously following them and we act
in such a way that our words are not different from our acts.''
   L'Unita reported Shevardnadze said that in the Soviet Union and
East bloc countries ``the principal tendency is the democratization
of society, the formation of a democratic socialism.''
   Turning to this weekend's U.S.-Soviet summit, Shevardnadze was
quoted as saying he did not rule out ``agreements on basic choices
capable of enriching Soviet-American relations with new political
substance and new refinements.''
</TEXT>
