<FIRST>r i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0765 11-28 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0765,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidate Challenges President to Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling from Patch to Path in 12th graf bgng: Guerrillas
of the Maoist Shining ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Mario Vargas Llosa on
Tuesday challenged President Alan Garcia to a debate after an angry
exchange of charges in the campaign for next year's election.
   Palace spokesman Carlos Guillen said Garcia rejected the
challenge. Garcia is barred by the constitution from seeking
re-election.
   Vargas Llosa, a novelist who is considered the front-running
candidate for the April 8 election, called Garcia ``shameless,''
and accused the president's center-left Aprista party of spreading
lies.
   On Monday, Garcia said Vargas Llosa had promised to fire 500,000
public workers if elected, and the president said the government
employs only 507,000 people.
   At a news conference Tuesday, Vargas Llosa denied he had said he
would fire a half million employees and said he would resign his
candidacy if Garcia could prove that he did.
   ``Where is the recording of that declaration?'' said Vargas
Llosa. ``I defy President Alan Garcia to show that recording.''
   He also disputed Garcia's figures, saying the government employs
more than 1.6 million people.
   Vargas Llosa is running on a platform to reduce the government
bureaucracy and budget deficit.
   Police reported the decapitated bodies of two teachers and a
lawyer were found Monday near Chanchamayo, 140 miles east of Lima.
The three men had been kidnapped a few days before the Nov. 12
municipal elections by a group of armed men wearing military
uniforms, according to police.
   They said the three were active in the United Left party.
   No group asserted responsibility for the killings, officials
reported.
   Guerrillas of the Maoist Shining Path movement killed scores of
candidates and party activists in their effort to disrupt the
elections.
   Police also said the mayor and two councilmen of San Martin de
Pangoa, 175 miles east of Lima, were abducted Tuesday by Shining
Path rebels.
   The police said Mayor Mauro Caballero belongs to the United Left
party and the councilman are members of the Aprista party.
   Government reports say more than 16,000 people have been killed
in violence related to the Shining Path insurgency since it began
in 1980.
</TEXT>
