<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Dec. 1, or thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``La Lucha (The Struggle),'' a film produced by
the National Council of Churches about Christian base communities
in wartorn El Salvador, will be shown on ABC-TV on Sunday, Dec. 3.
   The film, presented on the Interfaith Broadcasting Commission's
series, ``Vision and Values,'' is about the religious struggle of
people in a wartorn land, particularly in base communities that
gather for worship and Bible study outside traditional church
structures.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Episcopal ecclesiastical court here has
found the Rev. George Gaines Swanson guilty of ``conduct unbecoming
a member of the clergy'' and has recommended his suspension from
clerical duties for two years.
   Swanson, rector of the Church of the Ascension in Jersey City,
N.J., has been involved in a long-running feud with Newark Bishop
John S. Spong over handling of parish property.
   The five-member court found that Swanson made misstatements
under oath in a civil suit against the bishop and diocesan
officials, swearing they had ``engaged in a scheme to raid, take
and acquire the corporate assets'' of the parish.
   Swanson's actions, the court ruled, were irresponsibile,
injurious and malicious.
   Under canon law, Spong will wait at least 30 days to pronounce
sentence to allow time for Swanson to appeal the verdict.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishop says the plague of
drug abuse that is engulfing entire neighborhoods and destroying
many families cannot be separated from their impoverished
circumstances.
   Brooklyn's Auxiliary Bishop Joseph M. Sullivan, head of the U.S.
Catholic Conference domestic policy committee, told a House
committee:
   ``It is clearly not enough to tell individuals that using and
selling drugs is bad, as true as that is, and not provide them with
other ways of finding employment and gaining productive means of
self-improvement.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About a fifth of United Methodist bishops
responding to a survey conducted by the Duke University Divinity
school said the church should no longer guarantee jobs for clergy.
   Asked what change they would favor in the system of itinerant
ministry _ in which clergy are guaranteed a job in return for going
where the bishop appoints them _ 15 of the 74 active and retired
bishops said they would do away with guaranteed appointments.
   The right to a guaranteed job is a longstanding tradition in
Methodism, but was not spelled out in church law until 1956.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An interfaith gathering of Jews and Christians
who work with AIDS sufferers was scheduled in Atlanta, Dec. 3-4 to
consider a unified religious response to AIDS.
   The consultation on ``AIDS-The Moral Imperative: A Call to
National Leadership,'' is being sponsored by the Carter Center of
Emory University, the AIDS National Inferfaith Network and its
Atlanta chapter.
   Former President Carter is to address the gathering.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Older blacks help themselves handle
stress and build self-esteem through religious involvement,
according to a recent University of Michigan study.
   Religious involvement helped increase self-esteem for older
blacks who help others and through association with the respected
institution of church, said Neal M. Krause, associate professor of
health gerontology at the university's School of Public Health.
   Personal beliefs that God will intervene in times of trouble
also help relieve stress, the study found.
   However, Krause and co-author Professor Thanh Van Tran of Boston
College found the study group members didn't necessarily increase
their religious involvement in times of trouble.
   The findings, published in the 1989 Journal of Gerontology:
Social Sciences, were based on a national study of about 500 people
with an average age of 67.
</TEXT>
