<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv29   11-28 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 29,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, Nov. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>In Housing, Now Its The Buyer's Turn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sellers of homes have had an advantage over
buyers in much of the country throughout the 1980s, but that
situation is likely to change in the early 1990s.
   Among the chief reasons: a large inventory of unsold homes in
many parts of the country, falling mortgage rates and expectations
of cuts to come, and a relative decline in the age 25 to 34
homebuying population.
   In fact, the mid-20s to mid-30s age group that produced a bulge
of demand and higher prices in the 1980s is now shrinking as a
percentage of the population, although the impact on housing will
be delayed until late in the decade.
   At the same time, the age group 65 and older is growing larger,
and could be a cause of more family-size houses coming on the
market, a consequence of that age category's tendency to trade down
in search of convenience over space.
   How far mortgage rates will fall is debatable, but the trend is
lower and housing forecasters say it will continue into 1990.
   Three economists speaking at the annual convention of the
National Association of Realtors in Dallas this month agreed that
the first half of the next decade would be characterized by falling
interest rates.
   The national average commitment rate for conventional loans, in
double digits through much of the 1980s, had fallen to 9.79 percent
early this month, and loans of a half-percentage point below that
already have developed.
   The improved climate is reflected in more favorable home-buying
attitudes measured by the University of Michigan. In the October
survey, 26 percent of those interviewed mentioned the availability
of good buys. Should that percentage be maintained for an entire
quarter it would be a 30-year record.
   Internal changes in the mortgage market might also help would-be
buyers find the best possible rates. While there will be fewer
thrift institutions in the 1990s, the amount of money available for
mortgages might actually grow.
   One reason for the expectation, according to speakers at the
realtors' convention, is the prospect of greater participation in
the market by the Federal National Mortgage Association and the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   This secondary market, as it is called, will absorb a much
larger share of mortgages in the 1990s, according to John Tuccillo,
the realtors' chief economist. He also expects more overseas money
to flow into the home mortgage markets.
   In addition, it is expected that more stress will be aimed at
resolving the financing problems of low and moderate-income housing
as a result of provisions in the Financial Institutions Reform,
Recovery and Enforcement Act.
   Under FIRREA's affordable housing program, each federal home
loan bank will subsidize interest rates on advances to member
institutions making long-term loans on such housing.
   ``There will be a real emphasis to squeeze the (mortgage
finance) system down to the low-income portion of the housing
sector,'' Tuccillo said.
   Whatever the consequences of demographic and market conditions
now taking shape, there is little likelihood of prices soaring
during the 1990s, as they did in many areas during the 1980s.
   At the beginning of 1980, for instance, the price of a typical
starter home was $50,000. Realtor records show that in the third
quarter of this year a comparable house sold for $80,700.
   While convention speakers said they expected houses will
continue to appreciate, most looked for much more stability than
existed in the 1980s. And if interest rates remain below 10
percent, it creates a buying combination.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, Nov. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv01   11-28 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 01,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sunday Is Lord's Day in Rural Churches, With or Without Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Sam Hayes drives 220 miles across eastern Wyoming each
weekend to say Mass at three rural churches. But when he's sick or
the weather makes travel impossible, the parishioners are on their
own.
   A priest can make it only one Sunday a month to St. Christopher
Mission in Unalaska at the end of the chain of Aleutian islands in
Alaska. The other weekends, Brenda Moscarella, a laywoman, puts the
services together.
   Despite criticism they will undermine the Sunday Mass tradition
in the United States, the U.S. Roman Catholic bishops have approved
a rite for Sunday celebrations in the absence of a priest. It is
intended to help several hundred parishes where no clergy are
available some Sundays.
   ``What do we do on Sunday if there is no priest? Do we tell
those people to stay home?'' asked Bishop Michael J. Sheehan of the
Diocese of Lubbock in west Texas. ``It's the best we can do in the
situation we're in: namely, the priest shortage.''
   Sundays have always been special for Christians.
   There was no evidence until the late second century of separate
Easter celebrations of the resurrection of Jesus. For the early
church, every Sunday fulfilled the same function.
   More than half of the nation's 53 million Catholics attend Mass
on an average Sunday.
   ``Sunday is the Lord's Day,'' Sheehan said. ``The Catholic
Church wants the memory of the resurrection to stay alive in the
Catholic community.''
   With or without a priest.
   A 1987 survey taken by the Liturgy Committee of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops found there were already priestless
celebrations in 51 dioceses. An estimated 1,000 parishes are in
that situation. Sheehan said more such celebrations are expected as
the clergy shortage worsens.
   The number of American priests has dropped to 53,000 from 59,200
in 1970. The ratio of worshipers to priests has gone from about 700
per priest in 1955 to almost 1,000 today.
   The U.S. priestless rite, which still must be approved by the
Vatican, follows guidelines for such celebrations that the Vatican
devised in response to requests from several bishops' conferences
throughout the world.
   The service is similar to a Mass, with the main difference being
that no one other than a priest can celebrate the Eucharist, in
which Catholics believe elements of bread and wine are consecrated
into the body and blood of Jesus. A communion service in which
hosts consecrated earlier by a priest are distributed may be
substituted in the priestless celebration.
   Retired Bishop William E. McManus, of the Diocese of Fort
Wayne-South Bend in Indiana, warned the bishops at their fall
meeting in October that approval of the rite ``will bless a monster
that could destroy the Sunday Mass tradition and Sunday Mass
obligation'' in the United States.
   But people in the dioceses involved say the services are
preferable to no Mass at all.
   ``The critical thing is we recognize we are a community,'' said
Sister Brenda Aiken, director of the Office of Pastoral
Administrators of the Catholic Diocese of Anchorage in Alaska.
   ``I think the bottom line is, yes, it is important for people to
gather,'' said Sister Marie Ann Brent, administrator of Holy Rosary
Church in Dillingham in southern Alaska.
   She said there is no difference in attendance when a priest says
Sunday Mass compared to the priestless celebrations and suggested a
priest may not necessarily provide the best kind of ministry.
   ``Maybe we work a little harder on the building of the
community,'' she said.
   Others also praised the celebrations as a way of getting lay
people more involved.
   ``I would say that even if we didn't have a shortage of priests,
there would be great value in training laypeople,'' Sheehan said.
``I see it as an opportunity to involve a greater number of people
in the ministry of the church.''
   Moscarella, who holds three services each weekend for 30 to 50
people, said the priestless celebrations are good ``because people
realize it isn't just them out there and someone on the altar, but
it should be group participation.''
   Still, the bishops said, having a priest ``who acts in the
person of Christ'' celebrate Mass remains the ideal.
   ``In the outlying communities, that's where they touch base with
the church on a once-a-week basis,'' Hayes said. ``They don't have
an experience of church other than that.''
   Why does he spend his weekend driving hundreds of miles across
two counties in Wyoming to say Mass in small, agricultural
communities like Sundance and Upton and Hulett for a total of less
than 200 people?
   ``To answer the Lord's call to take his message to the ends of
the Earth,'' Hayes said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, Dec. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
