<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Boatman Adv15-17   11-28 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Boatman, Adv 15-17,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 15-17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Michael Boatman Deals With Dark Side on `China Beach'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On ABC's ``China Beach,'' Michael Boatman's
Samuel Beckett is frequently shunned because he works among the
dead of the Vietnam War.
   Beckett is assigned to the Graves Registration Unit, where he
prepares those killed in action for return to this country.
   ``He gives people the creeps,'' said Boatman. ``People are
suspicious. They don't want to see this guy after their buddies got
killed. So, except for his close friends, people don't talk to him.
   ``He spends most of his time by himself. So, not only is he
sentenced to this horrible duty, but he's sentenced to do it
alone.''
   Beckett may be television's first mortician since Digger O'Dell
on the original ``Life of Riley'' in 1949-50. Beckett has a wry
sense of humor, but Digger was played for laughs on the comedy
series starring Jackie Gleason.
   He is not, however, the only character named after the Irish
playwright. Scott Bakula's time-traveling character on NBC's
``Quantum Leap'' is also named Sam Beckett. The only reference on
``China Beach'' to the real Beckett, who wrote ``Waiting For
Godot,'' was an episode called ``Waiting For Beckett.''
   ``The way it was explained to me, a frustrated playwright in the
Army was in charge of assigning duties,'' said Boatman. ``When a
guy named Samuel Beckett came along he thought it was amusing to
put him in Graves Registration.'' Duties of that job were to count
casualties each day, record the cause of death and make sure
personal effects were sent to the family.
   ``We take some liberties on the show. He works as a mortician
and he writes letters to the families. In reality, he wouldn't be
doing all that.''
   Beckett recently ended a relationship with a Vietnamese woman
played by Elizabeth Lindsey. At the beginning of this season, when
the writers asked the actors to suggest stories for their
characters, Boatman said he had heard of rear echelon soldiers who
suffered from ``survivor's guilt.'' They had desk jobs and felt
they were irrelevant to the war.
   ``I thought it would be interesting if Beckett goes into the
bush,'' Boatman said. ``He's suffering from `survivor's guilt' and
decides to go out. He says he's not in the action. He's in the
results. He thinks he can make a difference and keep somebody from
becoming a casualty.
   ``Beckett's going through a transition. He's still shocked and
horrified by the things he sees. He hasn't become numbed to it.
He's still shocked, but he realizes now he can make it. He's
finding ways to function. He has a perspective of the war other
people don't see or want to see. He's there with death every day.''
   Boatman can't seem to escape military connections. He was born
on an Army base in Colorado during his father's military service.
He also spent a brief time in Germany but grew up in Chicago and
its suburbs.
   His first movie was ``Hamburger Hill,'' in which he played a
soldier in Vietnam.
   ``I was a grunt in the picture,'' he said. ``It was based on a
true story about the assault on Hill 937. It was a big controversy
because hundreds of men were lost in taking the hill. Then it was
abandoned as having no tactical value.''
   Boatman had no interest in acting until high school, when he was
persuaded to try out for a school play. He was cast in one of the
leads and an acting career replaced plans to become a marine
biologist. He studied acting at Western Illinois University and
went from there directly into ``Hamburger Hill.''
   After four months of filming in the jungles of the Philippines,
he moved to New York.
   ``I did an off-Broadway play called `Something About That Face'
that had only one performance,'' he said. ``Then nothing for a
while. I handed out fliers on the street and worked as a security
guard. Working as a guard was the worst job I've ever had in my
life. I was resented because I had a college degree and had done a
movie. They knew I wouldn't stay long.''
   He's an avid collector of comic books and video animation from
Japan.
   ``I started collecting in kindergarten,'' he said. ``I've had
several collections. I lost my first in a flood. I had to sell my
second collection in college because I was desperate for money. It
was worth about $800 and I sold it for $90. The guy really took
advantage of me. Later, I was foolish enough to buy some of the
books back at his prices.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 15-17</NOTE>
</DOC>
