<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 2146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i BC-Asia-1990s Adv03-2Takes   11-28 0951</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asia-1990s, Adv 03-2 Takes,0977</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Asia Faces New Challenges in Politics and Development in 1990s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After emerging as the world's most vibrant
region in the 1980s, Asia faces the tricky task of maintaining its
double-time march toward prosperity while grappling with a
potential crisis of leadership in the new decade.
   Political stars of the 1980s, such as Deng Xiaoping in China and
Corazon Aquino in the Philippines, may soon leave the world stage
with their work in danger of unraveling.
   Other stories to watch for in the coming decade will be the
economic emergence of Vietnam, greater regional cooperation in
Asia, and the fate of Hong Kong as it switches from British to
Chinese sovereignty.
   Asia has plenty to be proud of as the 1980s draw to a close.
Japan has the world's No. 2 economy after the United States, and
the four ``little dragons'' _ South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong and
Singapore _ have seen dizzying export-led growth that has averaged
9 percent annually in the past generation.
   Further economic growth seems assured for Japan. A large pool of
capital for investment in factory expansion already has the United
States bracing for a new Japanese export wave.
   Much of Japan's plant and equipment investment is going into new
technology, product development and labor-saving automation,
according to Fuji Research Institute Corp., ensuring Japan will
remain highly competitive.
   But Fuji also predicts that as the United States continues to
demand Japan open its markets, ``there is a strong possibility that
the (trade) surplus will gradually shrink over the next three or
four years.''
   If that happens, the institute said, economic friction between
the two giants could focus on Japanese investment in the United
States. Sony Corp.'s takeover of Columbia Pictures and the purchase
of Rockefeller Center in New York by Mitsubishi Estate Co. already
have raised eyebrows.
   The ``little dragons'' also want continued growth but know that
their economic formula for the 1980s is outdated. Rising wages mean
that labor-intensive, low-technology factories must give way to
more advanced industry.
   In Taiwan, for example, shoe and textile plants are being
replaced by factories making computer chips and other
high-technology components.
   The region's basic manufacturing base has begun to shift toward
Southeast Asia, where a second generation of ``little dragons'' is
coming to life with cheap and plentiful labor.
   Thailand has become the region's most dynamic economy, according
to Miron Mushkat, chief regional economist for Baring Securities
Ltd. of Hong Kong. Annual growth rates are expected to continue for
at least several more years in the 5 percent to 10 percent region.
   Much of the capital fueling growth in Southeast Asia is from
cash-rich Japan and Taiwan, which have billions of dollars to burn.
   Japanese aid to Thailand, for example, was $859 million last
year, up from $48 million in 1985.
   And the Philippines is risking diplomatic trouble with China by
courting business from Beijing's political rival, Taiwan, which
invested $123 million in the first half of 1989, up one-fourth from
the same period a year earlier.
   As Southeast Asia develops, all eyes will be on Vietnam, which
could become the continent's next economic frontier. With Vietnam's
announced pullout of its troops from Cambodia, Western aid and
investment could soon pour into what has been one of the world's
most impoverished economies.
   ``Vietnam will take off in a flurry,'' once the United States
drops its trade embargo, says Robert Broadfoot, managing director
of Hong Kong-based Risk Consultancy Ltd.
   Foreign businessmen now fly into the Communist nation each day.
As a possible sign of things to come, Vietnam has emerged this year
as the world's third largest exporter of rice, after Thailand and
the United States.
   Markets for Vietnam and other expanding Asian economies will
increasingly be within the region, particularly if Europe becomes a
more difficult trade partner after the Common Market unifies in
1992.
   That has triggered talk about increased regional cooperation.
Foreign and trade ministers from 12 Pacific Rim countries,
including the United States, met in Australia in November to
discuss the issue.
   ``We now see conditions ripening for cooperation, as the
prospect of economic advance provides positive incentives for
collaboration,'' Richard H. Solomon, assistant secretary of state
for East Asian and Pacific Affairs, recently told a Hong Kong
audience.
   The ministers' meeting agreed to act in concert to secure
international trade reforms but ruled out formation of an Asian
Pacific trading bloc to counter restrictions that may come from the
European market.
   Experts now envision development of a regional forum, perhaps at
the ministerial level, under which Asian nations could issue
general statements or consult with each other in times of crisis.
   Greater cooperation may not be feasible. ``Asia is very
fragmented, it lacks strong political leadership'' needed to
``sustain and galvanize a regional movement,'' explains Mushkat.
   Perhaps the greatest challenge facing Asia in the 1990s is a
potential crisis of national leadership.
   Nowhere is this more obvious than in China, where jockeying has
already begun to head the post-Deng Xiaoping era.
   Deng, 85, recently retired from his last Communist Party post
and has been trying to rally support around party chief Jiang Zemin
as his heir apparent. But Jiang's power base remains weak and it is
not clear who will rule once Deng dies.
   No matter who governs China's 1.1 billion people in the 1990s,
they will face enormous obstacles such as corruption, rising
unemployment, and lack of raw materials and energy.
   They also will have to contend with aspirations for political
change that exploded during the spring pro-democracy movement but
were crushed, at least temporarily, by the military crackdown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
