<DOCNO> AP891128-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 2147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i BC-Asia-1990s Adv03-1stAdd   11-28 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asia-1990s, Adv03-1st Add,0912</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>HONG KONG: military crackdown.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The future of Deng's decade of market-oriented economic reforms,
under which China's economy staged a remarkable recovery after the
ruinous 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, is particularly murky.
   ``To get rich is glorious'' was the phrase that moved the masses
in the 1980s, but it has fallen out of favor with the ascendancy
this year of ideological hard-liners.
   If conservatives such as Premier Li Peng win the power struggle,
the open-door policy would slow and more emphasis would be placed
on central planning, which would be bitterly opposed by coastal
regions that prospered greatly during Deng's reforms.
   China's uncertain future was summed up recently by U.S.
Ambassador to Beijing James Lilley, who said: ``It may be some
years before we can put a name or theme to the new chapter China
will write in the 1990s. In the meantime, we must be prepared for
twists and turns that may defy attempts'' at labeling.
   A crisis also could occur in the Philippines, a fledgling
democracy where President Corazon Aquino has said she will not seek
re-election when her term expires in 1992. No strong candidate has
emerged as her heir apparent on the politically fractured
archipelago.
   Singapore's President Lee Kuan Yew, Malaysia's Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and Indonesia's President Suharto are strong
leaders who also may leave the scene in the coming years.
   ``Every leader but one will change'' in the region, said
Broadfoot. He expects only the Sultan of Brunei to still be in
power at the turn of the century.
   One territory that is almost assured of a rough decade is Hong
Kong, which Britain will hand over to China in 1997.
   Fewer and fewer of the colony's 5.7 million people have faith in
Communist China's promise that Hong Kong can maintain its
capitalist lifestyle for 50 years and enjoy a ``high degree of
autonomy,'' particularly since the suppression of the pro-democracy
movement in Beijing.
   Huge numbers of people uncertain about the future are emigrating
from Hong Kong. A foreign passport is the most prized possession in
the colony, and residents are sparing no effort to secure one.
Marriage counselors report booming business from people desperately
seeking foreign national spouses.
   The government, in estimates often criticized as too
conservative, believes 42,000 people will emigrate in 1989 and
another 55,000 will leave the following year.
   Many highly educated white-collar workers are among those
leaving, leading to a brain drain that could reduce the territory's
economic competitiveness.
   Adding to the territory's headache are the approximately 57,000
Vietnamese boat people who have sailed to Hong Kong seeking asylum.
The squalid camps in which they are housed could erupt in violence
if the government carries through plans to send most of them back
to their homeland against their will.
   Two of the other ``little dragons'' _ Taiwan and South Korea _
show promise for furthering what Mushkat calls ``the slow and
painful process'' of democratic change in Asia, which has a long
history of authoritarian rule.
   For example, the ruling Nationalist Party is slowly giving up
its monopoly on political power in Taiwan.
   ``Democratization shall not move backward in Taiwan unless the
economy collapses or in case of a war, neither of which looks very
likely,'' said Lu Ya-li, a political commentator at National Taiwan
University.
   But Taiwan may experience some social instability because of a
problem also faced by South Korea and Japan _ a population that has
not seen its standard of living increase as quickly as national
wealth.
   Property prices have skyrocketed in Taiwan, and most
middle-class families have lost all chance of buying their own
homes. Crime has increased to the point where sales of luxury
foreign cars have fallen sharply because businessmen say the
vehicles make them targets of blackmail.
   In Japan, the average person lives in cramped housing, suffers a
long commute through congested traffic and pays prices 20 percent
to 30 percent higher than in other industrial nations.
   Says Broadfoot: ``You'll see a much greater emphasis on quality
of life in Northeast Asia'' during the 1990s.
   In Southeast Asia, the 1990s will begin with a number of thorny
security issues, including the Cambodian civil war in which the
genocidal Khmer Rouge is among several groups fighting for power.
   Washington will be negotiating the future of six U.S. military
bases on the Philippines whose lease expires in 1991. Many
influential politicians oppose the bases, and there has been some
indication of growing sentiment in the Philippines' armed forces
against the U.S. facilities.
   But perhaps the most interesting security question will be what
Tokyo does to protect its growing economic interests in the region.
   Broadfoot sees Japan likely flexing greater military strength.
``I don't think the United States will be able to continue to be
the defense umbrella of Asia to the extent that it has been,'' he
said.
   A stronger Japanese military will undoubtedly rekindle painful
memories throughout the region of Tokyo's efforts to carve a
subservient Great East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere during the World
War II era.
   Japan may choose to protect its investment through the use of
foreign aid designed to promote stability in the region, but that
could help create a zone of influence that also could lead to
anti-Japanese sentiment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 3</NOTE>
