<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   11-28 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Adventures of Baron Munchausen'' (RCA-Columbia Home Video.
VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated PG)
   
   Baron Karl Friedrich Hieronymus von Munchausen was a German
solider and adventurer who lived in the 18th century. He also was a
master prevaricator whose tales would make Paul Bunyon's munchkin
size.
   Terry Gilliam, a founding member of the irreverent Monty Python
troupe, has taken this legendary liar and made ``The Adventures of
Baron Munchausen,'' the third in his fantasy triology that includes
``Time Bandits'' and ``Brazil.'' But where ``Time Bandits''
primarily had a comedic appeal to youngsters and ``Brazil'' tapped
more philosophical and political chords, ``Baron Munchausen'' is a
priceless romp with more visual effects and excursions into pure
fantasy than any movie in memory. There's even an unbilled cameo by
Robin Williams as the King of the Moon.
   The story opens in ``late 18th century, the Age of Reason,
Wednesday,'' with an attack on an ancient city by the ferocious
forces of the Ottoman Empire. A play about the baron is under way
at a local theater but the real baron is in the audience and takes
issue with the mockery on stage.
   The movie soon becomes the baron's story, and the spectacle is
nonstop: a hot-air trip in a balloon made of ladies' knickers that
takes the baron (John Neville) and Sally Salt (Sarah Polley), a
little girl who believes in imagination, to the moon and heaven;
heads that separate from bodies; a Venus rising from a half-shell,
complete with little angels with little wings; sea monsters;
strange trees; creatures.
   But there's so much more in Gilliam's odyssey. The film is a
wondrous and brilliant work whose underpinnings tap the very
essence of imagination and conformity. The rigid bureaucrat Horatio
Jackson (Jonathan Pryce) questions the place of fancy, imagination
and dreamers in the age of reason. There isn't one, he says.
   Fairy tales, however, never die.
   Charles McKeown, who also has the dual role of Rupert and
Adolphus, wrote the masterful screenplay with Gilliam. Eric Idle
appears as Desmond and Berthold and Oliver Reed is Vulcan.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Mighty Quinn'' (CBS-Fox Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98)
   
   Xavier Quinn (Denzel Washington) is the island-born police chief
of a Caribbean country ruled by a puppet governor and white
American money interests. His childhood pal, Maubee (Robert
Townsend), is something of thorn in the community's side.
   Maubee also is an impish bad boy who loves living on the edge, a
Peter Pan with all the special skills of a ninja.
   Maubee is the prime suspect in the slaying of a wealthy
American. But only the governor and the Americans believe Maubee to
be the killer. Quinn's investigation is hampered by the CIA, the
governor, South American interests and the White House, but he
doggedly unravels the mystery and discovers the murderer.
   With a wonderful reggae soundtrack and the scenic beauty of Port
Antonio, Jamaica, ``The Mighty Quinn'' is a smooth and exciting
romp. There also are some great performances by Washington,
Townsend and the supporting cast.
   This is a must video to own or to rent. But if you rent it,
you'll want to take it out more than once.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
