<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-28 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0830</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Existing-home sales remained steady last month
at their highest level since January, a real estate trade group
said, and analysts expect single-digit mortgage rates to sustain
sales well into 1990.
   The National Association of Realtors said Monday that sales of
existing single-family homes totaled a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 3.52 million, the same as September's revised rate and the
highest since January's 3.55 million rate.
   The September rate was 1.2 percent above August's 3.48 million
sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new North American-made cars and trucks
fell 4.4 percent in mid-November from the same period last year,
automakers reported in the latest indication of their industry's
weakness.
   The industry's lengthening sales slump could mean automakers
will lengthen their year-end factory shutdowns in an attempt to
trim production and deflate an inventory backlog, analysts said
Monday.
   The eight major companies making cars and light trucks in North
America said they sold an average of 31,032 vehicles daily during
the Nov. 11-20 period, compared with a daily rate of 32,466 during
the year-earlier period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union are on
the verge of reviving normal trade relations as their leaders meet
in this weekend's summit, though it could be years before trading
practices catch up with the political changes sweeping the
Communist bloc.
   Trade between the two superpowers will be a primary topic of
discussion at the Mediterranean shipboard summit meeting between
President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community Commission said
it has signed a trade and economic cooperation accord with the
Soviet Union that goes beyond similar deals signed in the past 14
months with Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia.
   The pact provides for a gradual lifting of import quotas on
Soviet industrial goods by 1995 and cites a dozen areas in which
the two sides plan to establish economic cooperation, an EC source
said Monday. These include science and technology, banking,
transport, agriculture, environmental protection, energy, raw
materials and mining.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court refused to allow New York
City, and perhaps other communities, to enlist unwilling developers
in the fight against homelessness.
   The justices left intact Monday a victory for developers who
said New York City violated their rights by banning conversion or
demolition of hotels that offer a haven for the poor, elderly and
ill.
   The court let stand a ruling that a law banning conversion or
demolition of New York City's single-room-occupancy housing
unconstitutionally confiscates private property.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mainstream merchants widely are offering
discounts to court shoppers during the critical holiday season, but
off-price retailers are fighting back with broadened selections and
promotions of their own.
   Off-price chains say their strategy of seizing opportunities to
buy attractively priced merchandise from manufacturers has put them
in an especially strong position to compete for customer dollars
this Christmas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. said it was seeking
to oust the board of directors of Great Northern Nekoosa Corp.,
which has advised shareholders to reject Georgia-Pacific's $3.6
billion buyout offer for the paper company.
   Georgia-Pacific stated Monday it was soliciting shareholder
consents for a special meeting at which Great Northern shareholders
would vote on whether to remove the board.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A move by International Business Machines Corp.
to reduce the electromagnetic radiation emitted by computer screens
does not go far enough, some critics said.
   IBM was praised Monday for taking the lead in reducing very low
frequency radiation, but several advocates of radiation reduction
said the company had neglected to do anything about the extremely
low frequency spectrum.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sale of now-worthless bonds through
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association flagrantly violated federal
securities rules, the chairman of the House Banking Committee
charged.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, whose panel is investigating
the collapse of Lincoln, said Monday a recently discovered memo
written by a senior Lincoln official indicates ``numerous
violations'' of regulations.
   They include the payment of prohibited sales bonuses to bond
salespeople and the participation of Lincoln employees in the sales.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market followed through on its Thanksgiving-week rally
with another advance Monday as traders debated the prospects for
lower interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose
19.42 points to 2,694.97.
   The dollar fell sharply against most major foreign currencies as
traders anticipated a further decline in U.S. interest rates.
   Government bond prices dropped as the Federal Reserve drained
reserves from the banking system.
   Gold prices plummeted; cotton futures plunged the permitted
daily limit; soybeans were down sharply; oil futures retreated; and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
