<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     11-28 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction to their highest level in two
weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $8 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 7.63 percent, up from 7.61 percent last
week. Another $8 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average
discount rate of 7.45 percent, up from 7.40 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since Nov. 13 when three-month bills
sold for 7.68 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.51 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.89 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,807.10 and 7.85 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,623.40.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 7.64
percent last week, down from 7.71 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OffPriceShopping Bjt   11-28 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Off Price Shopping, Bjt,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Off-Price Stores Hoping To Capitalize on Bargain-Hunting Shoppers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Marshalls,'' no apostrophe, is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Off-price retailers are poised to take advantage
of the annual search for holiday gifts that won't bust personal
budgets.
   They say their practice of seizing opportunities to buy
attractively priced merchandise from manufacturers has enabled them
to broaden their selections, putting them in an especially strong
position to compete for customer dollars this Christmas.
   ``We have found quite an abundance of terrific merchandise in
the marketplace,'' Steven Wishner, vice president and treasurer of
retailer TJX Cos. Inc., said Monday.
   There have been more chances for them to get good buys this
autumn. In some cases, apparel suppliers that balked at shipping to
department store chains owned by financially troubled Campeau Corp.
_ worried that the cash-needy parent company would be slow in
paying _ opted to unload their goods with off-price outlets.
   ``Manufacturers are much more interested in working with the
off-pricers than ever before,'' said Jane Maxwell, a spokeswoman
for Marshalls, the nation's biggest off-price chain.
   ``When an opportunity became available, we were there to buy. We
were very well poised to take advantage of anything that did come
up,'' she said. ``When a big department store cancels an order,
we're right there to pick it up.''
   Marshalls, an Andover, Mass.-based unit of Melville Corp., and
other off-price merchants sell national brands of clothing and
designer labels at significantly smaller markups than department
stores, specialty retailers and other conventional, full-price
retailers.
   In contrast, discounters such as K mart and the Target division
of Dayton Hudson Corp. mainly carry their own private labels of
apparel or lesser-known brands, sometimes with a limited selection
of national names at reduced prices.
   The fight for market share between conventional retailers and
off-pricers always is fierce, particularly during the holiday
shopping season, which can account for more than half of a
retailer's annual profit. At the peak spending season, shoppers who
normally don't patronize off-price stores may do so in an effort to
stay within their budgets _ especially during slow economic growth.
   The battle lines have blurred lately because regular retailers
are relying heavily on price cuts to boost traffic and capitalize
on the seasonal surge in spending, a tactic industry analysts think
is a must if stores hope to woo reluctant consumers.
   ``We are expecting a restrained shopping climate to prevail in
which people will be very, very thoughtful about the way they spend
money and will look for incentives before making a purchase,'' said
retail consultant Kurt Barnard.
   Meanwhile, off-price chains are touting their expanded offerings
and their consistently lower prices in hopes of winning a larger
following.
   Marshalls has been pushing key items aggressively through
television and radio spots. Designer jogging suits, plus ladies
sweaters and silk blouses recently have been featured in Marshalls'
ads.
   Wishner said TJX has been running special advertisements to
highlight its merchandise and its T.J. Maxx stores are winding down
a 10-day promotional blitz. Besides its 337 T.J. Maxx stores,
Framingham, Mass.-based TJX owns 534 Hit or Miss women's clothing
stores and Chadwick's of Boston, a women's off-price fashion mail
order catalog.
   Rather than hurting the off-price chains, the sporadic
discounting at department stores over the past several months has
played into the hands of these retailers.
   ``It has not worked to our disadvantage,'' said Ms. Maxwell of
Marshalls. She said consumers are getting confused about what is a
fair price; by slashing prices department stores have given the
impression that their prices were too high in the first place.
   Burlington Coat Factory Warehouse Corp., one of the country's
largest outerwear retailers that also has extensive mens, womens
and childrens clothing departments, picked up merchandise from
vendors with whom it normally didn't do much business.
   Robert LaPenta, chief financial officer of the Burlington,
N.J.-based company, said in the past suppliers waited to fill
Burlington orders until after they had satisfied department store
customers. This year, vendors have been more willing to supply
Burlington early.
   ``We were there for them,'' LaPenta said. ``We think that is
going to help us into the future. This might be the opportunity to
develop some relationships that can carry us into the '90s.''
   For this year, off-price chains hope they will have an edge over
their full-price competitors by being better stocked to meet demand.
   ``We hear that the department stores don't have the goods to do
the business through the season,'' LaPenta said. ``We definitely
have the inventory.''
</TEXT>
