<FIRST>r f PM-Brady     11-28 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brady,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary To Undergo Hip Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F.Brady, who has
been plagued in recent months by arthritis, will undergo elective
surgery on Dec. 14 to replace his right hip, the Treasury
Department announced.
   The surgery, to be performed in an undisclosed location, has
been planned for a long time, said a department official who
declined to be identified. Recovery should take three to six weeks,
he said Monday.
   Deputy Secretary John Robson will serve as acting secretary,
Brady said in a memo to top department officials.
   Despite his absence until mid-January, Brady will remain in
touch with Treasury officials and take part in major decisions just
has he does when traveling outside the capital, the department
official said.
   With then-Vice President Bush's support, Brady was named
Treasury secretary in August 1988, succeeding James A. Baker III in
the final five months of the Reagan administration after Baker
resigned to head Bush's presidential campaign.
   As expected, Bush kept Brady, a close friend and political ally,
in the post after his election.
