<FIRST>r f PM-GreatNorthern     11-28 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Great Northern,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia-Pacific Steps Up Attack on Great Northern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. wants shareholders
of Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. to vote quickly on an unsolicited,
$3.6 billion tender offer for the paper company while considering
the removal of Great Northern's directors.
   Great Northern, which has refused to negotiate with
Georgia-Pacific, promised a vigorous defense to the new attack.
   The latest round in the dispute came Monday as Georgia-Pacific
filed more papers in federal court, seeking a shareholder vote on
the buyout offer within weeks instead of months. Georgia-Pacific
also announced it would run advertisements asking shareholders to
demand a special meeting at which the Great Northern executives
could be ousted.
   ``It's clearly time to let Great Northern's shareholders speak
for themselves, since their board obviously does not speak for
them,'' Georgia-Pacific Chairman T. Marshall Hahn Jr. said in a
statement released by his Atlanta headquarters.
   In papers filed in U.S. District Court, Georgia-Pacific asked
for a temporary restraining order and a preliminary injunction that
would force a Great Northern shareholder meeting to be moved up
from March 20 to sometime within the next 30 days for a vote on the
tender offer.
   Georgia-Pacific also seeks to force Great Northern to disclose
to the Securities and Exchange Commission any steps it might be
taking to alter its financial structure to make a takeover more
difficult.
   Great Northern, based in Norwalk, Conn., but incorporated in
Maine, called Georgia-Pacific's motion ``entirely meritless'' and
``an effort to divert attention from the illegal and ill-conceived
nature of Georgia-Pacific's takeover effort.''
   ``In essence, Georgia-Pacific is asking the court to give
shareowners less time to consider the merits of each side's
position,'' Great Northern spokesman Stephen M. Hill said in a
statement.
   Great Northern has refused to negotiate with Georgia-Pacific
since it made a tender offer of $58 per share last month, then
raised the offer to $63 per share this month. Great Northern said
the offer would not be good for shareholders and that it would
violate antitrust laws.
   Georgia-Pacific spokeswoman Gail Smith said that under Maine
law, if at least one-third of the shareholders request a special
meeting for voting on removal of the directors, the meeting must be
called within 60 days.
   Hill said his company had not seen a copy of Georgia-Pacific's
request for any such meeting, and so he had no immediate comment.
   Hahn was to meet in Augusta today with Gov. John R. McKernan and
Attorney General James E. Tierney in separate sessions.
   Maine officials have sought assurances from both companies that
any merger would not cost any state residents their jobs or put
valuable woodlands in the hands of developers.
   Hahn has balked at making any promises, saying that since he
does not have access to Great Northern's inside information on its
Maine holdings, he cannot say for sure what Georgia-Pacific will do
if it wins the takeover battle.
</TEXT>
