<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   11-28 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Sales Continue Slump, Making Layoffs a Growing Possibility</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales remained weak in
mid-November, down 4.4 percent compared with the same time last
year, making extended manufacturing layoffs around Christmas a
growing possibility, analysts said.
   The eight major automakers with U.S. assembly plants said Monday
they sold vehicles at an average rate of 31,032 a day during the
Nov. 11-20 period this year compared with a daily pace of 32,466
vehicles during the same time last year.
   Car sales slumped 6.1 percent and light truck sales declined 1.8
percent for the period.
   The decline may seem small compared with some double-digit
tumbles a few weeks ago, but a large percentage of the cars being
sold now are going to fleets such as rental car companies and large
corporations, said analyst John Kirnan of Kidder Peabody &amp; Co. in
New York.
   ``About 40 percent (of the sales) in the first 50 days of a
model year are fleet sales,'' Kirnan said. ``It basically means
that the individual has not been in the market.
   ``Come the first quarter (of 1990) we'll have a better sense of
whether the market is really as weak as we may be seeing now,'' he
said.
   Between now and then, automakers are likely to shy away from
large-scale increases in their incentive programs, opting instead
for longer Christmas and New Year holiday shutdowns to help control
new car inventories, analysts said.
   ``I think they are finding the incentives didn't work, so they
are cutting back production,'' said analyst Mary Anne Sudol of
Fitch Investors Service Inc. in New York.
   During the first nine months of this year, automakers shuffled
incentive packages at a nearly dizzying pace. But by the time the
1990 models began appearing in showrooms in October, many of the
incentive packages had been trimmed for the new cars.
   Contributing to the sales decline were higher prices for the
1990 models due in large part, the companies said, to such
government-mandated safety devices as driver-side air bags and
automatic seat belts.
   The double wallop of higher prices and lower incentives pushed
consumers into buying 1989 models in August and September, analysts
and company officials have said.
   The sales numbers reported Monday were not surprising, Kirnan
said.
   ``The industry has anticipated the weakness in the present
quarter because of what happened in the summer, the big blowout
sales and consumers taking advantage of the pricing on the '89
models,'' he said.
   Through Nov. 20, car and truck sales from manufacturers with
U.S. plants were 2.6 percent behind last year's pace. Car sales
were down 3.6 percent and truck sales were off 0.8 percent.
   Ford Motor Co. said sales of its vehicles were down 13 percent
in mid-November, with car sales falling 11.6 percent and truck
sales off 14.8 percent. For the year, Ford's vehicle sales were
down 2.5 percent.
   Chrysler Corp.'s cars and trucks sold at a pace 3.3 percent
slower in mid-November this year compared with the same time last
year. A 12 percent drop in its car sales was offset by a 6 percent
increase in its light truck sales.
   Chrysler's year-to-date car and truck sales were 6.4 percent
behind last year.
   General Motors Corp. said its mid-November car sales were down
13 percent while its truck sales were up 4.1 percent, combining for
a 7.3 percent decline for its vehicles during the period. For the
year, GM's car and truck sales were down 5 percent from last year.
</TEXT>
