<DOCNO> AP891128-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0817EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Miller&amp;Rhoads     11-28 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miller &amp; Rhoads,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Department Store Chain to Sell All Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The end of the line may be near for the
104-year-old Miller &amp; Rhoads department store chain, which has
abandoned a plan to reorganize under bankruptcy law and says it
wants to sell all its assets.
   ``If Miller &amp; Rhoads cannot continue as a viable retail entity,
then it's best that this action be taken,'' President John E.
Stokely told a news conference Monday at the company's flagship
store in downtown Richmond.
   Stokely said the Richmond-based chain had filed a plan earlier
in the afternoon in U.S. Bankruptcy Court that ``contemplates the
sale of all assets.''
   Miller &amp; Rhoads had 14 stores in July when it filed for
protection from its creditors to enable it to reorganize under
Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy code. The company has since begun
arrangements to rid itself of six of its less profitable stores.
   The company's ``current circumstances and financial condition
led the board of directors to conclude that a reorganization as a
profitable going concern is not feasible,'' Stokely said.
   He said negotiations are continuing to sell four of the eight
remaining outlets to May Department Stores Co. of St. Louis. May,
which operates 14 department store chains around the country, is
interested in Miller &amp; Rhoads stores at Lynnhaven Mall in Virginia
Beach, Greenbrier Mall in Chesapeake, and Chesterfield and Regency
malls in suburban Richmond, he said.
   ``The nature of these negotiations is such that they could be
consummated tomorrow, next week ... or never,'' he said.
   Hecht's, a department store chain owned by May, planned to hold
a news conference today in Washington, but Stokely said he did not
know if the subject would involve a possible purchase of Miller &amp;
Rhoads stores.
   Stokely estimated it would take four to six months to complete
the sale of all Miller &amp; Rhoads assets, and said none of the sales
transactions would be completed before the end of January.
   The chain will operate normally through the Christmas season,
Stokely said.
   ``All customer services will remain intact, including
after-Christmas returns and refunds,'' he said.
   Stokely said factors affecting Miller &amp; Rhoads' decision to sell
its assets included a weakness in the retail industry, inventory
levels, financing and the company's debt level.
   ``I'm disappointed. Certainly, everybody in the company is
disappointed,'' he said.
   He said jobs should be available to the majority of the
company's approximately 2,000 employees through the sale of the
chain's properties to other retailers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
