<FIRST>u f PM-Chevron-ESOP 1stLd-Writethru   11-28 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chevron-ESOP, 1st Ld - Writethru,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chevron Announces Creation Of Employee Stock Ownership Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling to `Ilacqua' sted `Illacqua.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Corp.'s creation of a leveraged
employee stock ownership plan will likely decrease the chances of a
takeover of the oil giant, analysts say.
   ``It improves the company's defenses,'' said Rosario Ilacqua, an
analyst with New York-based Nikko Securities. ``In a real showdown
with someone they (employees) will vote for their management rather
than with someone from without. People are afraid they will lose
their jobs.''
   The announcement of the ESOP plan on Monday follows weeks of
speculation that Chevron is ripe for takeover, possibly by Pennzoil
Co.
   But a spokesman for Chevron, the world's sixth largest oil
company and the nation's largest petroleum refiner, denied the move
was intended to thwart a possible takeover.
   ``We did not do this as a defensive measure. We have been
examining the feasibility of an ESOP since April when we created a
task force to look into it,'' said spokesman Larry Shushan. He
declined to comment on takeover rumors.
   He said the program was created as a low-cost means of paying
for part of employee benefits.
   Shushan said the company had put the idea on hold until Congress
last week passed legislation preserving the tax deduction on
dividends paid by a corporation on shares held by such a plan.
   The plan will eventually place 16 percent of the oil company's
stock in the ownership of its employees. It envisions an employee
trust spending $1 billion to add about 5 percent of Chevron's 342
million shares to the 11 percent already held by the company's
profit-sharing plan.
   Under the ESOP, which will be part of Chevron's Profit
Sharing-Savings Plan, the company will sell stock to its employees
and then buy a comparable amount on the open market. Chevron's
Profit Sharing plan holds about 11 percent of the company's
outstanding stock.
   The ESOP trust will borrow $1 billion from banks and use the
money to buy newly issued shares of Chevron common stock from the
corporation.
   The new shares, which are about 5 percent of Chevron's 342
million outstanding shares, will be held by the leveraged ESOP
Trust, the company said. They will be allocated to employee
accounts in May when Chevron makes its profit sharing distribution
for the first quarter of 1990, to non-union employees. The plan
will be offered to union workers through the collective bargaining
process, Shushan said.
   Chevron's stock closed Monday at 68\ per share on the New York
Stock Exchange, up 3\. The stock has sold as high as 69 in recent
weeks.
   Analysts said the rise in Chevron stock since takeover
speculation began is not surprising since the stock has been
undervalued in recent years. Chevron's stock has risen about 48
percent this year.
   Chevron, rich in oil and gas reserves and a high-performing
chemicals unit, had sales in 1988 of $28.9 billion, down from $29.1
billion in 1987. Earnings last year totaled $1.8 billion, or $5.17
a share, up about 40 percent from $1.3 billion, or $3.65 a share.
   Some analysts say that in a breakup, Chevron's assets could be
worth $100 to $125 a share - or about $40 billion.
   A published report Monday suggested that a group of investors
could be acting in concert to force Chevron into a restructuring
that would boost the stock further.
   A buyer, possibly a company acting alone or with partners, has
reportedly accumulated 12 million to 16 million shares of Chevron
stock, or 3.5 percent to 4.7 percent, according to USA Today.
Shushan declined to comment on the stock's purchaser, in accordance
with company policy.
   Pennzoil also declined to comment, but the Houston-based oil
company is rumored to be looking for a place to park some $2.5
billion in cash that it received in a 1988 settlement with Texaco
Inc. following a prolonged battle over Getty Oil Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
