<FIRST>d f BC-Britain-Grains     11-28 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Grains,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Grain Crop Estimates Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Wheat Council on Tuesday raised
its 1989-1990 estimate of world grain production to 1.346 billion
tons, up 4 million tons from last month's forecast of 1.342 billion.
   This would be well above last season's poor drought-hit harvest
of 1.231 billion tons, but still below estimated world consumption,
the council said.
   The council raised its figure for 1989-90 world production of
coarse grain, principally corn, to 816 million tons from 812
million forecast last month. Estimated 1988-89 output was 729
million tons.
   The estimated 1989-90 world wheat production was unchanged at
530 million tons, compared with 502 million last season.
   The council is sticking to its estimate of a 1989-90 Soviet
grain harvest of 205 million tons, compared with 195 million in
1989-90.
   It raised its projection of Soviet 1989-90 grain imports to 33
million tons compared with 31 million tons forecast last month and
estimated 1988-89 imports of 39 million tons.
   Soviet wheat imports are put at 11 million tons vs. 15 million
last season, and coarse grain at 20 million tons vs. 24 million
tons.
</TEXT>
