<FIRST>u f PM-DetroitNewspapers 1stLd-Writethru f0047 11-28 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0047,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions, Newspapers Reach Tentative Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, Newspaper and ..., with four grafs to UPDATE
with source information on agreement, salary background. Picks up 8th graf
pvs, The unions ... A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press reached a
tentative agreement with five unions today, ending the threat of a
strike that could have disrupted the start of their joint operating
agreement.
   ``We're delighted we have a settlement,'' said Robert Giles,
president and publisher of The News. ``We expected to able to work
it out on an amicable basis, and we did.''
   ``Now we can go full speed ahead,'' said Robert J. Hall,
publisher and chairman of the Free Press.
   The agreement was reached about 6:45 a.m. EST in a negotiating
session that began about late evening Monday.
   Joe Fundaro, interim secretary-treasurer of Teamsters Local 372,
which represents 1,100 workers in the merged circulation department
serving the two newspapers, said ratification meetings for union
members would be scheduled Sunday.
   ``It's the best that the unions felt they could achieve,'' said
Lou Mleczko, president of the Newspaper Guild Local 22,
representing about 900 editorial employees at the papers. ``We went
along with the recommendation of the Teamsters.''
   Terms of the tentative contract were not immediately released,
but The Detroit News quoted a union source today as saying the
two-year agreement would provide raises totaling $80 a week, plus
two-week bonuses.
   The unions sought raises totaling $110 weekly during a 2{-year
contract plus a three-week pay bonus, said Lou Mleczko, president
of the Newspaper Guild Local 22, representing editorial employees
at the papers.
   The average weekly salary of all workers at the two papers,
excluding benefits, is about $570, Hall said.
   Many employees have had only one raise since 1986, when News
owner Gannett Co. and Free Press owner Knight-Ridder Inc. announced
plans for a joint operating agreement.
   The unions had set a 12:01 a.m. Thursday strike deadline,
averting a walkout that could have delayed the long-stalled partial
merger between the nation's ninth- and tenth-largest newspapers.
   The joint operating agreement sought since 1986 began on
schedule Monday.
   The papers merged business, advertising, production and
circulation operations to cut costs, while retaining separate news
and editorial departments.
   The Free Press remains a morning newspaper, while the News will
generally have afternoon home deliveries. Weekend editions will be
jointly produced under the masthead of The Detroit News and Free
Press.
   The daily circulation of the News is 690,422 and 832,382 on
Sundays, and the Free Press' is 626,434 daily and 687,537 Sundays.
   The JOA's path was cleared of legal challenges from a coalition
of readers and advertisers when the U.S. Supreme Court tied 4-4 on
Nov. 13. The tie let stand lower court rulings that approved the
100-year deal.
   The Free Press, which lost millions of dollars in the past 10
years, was described as in danger of failing without the JOA. The
two papers say they have lost about $200 million in the past decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
