<FIRST>r f BC-CoalProduction     11-28 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coal Production,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Output Off Slightly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Coal Production-List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic coal production totaled 20.64
million tons during the week ending Nov. 18, down slightly from the
20.66 million tons produced in the previous week, the Department of
Energy reported Tuesday.
   The U.S. coal industry produced 19.9 million tons in the same
week last year, according to the department's Energy Information
Administration.
   West Virginia ranked first among the 27 coal-producing states
with 3.4 million tons produced in the period. Kentucky was second
at 3.39 million tons and Wyoming was third at 3.3 million, the
agency said.
   Domestic coal production so far this year is 862 million tons,
5.7 percent above last year's production at this time, the agency
said.
   The week's production accounts for bituminous and lignite coal.
</TEXT>
