<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rebounded in moderately active
trading today after early weakness as players continued to sort out
the prospects for lower interest rates.
   At noon EST, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 5.54
points at 2,700.51. An hour earlier, the blue-chip indicator was up
2.98 points.
   Philip Puccio, senior vice president at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., said the 2,700 mark on the Dow Jones Industrials
could prove to be an important psychological resistance level.
   ``If the Dow can break through 2,700, it will bring in some
buying,'' Puccio said shortly before the blue-chip indicator
penetrated 2,700.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 5 to 4 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 724 issues up, 568 down and 543
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 75.26 million shares.
   Wall Street analysts said market players continued to debate the
Federal Reserve's next move after the central bank surprised many
observers on Monday by draining reserves from the banking system.
The Fed action pushed short-term interest rates higher, dashing
widely held beliefs that it was easing credit.
   Nevertheless, investors remained generally optimistic that
interest rates are in an overall declining pattern, analysts said.
   ``Over the next couple months the perception is that rates have
to come down so there's no reason to get excited about short-term
action by the Fed,'' said Dennis Jarrett, technical analyst with
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.
   Foreign investors also were helping keep stock prices firm,
Puccio said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.44 to 191.57.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had
gained 0.14 to 374.18.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Chevron was down 1\ to
67, McDonalds was off [ to 32~ and Texas Utilities had lost { to
34\.
   Exxon, meanwhile, was up } to 47|, General Electric had gained }
to 62[ and Philip Morris was up \ to 41}.
