   The stock market sputtered in afternoon trading
today in generally featureless dealings.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 1.06 points to
2,696.03 at 2 p.m. EST. The blue-chip indicator was up 5.54 points
at noon.
   Advancing issues barely outnumbered decliners on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 713 issues up, 686 down and 526 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 113.96 million shares.
   The market stalled around midday after bouncing back in the
morning session from a weak opening. The Dow Jones Industrials
briefly pierced what some Wall Street observers said was a
psychological resistance level of 2,700 around noon then retreated.
   It was the first time since the Oct. 13 stock plunge that the
indicator penetrated the 2,700-point mark. The Dow Jones average
closed at 2,759.84 on Oct. 12.
   Analysts said that while investors are generally optimistic that
interest rates are in an overall declining pattern, the Fed's
recent action has left many confused.
   The Federal Reserve on Monday drained reserves from the banking
system in a move that surprised many observers. Last week, the Fed
added funds to the system, which many interpreted as a signal that
the central bank was easing credit. Monday's Fed action pushed the
federal funds rate higher.
   ``Over the next couple months the perception is that rates have
to come down so there's no reason to get excited about short-term
action by the Fed,'' said Dennis Jarrett, technical analyst with
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.04 to 191.09.
