<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grains and Soybeans Higher Despite Lack of News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade despite the lack of news to
influence trading.
   Soybean futures closed higher as traders reacted to a sense that
the market was oversold in the wake of Monday's sell-off of soybean
futures.
   ``There wasn't much selling in the market today, it was all done
yesterday,'' said analyst Dale Gustafson of Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. Prices plunged Monday on slack export sales and bearish
technical signals.
   Soybeans also received support from the Malaysian palm oil
market, where futures were higher yesterday after last week's
weakness, Gustafson said.
   Palm oil accounts for the largest share of edible vegetable oil
traded internationally. Its price has a big effect on soy oil
prices, Gustafson said.
   Wheat prices gained in the wake of the National Weather
Service's six- to 10-day forecast out Monday. The outlook calls for
continued dry weather in winter wheat crop areas.
   Corn prices were higher on expectations of another week of
strong export shipments, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was } cent lower to 1} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.06} a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 2} cents higher with December at $2.34\ a bushel; oats were
} cent to 1} cents higher with December $1.43} a bushel; soybeans
were a { cent to 3{ cents higher with January at $5.79{ cents a
bushel.
</TEXT>
