<FIRST>r f AM-Stello-Nuclear 1stLd-Writethru f0166 11-28 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stello-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0166,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Nominee Accepts `Interim' Post in Weapons Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs, `Stello's critics... with
Rocky Flats safety review; PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `After confirmation...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration's nominee to run nuclear
weapons production has taken a lower-ranking post in the arms
program until the Senate concludes its drawn-out hearings on the
nomination early next year, the Energy Department said Tuesday.
   In his new appointment as principal deputy assistant secretary
for defense programs, Victor Stello Jr. can work on the weapons
program without Senate confirmation.
   In an internal memorandum disclosing the appointment, Energy
Undersecretary John Tuck said Stello would hold his new title for
an ``interim period'' pending Senate action on his nomination as
assistant secretary for defense programs.
   Stello has been working for Energy Secretary James D. Watkins as
a special adviser on nuclear weapons matters since President Bush
announced his nomination last July. In that period, Stello remained
on the payroll of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, where he
served as executive director for operations.
   On Monday, Stello officially quit his NRC post to take the
Energy job, said Joseph Fouchard, a commission spokesman. Stello
worked for the NRC, which regulates commercial nuclear power, and
its predecessor the Atomic Energy Commission, for 24 years.
   The latest manuevering by Watkins stems from the political
controversy surrounding the Stello nomination. Several prominent
members of Congress, including some members of the Senate Armed
Services Committee that held confirmation hearings earlier this
month, claim Stello is unfit for the position.
   Stello's critics contend he lacks enough commitment to nuclear
safety and that his reputation for drawing controversy could
undermine the credibility of the weapons program at a time when
public trust in the program's safety is declining.
   In the latest sign of trouble in the weapons complex, the
department on Tuesday dispatched a high-level team of experts to
the Rocky Flats plutonium processing plant in Colorado to try to
resolve ``continuing safety concerns.''
   Watkins said ``this is a critical time at Rocky Flats,'' but did
not elaborate beyond saying federal and state officials had raised
unspecific safety issues at Rocky Flats, which already is under FBI
investigation for alleged environmental violations.
   After confirmation hearings on Stello Nov. 15 and 16, the Senate
Armed Servies Committee decided to postpone action until after
Congress reconvenes in January. The panel held open the possibility
that Stello would be asked to testify again.
   Tuck said the appointment was made after Watkins consulted with
Sens. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the Armed Services Committee chairman, and
John Warner of Virginia, the panel's ranking Republican.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ForeignWorkers     11-28 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Workers,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Farm Workers Protest Cheap Foreign Labor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Florida farm workers marched
outside a meeting of federal labor officials Tuesday to protest a
citrus company's plan to import hundreds of foreign pickers at
rock-bottom wages.
   ``It's nothing but legalized slave labor as far as we're
concerned,'' said farm labor organizer Fernando Cuevas, who led the
protest. ``There's no reason to bring in foreign workers when we've
already got too many American workers.''
   At issue is the federal government's H-2 program, which allows
foreign workers into the country to pick crops when domestic labor
is in short supply.
   The program was started under the Immigration Reform and Control
Act in 1987 after farmer complaints that legalization of many alien
workers in recent years had depleted their labor pool.
   Oakley Brothers Inc., a Lake Wales-based grower, has petitioned
the government to bring in 942 workers from Mexico in January to
pick citrus at a prevailing rate of 65 cents a box.
   ``Sixty-five cents is an absolute minimum rate that Oakley wants
to pay to everyone,'' said farm worker Tirso Moreno. ``It's not
that there's not enough American workers _ there's just not enough
who will work for 65 cents a box.''
   Moreno said other growers are paying seasonal rates ranging from
$1.03 to $1.23 a box.
   Cuevas claimed that growers such as Oakley are seeking foreign
workers who will agree to substandard wages and working conditions,
which he said undermines domestic workers and puts more Americans
on welfare.
   About 75 chanting, sign-carrying demonstrators marched outside a
hotel where more than 200 federal farm labor officials were holding
a national planning conference.
   Some of the conferees who oversee the H-2 program said every
effort will be made to protect domestic workers.
   ``For us to approve Oakley's petition, it has to be demonstrated
that they've exhausted their domestic supply of workers,'' said
Carol Gaudin, Atlanta regional administrator for the U.S.
Department of Labor's Employment Standards Administration.
   Gaudin said a decision will be made on Oakley's petition up to
12 days before the January picking date when workers are needed.
   ``Every effort is being made to hear the concerns of the
domestic workers,'' she said, adding that federal representatives
were to meet with the farm worker representatives.
   The application by Oakley is the first by a citrus or vegetable
grower in Florida under the federal program. H-2 workers from
Jamaica have been used the past few season for cutting sugar cane.
   An Oakley spokesman did not immediately return telephone calls
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
