<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-28 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed higher today as
investors remained focused on the direction of the economy and
interest rates.
   The market opened weak following Monday's rally then stalled
around midday after the Dow Jones industrial average pierced the
psychological resistance level of 2,700.
   The blue-chip indicator had not closed higher since the day
before the Oct. 13 stock plunge when it reached 2,759.84.
   The market regained its footing in mid-afternoon behind a
strengthening bond market, but wasn't able to sustain a strong
rally as volume faded.
   ``It was a sleepy, slow day, not the kind of market that gives
people inspiration,'' said John Burnett, senior vice president at
the investment firm Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   Analysts said recent actions by the Federal Reserve confused
investors and sent many scurrying to the sidelines to await fresh
signals as to its intentions.
   The Federal Reserve on Monday drained reserves from the banking
system in a move that surprised many observers. The Fed action
pushed up the federal funds rate, the interest commercial banks
charge each other for overnight loans.
   Last week, the Fed added funds to the system, which many
analysts took as a signal that the central bank was allowing
short-term interest rates to fall in an effort to cushion the
impact of a slowing economy.
   Analysts said that despite the confusion investors remained
generally optimistic that interest rates are in an overall
declining pattern.
   ``Over the next couple months the perception is that rates have
to come down so there's no reason to get excited about short-term
action by the Fed,'' said Dennis Jarrett, technical analyst with
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.
   Oil stocks led the blue-chips on the upside, while technology
stocks remained generally weak, equities traders said.
</TEXT>
