<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-28 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices tumbled Tuesday despite
an OPEC agreement to limit crude oil production.
   Energy market analysts said traders doubted that the 13 members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would abide by
their promises and keep oil output to 22 million barrels a day in
the first half of next year.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, slid 38 cents to close at $19.25 per
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Contracts for
delivery in February through April posted similar declines.
   The January crude contract ended with a 19-cent loss on Monday.
   Refined petroleum products traded on the New York Merc also
ended lower, in part due to the developments at OPEC's regular
winter conference. Heavy wholesale gasoline stocks in the Northeast
and technical selling also weighed down gas futures.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for December delivery dropped 1.36
cents to settle at 49.53 cents a gallon, adding to Monday's loss of
0.74 cent. Contracts for later delivery also finished sharply lower.
   No. 2 heating oil for December delivery shed 0.61 cent to 60.31
cents a gallon after falling 0.49 cent in the previous session. The
January through March contracts finished with larger declines.
   Andrew Lebow, a senior broker at E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc., said: ``I think that the market lost ground today on
skepticism regarding the recently concluded OPEC agreement.''
   OPEC's 13 ministers, meeting in Vienna, Austria, signed a
production-limiting deal intended to raise the price of their crude
oil to at least $18 a barrel and curb cheating on individual output
quotas in the first half of 1990.
   The ministers agreed to raise the cartel's self-imposed daily
production limit to 22 million barrels from the current 20.5
million barrels. OPEC also changed its ``target price'' of $18 a
barrel to a ``minimum reference price.''
   A basket of OPEC crudes monitored by the cartel stands at $17.74
a barrel.
   Apart from the possibility that OPEC members, Kuwait in
particular, might overproduce, Lebow said there is speculation the
cartel has been overly optimistic in its demand projections for
next year. This means that even if OPEC stays within its limits, it
would still have excess crude.
   Meanwhile, he said gasoline futures prices have been depressed
by industry statistics showing abundant supplies on the East Coast.
Weekly figures from the American Petroleum Institute, due to be
released after the market closed, were expected to confirm another
buildup in gas stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
