<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   11-28 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Finish Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed higher in cautious
trading Tuesday as the market remained focused on the economy and
interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.04 points to
2,702.01 behind a strong performance in the energy sector. The
blue-chip indicator had not closed higher since the day before the
Oct. 13 stock plunge, when it closed at 2,759.84.
   The market opened weak following Monday's rally, surged briefly,
then stalled around midday. It regained its footing in
mid-afternoon behind a strengthening bond market, but wasn't able
to sustain a strong rally as volume faded.
   ``It was a sleepy, slow day, not the kind of market that gives
people inspiration,'' said John Burnett, senior vice president at
the investment firm Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
   Analysts blamed the sluggishness on recent actions by the
Federal Reserve, which they said confused investors and sent many
to the sidelines to await fresh signals as to its intentions.
   The Federal Reserve on Monday drained reserves from the banking
system in a move that surprised many observers. The Fed action
pushed up the federal funds rate, the interest commercial banks
charge each other for overnight loans.
   Last week, the Fed added funds to the system, which many
analysts took as a signal that the central bank was allowing
short-term interest rates to fall in an effort to cushion the
impact of a slowing economy.
   ``There is not a broad-based interest in equities because of
concern and confusion over the status of the economy and when the
Fed is going to ease interest rates,'' said Edward P. Nicoski,
technical analyst with the investment firm Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood
Inc.
   Energy stocks led the blue chips upward in what analysts said
could be the start of a bullish period for oil companies as the
reindustrialization of Eastern Europe gets under way. Analysts also
cited an agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to limit output in the first half of 1990 as a possible
factor behind the strength in oil stocks.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
848 issues up, 647 down and 502 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 153.77 million
shares, up from 149.39 million in Monday's session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 183.19 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the overall market rose $3.633 billion, or
0.11 percent, in value from Monday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
advanced 0.21 to 191.34.
   Chevron, the most active NYSE stock, lost { to 67} after
Monday's announcement that the company had created an employee
stock ownership plan, a move some analysts said appeared aimed at
discouraging potential suitors. Chevron's stock had risen in recent
weeks on takeover speculation.
   Exxon, meanwhile, rose 1 to 47~, Texaco advanced ~ to 54} and
Unocal gained ] to 28\. General Electric also rose ] to 61} and
American Express increased | to 35].
   IBM declined { to 98~, Texas Utilities lost { to 34\ and
McDonald's slipped [ to 32~.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index gained 0.39 to 395.27, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index rose 0.16 to 345.77.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
0.49 to 456.66. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 375.10, up 1.06.
</TEXT>
