<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-28 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was generally lower Tuesday as
interest rate concerns continued to dominate the foreign exchange
markets.
   Gold prices were mixed as traders began to take profits in
response to the metal's recent gains.
   Analysts said the dollar moved higher in early trading following
signals on Monday that the Federal Reserve was not lowering
interest rates. When interest rates rise in the United States,
dollar-denominated securities and the U.S. currency itself become
more attractive to investors.
   The dollar has fallen in recent sessions amid expectations the
Fed would move interest rates lower. But Monday's developments
``caused a momentary hesitation in the market'' and traders began
buying dollars early in Tuesday's session to shore up their
positions, said Robert Ryan, senior foreign exchange trader with
the Bank of New York.
   But the dollar continued its slide in later trading because of
continuing expectations that interest rates would rise overseas,
particularly in West Germany, making foreign currencies more
valuable, said Jack Barbanel, president of First Global Asset
Management Inc.
   The West German mark has been strong against most currencies
since East Germany opened the Berlin Wall on Nov. 9, raising
expectations that West German industry would benefit from the new
opening to the East and that the Bundesbank would raise West German
interest rates.
   The mark suffered from some profit-taking Tuesday, but still
closed higher. In New York, the dollar fell to 1.7770 marks from
late Monday's 1.7890 after slipping earlier in Frankfurt to 1.7880
marks from 1.7900 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
quotes, included: 1.5880 Swiss francs, down from 1.6040; 6.0710
French francs, down from 6.1100; 1,312.75 Italian lire, down from
1,320.75; and 1.16645 Canadian dollars, down from 1.16665.
   The dollar also declined against the British pound. One pound
cost $1.5670 in New York, compared with $1.5585 late Monday, and in
earlier London trading, sterling rose to $1.5625 from $1.5605 late
Monday.
   The dollar rose slightly to 143.20 Japanese yen in New York from
late Monday's 143.195. In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing
143.65 Japanese yen from 143.35 yen, and in London, the dollar
traded at 143.69 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.5950 Swiss francs, down from 1.6050; 6.1035
French francs, down from 6.1125; 2.0270 Dutch guilders, up from
2.0203; 1,319.50 Italian lire, down from 1,321.25; and 1.1674
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1670.
   Gold prices were mixed in New York and lower overseas amid a
second straight day of profit-taking. Gold had risen steadily
during the past two months and broke through the $400 an ounce
level Nov. 21 for the first time since January, and traders had
been expected to take some profits.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, a troy ounce of gold fell
50 cents to close at $413.40, while the Republic National Bank of
New York quoted a late bid of $413.35, up 40 cents.
   Gold fell earlier in London to a late bid price of $411.25 a
troy ounce, down from $414.25. The late bid price in Zurich was
$410.50, down from $414.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $409.35 bid, down from $418.15.
   Silver rose 0.30 cent on the Commodity Exchange to close at
$5.693 a troy ounce. Earlier in London, silver fell to a late bid
of $5.64 a troy ounce, down from $5.73 late Monday.
</TEXT>
