<HEAD>Commuter Airline To Be Sold; Expansion of Service Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Precision Airlines, a regional airline
operating in the Northeast, said Tuesday it had agreed to be bought
by another small carrier.
   Northeast Express Airlines, of Bangor, Maine, was buying the
Manchester-based Precision for an undisclosed amount, said Fred
Martin, Precision's vice president for marketing. The sale was
expected to be completed on Friday, he said.
   Precision, which has 300 employees and 13 planes, flies from
Manchester to Boston, Newark, Philadelphia and New York's LaGuardia
Airport.
   ``Financially, there will be more new money coming in and this
will allow us to continue through the slow time of the year and
also fulfill our expansion plans,'' Martin said.
   Northeast Express is owned by Allen Caruso, former owner of Bar
Harbor Airways.
