<DOCNO> AP891128-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CFTC-DualTrading     11-28 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CFTC-Dual Trading,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators To Begin Working on Dual Trading Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal commodity futures regulators approved
plans Tuesday to begin a long process for developing rules to
restrict dual trading in a limited pilot project.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission approved the dual
trading curb project as an objective for fiscal year 1990.
   The CFTC's Division of Economic Analysis released a study
earlier this month that said dual trading does not enhance market
liquidity or present other benefits, as claimed by its supporters.
   Dual trading, in which floor traders can conduct transactions
for themselves as well as their customers, is legal but has come
under sharp criticism since more than 40 traders were indicted last
August on various fraud charges.
   Critics charge that dual trading was linked to many of the
alleged schemes uncovered at the Chicago Board of Trade and the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   The CFTC's Division of Trading and Markets is working on
proposed rule-making that would restrict dual trading on a
staggered, phased-in pilot basis by floor members in certain
markets, subject to certain exceptions.
   The CFTC did not specify what exchanges or what exceptions would
be included in the proposed rules.
   In the first quarter of fiscal year 1990, the division will
prepare proposed rules for consideration by the five-member CFTC.
   Following a 60-day comment period the division will begin
drafting final rules in the second quarter, with final approval of
the dual trading curbs coming in the third quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891128-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1922EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ColtFirearms-Sale     11-28 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colt Firearms-Sale,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colt Industries To Sell Firearms Division</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colt Industries Inc. said Tuesday it
would sell its beleaguered firearms division to a group of
investors in a deal that could end a nearly 4-year-old strike by
some union workers.
   Terms of the sale to CF Holding Corp., which includes a Colt
executive and two former United Technologies Corp. officials, were
not disclosed. Analysts had said they expected the sale to bring
between $150 million and $200 million.
   The deal at the 153-year-old company that makes the Colt .45
pistol ended 3{ months of negotiations as well as attempts by
striking union workers to buy the division.
   Michael Dunn, a spokesman for New York-based Colt Industries,
said company officials expected to complete the sale in January.
The new company will be called Colt's Manufacturing Co.
   The new owners said they did not know how many people will be
employed by the company, but they extended an offer of sorts to
striking United Auto Workers who walked off the job in January 1986.
   Anthony D. Autorino, one of the investors, said the new company
would contact current and striking Colt workers immediately and
begin hiring based on skill and seniority within three weeks.
   ``We think this will work out well for the people of Connecticut
and the workers as well,'' Autorino said in a statement.
   Colt currently employs about 950 workers at plants in Hartford
and West Hartford. Another 800 union workers are still on strike.
   Colt was founded in Hartford in 1836 by Samuel Colt, who
invented the revolver. The firearms division is a leading
manufacturer of handguns and rifles for military and commercial
uses.
   Products include the Colt .45 pistol, the King Cobra Magnum
revolver, AR-15 sport rifle and the M-16 military rifle. The
company also makes aerospace and automotive parts.
   Colt lost its contract to produce the M-16 for the Army in 1988.
The loss of that contract, coupled with the strike, apparently
figured in Colt's decision to sell that division, but company
officials deny it played a role.
   ``The buyout of Colt Firearms division by the CF Holding Corp.
offers us an opportunity to write a new chapter for Colt workers,
and I am hopeful that all the elements of this will come
together,'' Phillip Wheeler, executive director of the UAW's Region
9A, said in a statement.
   The investors include Autorino, former president of United
Technologies' Hamilton Standard division and now president of
Wethersfield-based Shared Technologies; Richard F. Gamble, another
former president of Hamilton Standard; and Ronald F. Stilwell, Colt
Firearm's vice president for military sales.
   Autorino declined to identify the remaining investors.
   When Colt announced in April it was seeking a buyer, the union
and managers of the firearms division combined forces with the
state and private investors to make a bid. State officials declined
to comment on Tuesday's announcement.
   About 1,050 union workers walked off the job Jan. 24, 1986,
after failing to reach agreement on a new contract during 10 months
of negotiations. Some workers have crossed picket lines and others
have found new jobs, leaving about 800 on strike. Replacement
workers have been hired to fill their positions.
   Autorino said the Colt plants are to close briefly in January to
allow for inventory and transition. He said the plants should be
operating at full capacity by March 1990.
   ``We have fairly extensive marketing and strategy plans which we
think can bring Colt back into its rightful place at the top of the
industry,'' Autorino said.
   In September, a judge found that Colt changed working conditions
unilaterally and refused to bargin in good faith with the striking
workers. The judge ordered Colt to rehire the strikers and pay lost
wages, estimated as high as $40 million.
   Autorino declined to discuss how the award figured into the
sale. Wheeler did not immediately return phone calls seeking
comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
