<FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 2347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Shearson     11-28 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shearson,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Shearson Considering Outside Investor for Cash Infusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. is considering
selling a large block of its shares to an outside investor to
provide a cash infusion for the troubled investment house, The New
York Times reported in its Wednesday editions.
   The identity of the investor was not known, the Times said.
   Under the proposal, American Express Co., which owns 62 percent
of Shearson, would sell a large percentage of its shares to the
investor, the Times said, citing unidentified sources. American
Express has said in the past that it wanted to cut its Shearson
holding to less than 50 percent.
   The sale of the shares would have to be approved by the
directors of both Shearson and American Express. Such a deal could
be hindered or blocked by opposition from Nippon Life Insurance
Co., the Japanese company that owns 13 percent of Shearson and
holds two seats on the company's board.
   On Oct. 30, Moody's Investors Service placed Shearson's debt and
commerical paper under review for a possible credit downgrading.
The credit rating concern cited the profitability problems among
Wall Street firms as well as Shearson's exposure to commercial real
estate through one of its subsidiaries.
   The Times said Peter A. Cohen, Shearson's chairman and chief
executive, declined to comment on any specific proposal that might
be under consideration to meet the concerns of Moody's.
   Shearson is expected to announce a sweeping change in its
management strucuture Wednesday, the Times said. The changes will
include new top managers for the firm's four divisions, the
elimination of the position of president and chief operating
officer, and the creation of a new executive planning committee,
the Times said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
